var tafsirData_2 = {
  1: {
    "Alif-Lãm-Mĩm.": "These are known as disjointed letters or mysterious letters that appear at the beginning of certain chapters in the Quran. Their exact meaning is known only to Allah. One wisdom behind them is to capture the attention of the listener and demonstrate that the Quran, though composed of the same Arabic letters known to all, is a miraculous speech that no human can replicate. The Arabs, masters of eloquence, were challenged by a Book made from their own alphabet yet beyond their ability to produce. This reminds us that divine knowledge surpasses human understanding, and some matters are best left to Allah's wisdom."
  },
  2: {
    "This is the Book!": "This refers to the Quran itself, the complete, perfect, and final revelation from Allah. Allah introduces it with honor and distinction, indicating its supreme status among all scriptures. When Allah calls it the Book, He establishes its authority as the ultimate source of guidance.",
    "There is no doubt about it": "The Quran is absolutely free from any error, contradiction, falsehood, or uncertainty. Unlike human writings that contain mistakes, this Book is protected and preserved by Allah Himself. A person may have doubts due to their own ignorance, but the Book itself is flawless and beyond suspicion.",
    "—a guide for those mindful of Allah,": "This Book serves as a complete guide for life, but its guidance benefits specifically those who have taqwa, a consciousness of Allah that makes them careful about obeying Him and avoiding His displeasure. Just as medicine only benefits one who takes it, the Quran's guidance reaches those whose hearts are open and receptive. The mindful are those who live with awareness that Allah sees them, so they try their best to do what pleases Him."
  },
  3: {
    "who believe in the unseen,": "True believers accept and have firm faith in everything that Allah and His Messenger have informed us about, even though we cannot perceive it with our senses. This includes belief in Allah, the angels, Paradise, Hellfire, the Day of Judgment, and all matters of the unseen realm. This is the foundation of faith, trusting Allah's word without demanding physical proof. For example, we believe in angels even though we cannot see them, because Allah told us they exist.",
    "establish prayer,": "They do not merely perform prayer, but they establish it, meaning they pray consistently, on time, with proper focus, humility, and adherence to all its conditions and pillars. Establishing prayer means making it a firm, unshakable part of one's life, not something done carelessly or occasionally. Prayer is the direct connection between the servant and Allah, and true believers prioritize it above all worldly matters.",
    "and donate from what We have provided for them,": "They spend from their wealth in the ways Allah has prescribed, giving obligatory charity (zakat), voluntary charity, and supporting family and those in need. The phrase what We have provided reminds us that everything we own is actually from Allah; we are merely trustees. True believers understand this and give generously, knowing that wealth is a test and that spending in Allah's cause purifies both the wealth and the soul."
  },
  4: {
    "and who believe in what has been revealed to you O Prophet": "They believe in the Quran that was revealed to Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), accepting it as the final and complete guidance from Allah. This includes believing in all its commandments, stories, promises, and warnings.",
    "and what was revealed before you,": "They also believe in the previous scriptures that Allah sent to earlier prophets, such as the Torah given to Moses, the Psalms to David, and the Gospel to Jesus. A Muslim's faith is incomplete without accepting all of Allah's messengers and their original messages, though we follow the Quran as the final, preserved revelation that supersedes previous scriptures.",
    "and have sure faith in the Hereafter.": "They have complete certainty, not mere hope or assumption, in the life after death, the Day of Resurrection, the accounting of deeds, Paradise, and Hellfire. This certainty shapes their entire worldview and actions. When someone truly believes that they will stand before Allah and answer for every deed, it transforms how they live each day."
  },
  5: {
    "It is they who are truly guided by their Lord,": "Those who possess the qualities mentioned above, belief in the unseen, establishing prayer, giving charity, believing in all revelations, and having certainty in the Hereafter, are the ones firmly established upon guidance from their Lord. Their guidance is not from their own intellect or desires, but from Allah Himself.",
    "and it is they who will be successful.": "These individuals are the truly successful ones, both in this world and the Hereafter. Success here means achieving what truly matters: Allah's pleasure, salvation from Hellfire, and eternal bliss in Paradise. The world may have different definitions of success such as wealth, fame, and power, but true success is measured by one's standing with Allah."
  },
  6: {
    "As for those who persist in disbelief,": "This refers to those who have chosen to reject faith and are determined to remain in that state. They have made a conscious decision to cover up the truth despite clear evidence. The Arabic word for disbeliever (kafir) literally means one who covers, they cover the truth that their own hearts recognize.",
    "it is the same whether you warn them or not—": "For such stubborn rejecters, the Prophet's warnings make no difference. This is not because the Prophet failed in his mission, but because they have closed their hearts to guidance. It is like shining a light for someone who refuses to open their eyes.",
    "they will never believe.": "Their persistence in rejection has led them to a state where they will not accept faith. This is a description of their chosen condition, not a predetermined fate. They had the opportunity to believe but repeatedly rejected it until their hearts became sealed. This verse comforts the Prophet (peace be upon him), letting him know that not everyone will believe, and that is not his failure."
  },
  7: {
    "Allah has sealed their hearts and their hearing,": "Because of their continuous rejection and arrogance, Allah has placed a seal upon their hearts and ears as a consequence of their own choices. This seal prevents guidance from entering. It is important to understand that Allah does not seal hearts arbitrarily; rather, this is a divine response to their persistent refusal to accept truth. When a person keeps rejecting guidance, eventually their heart becomes incapable of receiving it, like a lock that rusts shut from disuse.",
    "and their sight is covered.": "A covering has been placed over their eyes, so they cannot see the truth even when it is clear before them. They can see the physical world, but they are blind to spiritual realities and signs of Allah that are everywhere. This spiritual blindness is worse than physical blindness.",
    "They will suffer a tremendous punishment.": "In the Hereafter, they will face a severe and immense punishment in Hellfire. The punishment is described as tremendous to indicate its magnitude and severity, befitting their grave crime of rejecting their Creator despite all the signs and warnings."
  },
  8: {
    "And there are some who say, We believe in Allah and the Last Day,": "The hypocrites make verbal claims of faith, declaring belief in Allah and the Day of Judgment. Their tongues speak the words of believers, and outwardly they appear to be part of the Muslim community. In the Prophet's time in Madinah, there were people who saw the growing strength of Muslims and decided to pretend to be believers for worldly benefits and protection.",
    "yet they are not true believers.": "Despite their claims, they have no real faith in their hearts. Their declaration is merely lip service, empty words without sincerity. Allah, who knows what is hidden in hearts, exposes their reality. True faith requires the heart to believe what the tongue declares, and these people have a disconnect between the two."
  },
  9: {
    "They seek to deceive Allah and the believers,": "The hypocrites think they can trick Allah by hiding their disbelief, just as they fool the believers around them. They believe their act is clever and successful. By pretending to be Muslims, they hope to gain the benefits of both sides, safety among Muslims and loyalty with the disbelievers.",
    "yet they only deceive themselves,": "In reality, their deception harms no one but themselves. Allah is never fooled because He knows every secret of every heart. The believers may be temporarily deceived, but ultimately the hypocrites' scheme backfires on them. They think they are being smart, but they are actually destroying their own souls.",
    "but they fail to perceive it.": "They lack the awareness to realize that their deception is self-destructive. They are so caught up in their plotting that they cannot see the obvious truth: that they are earning Allah's anger and a painful punishment. Their arrogance blinds them to their own foolishness."
  },
  10: {
    "There is sickness in their hearts,": "Their hearts are diseased with doubt, hypocrisy, envy, hatred, and insincerity. Just as the body can become ill, the heart can become spiritually sick. This sickness prevents them from accepting truth and experiencing the sweetness of faith. Healthy hearts recognize truth and embrace it; sick hearts reject it and find comfort in falsehood.",
    "and Allah only lets their sickness increase.": "As a consequence of their choices and refusal to seek cure, Allah allows their disease to worsen. They had the opportunity to purify their hearts through sincere faith, but they chose hypocrisy instead. So their condition deteriorates further. This is divine justice, not oppression.",
    "They will suffer a painful punishment for their lies.": "Because of their persistent lying, claiming to believe while hiding disbelief, they will face a punishment that causes intense pain. The punishment matches the crime: they caused pain to the Muslim community through their deception, and they will taste pain in return."
  },
  11: {
    "When they are told, Do not spread corruption in the land,": "When the hypocrites are advised to stop their harmful activities, such as spreading discord among Muslims, secretly supporting enemies, weakening the community from within, and promoting disbelief, they are confronted with their wrongdoing.",
    "they reply, We are only peace-makers!": "Their response reveals their complete self-delusion. They claim to be doing good and bringing benefit, when in reality they are causing harm. This is a characteristic of hypocrites throughout history: they label their evil as good. They see themselves as intelligent mediators and wise politicians, when actually they are traitors and corruptors."
  },
  12: {
    "Indeed, it is they who are the corruptors,": "Allah firmly declares the truth: these people are the actual source of corruption, not reform. Their hypocrisy, lying, and secret plotting against Muslims is the real corruption in the land. Allah uses an emphatic structure to stress this reality.",
    "but they fail to perceive it.": "They are so deceived by their own egos and so accustomed to their ways that they genuinely cannot see themselves as wrongdoers. This is one of the greatest dangers of sin: when a person sins so much that they begin to see their sin as virtue. They have lost the ability to distinguish right from wrong."
  },
  13: {
    "And when they are told, Believe as others believe,": "When the hypocrites are invited to have sincere faith like the true believers, the companions of the Prophet who believed wholeheartedly, they are being offered the path to salvation.",
    "they reply, Will we believe as the fools believe?": "In their arrogance, they mock the sincere believers, considering them to be simple-minded, naive, and foolish. They see themselves as sophisticated and clever, while viewing true faith as something for the unsophisticated. This reveals their pride and how they value worldly intelligence over spiritual wisdom.",
    "Indeed, it is they who are fools,": "Allah turns their insult back on them: the hypocrites themselves are the truly foolish ones. True foolishness is not simplicity of heart but corruption of it. The greatest fool is one who sells their eternal happiness for temporary worldly gains.",
    "but they do not know.": "They are ignorant of their own foolishness. A wise person recognizes truth and follows it; a fool rejects truth while thinking himself wise. The hypocrites' self-image is completely inverted from reality."
  },
  14: {
    "When they meet the believers they say, We believe.": "In the presence of Muslims, the hypocrites wear a mask of faith. They verbally affirm belief and act like fellow believers to gain trust, protection, and worldly advantages that come with being part of the Muslim community.",
    "But when alone with their evil associates they say, We are definitely with you;": "However, when they are in private with their real allies, the leaders of disbelief and those who share their hatred of Islam, they reassure them of their true loyalty. They confirm that their hearts are with the disbelievers, not with the Muslims.",
    "we were only mocking.": "They dismiss their apparent faith as a joke, telling their allies that they were merely pretending and making fun of the believers. This reveals the depth of their insincerity and contempt for Islam and Muslims."
  },
  15: {
    "Allah will throw their mockery back at them,": "Allah responds to their mockery with what befits His majesty. He lets them continue in their delusion, thinking they are succeeding, when in fact they are heading toward destruction. Their temporary enjoyment in this world will be replaced by eternal humiliation. The mocker will become the mocked.",
    "leaving them to continue wandering blindly in their defiance.": "As part of this divine response, Allah extends their time in their rebellion, allowing them to go deeper into transgression. They stumble about in their disbelief, unable to find the straight path because they rejected it when it was offered. This is not Allah forcing them into evil, but allowing them to continue in the path they chose."
  },
  16: {
    "They are the ones who trade guidance for misguidance.": "The hypocrites made a conscious exchange: they had access to guidance through the Prophet and the Quran, but they gave it up in exchange for misguidance. Like foolish merchants, they traded something invaluable (guidance and eternal success) for something worthless (temporary worldly benefit and eternal loss).",
    "But this trade is profitless,": "Their transaction resulted in total loss, not gain. In any good business, one expects profit, but these people lost everything. They gained nothing of real value and lost the most precious thing: their souls and their Hereafter.",
    "and they are not rightly guided.": "The consequence of their terrible trade is that they remain without guidance. Having sold away their opportunity for salvation, they wander in darkness with no direction toward Allah's pleasure or Paradise."
  },
  17: {
    "Their example is that of someone who kindles a fire,": "Allah presents a vivid parable to illustrate the condition of hypocrites. They are like a person who lights a fire in the darkness. This represents their outward profession of Islam. When they entered Islam verbally, they appeared to have some light of faith.",
    "but when it lights up all around them,": "Initially, the fire provides light and benefit, just as the hypocrites benefited from being outwardly Muslim. They gained safety, social acceptance, and worldly advantages in the Muslim community.",
    "Allah takes away their light,": "Because of their insincerity and refusal to truly believe, Allah removes the blessing of guidance from them. The light they seemed to have was never really theirs; it was superficial, and now it is gone.",
    "leaving them in complete darkness—unable to see.": "They are left in layers of darkness, the darkness of disbelief, hypocrisy, and confusion, with no ability to find their way. They cannot see truth, cannot find guidance, and cannot escape their miserable condition. The fire they lit (their fake faith) provided no lasting benefit."
  },
  18: {
    "They are wilfully deaf, dumb, and blind,": "Though they have functioning ears, tongues, and eyes physically, they are spiritually deaf to truth, mute when it comes to speaking truth, and blind to the signs of Allah. They have made themselves this way by choosing to reject guidance. They hear the Quran but do not listen, could speak truth but choose lies, and see signs but refuse to reflect.",
    "so they will never return to the Right Path.": "Because of this self-imposed spiritual disability, they will not return to guidance. They have gone too far in their hypocrisy and cannot find their way back. The door of repentance is always open, but they have lost the desire and ability to walk through it."
  },
  19: {
    "Or those caught in a rainstorm from the sky with darkness, thunder, and lightning.": "Allah provides another parable: the hypocrites are like people caught in a terrifying storm at night. The rainstorm represents the Quran and Islam. It contains life-giving guidance like rain, but also warnings that terrify the hypocrites like thunder and lightning. The darkness represents the doubts and confusion in their hearts.",
    "They press their fingers into their ears at the sound of every thunder-clap for fear of death.": "When they hear the powerful warnings of the Quran about punishment and judgment, they react with fear and try to block it out, just as terrified people plug their ears against thunder. They fear death and what comes after, but instead of preparing for it through sincere faith, they try to ignore the warnings altogether.",
    "And Allah encompasses the disbelievers by His might.": "No matter how they try to escape or hide, Allah completely surrounds them with His power and knowledge. They cannot escape His grasp. Their attempts to avoid the message are futile because Allah is fully aware of them and in complete control of their fate."
  },
  20: {
    "It is as if the lightning were about to snatch away their sight.": "The brilliance of truth and the power of Quranic verses are so overwhelming that they almost overwhelm the hypocrites. The clarity of Islam's message is blinding to those who try to resist it while still being exposed to it.",
    "Whenever lightning strikes, they walk in its light,": "When things seem favorable to them, when Islam is victorious or they see some benefit, they walk along with the believers, taking advantage of the situation. In moments of clarity, they move forward with the Muslim community.",
    "but when darkness covers them, they stand still.": "But when trials come or the path becomes difficult, they stop and hesitate. When there is no worldly advantage visible, they freeze and cannot proceed. Their faith is conditional on circumstances, not rooted in genuine conviction.",
    "Had Allah willed, He could have taken away their hearing and sight.": "If Allah wished, He could punish them immediately by removing their physical senses, just as He has allowed their spiritual senses to be lost. But He gives them time, either as a test or an opportunity to repent.",
    "Surely Allah is Most Capable of everything.": "This is a reminder of Allah's absolute power. He is able to do all things: to punish instantly, to guide whom He wills, to take life or give it. Nothing is beyond His capability. This should cause the hypocrites to fear and the believers to trust completely in Allah."
  },
  21: {
    "O humanity!": "This is a universal call to all human beings, believers and disbelievers, past, present, and future generations. Allah addresses everyone because this message is relevant to every person ever created.",
    "Worship your Lord,": "The command is to worship Allah alone, to direct all acts of devotion, prayer, supplication, love, fear, and hope to Him exclusively. Worship is not merely ritual; it encompasses obedience in all aspects of life.",
    "Who created you and those before you,": "Allah establishes why He alone deserves worship: He is your Creator. He brought you into existence from nothing, and He created all generations before you. The One who gave you life has the right to tell you how to live it.",
    "so that you may become mindful of Him.": "The purpose of worship is to develop taqwa, consciousness of Allah that leads to avoiding sin and seeking His pleasure. Worship is not for Allah's benefit (He needs nothing) but for our own benefit, purifying our hearts and guiding our conduct."
  },
  22: {
    "He is the One Who has made the earth a place of settlement for you": "Allah made the earth stable and suitable for human life, not too hot, not too cold, with proper atmosphere and conditions. The earth serves as a comfortable bed or carpet, allowing you to live, build, and farm upon it. This is a sign of His care and planning.",
    "and the sky a canopy;": "The sky is like a protective ceiling over the earth, holding the atmosphere, blocking harmful radiation, and providing beauty. It is perfectly designed to sustain life below it.",
    "and sends down rain from the sky, causing fruits to grow as a provision for you.": "Allah sends rain from the clouds, which enables plants to grow and produce fruits, vegetables, and grains, all as provision and sustenance for humanity. This entire system of rain, soil, and growth is designed by Allah for your benefit.",
    "So do not knowingly set up equals to Allah in worship.": "After mentioning all these blessings and signs of Allah's sole creatorship, the command is clear: do not associate partners with Allah in worship. Since He alone creates and provides, He alone deserves worship. To worship others alongside Him while knowing this truth is the greatest injustice and ingratitude."
  },
  23: {
    "And if you are in doubt about what We have revealed to Our servant,": "Allah addresses those who question whether the Quran is truly from God. If anyone has doubt about the divine origin of this revelation sent to Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), who is described honorably as Allah's servant, then here is a fair challenge.",
    "then produce a surah like it": "Bring forth even a single chapter that matches the Quran in its eloquence, wisdom, consistency, prophecies, and impact. The shortest chapter of the Quran has only three verses, so the challenge is within reach if the Quran were truly man-made.",
    "and call your helpers other than Allah,": "Gather all your experts, poets, linguists, and anyone else you can find to help you in this task. Mobilize all resources available, human or otherwise, to meet this challenge.",
    "if what you say is true.": "If your claim that the Quran is not from Allah is true, then this should be easy. But if you cannot meet this challenge, it proves the Quran is from Allah. Fourteen centuries have passed, and no one has successfully met this challenge, confirming the Quran's miraculous nature."
  },
  24: {
    "But if you are unable to do so—": "If you cannot produce anything like the Quran despite your best efforts and all the help you can gather, then accept that you have failed the challenge.",
    "and you will never be able to do so—": "Allah makes a bold prophecy: not only have you failed, but you will never succeed. This is a declaration for all time. This prediction itself is a miracle. If the Quran were man-made, someone would have surely matched it by now to disprove this claim. But no one ever has.",
    "then fear the Fire fuelled with people and stones,": "Since the Quran is truly from Allah, believe in it and fear the Hellfire that awaits disbelievers. This Fire is so intense that its fuel is not just wood, but human beings and stones. Some scholars say these stones are the idols that were worshipped, and they will be fuel alongside their worshippers.",
    "which is prepared for the disbelievers.": "This terrifying punishment has already been prepared and is waiting for those who reject faith. It is not a threat that might happen; it is a reality that has been made ready for the disbelievers."
  },
  25: {
    "Give good news O Prophet to those who believe and do good": "The Prophet is commanded to convey glad tidings to the believers whose faith is accompanied by righteous deeds. Faith alone is not sufficient; it must be proven through action. This combination leads to the greatest reward.",
    "that they will have Gardens under which rivers flow.": "Paradise is described as gardens, lush, beautiful, and filled with blessings, beneath which rivers flow. These rivers provide constant beauty, freshness, and enjoyment. The imagery conveys peace, abundance, and eternal comfort.",
    "Whenever provided with fruit, they will say, This is what we were given before,": "The fruits of Paradise will look similar to what they experienced before, either in the worldly life or from previous provisions in Paradise. There is a sense of familiarity and comfort in what is served.",
    "for they will be served fruit that looks similar but tastes different.": "Though the fruits look alike, each one is unique in taste and pleasure. This ensures that there is no boredom in Paradise, constant variety in experience despite familiar appearances. Every fruit is a new delight.",
    "They will have pure spouses,": "The believers will have spouses who are purified from any physical, spiritual, or emotional impurity. There will be no illness, jealousy, anger, or any unpleasantness. These relationships are perfect and blissful.",
    "and they will be there forever.": "Unlike worldly pleasures that end, the blessings of Paradise are eternal. There is no fear of death, decline, or removal. The believers will enjoy these rewards without end, in perpetual happiness."
  },
  26: {
    "Surely Allah does not shy away from using the parable of a mosquito or what is even smaller.": "Allah is not embarrassed or hesitant to use any example in the Quran, no matter how humble, even a tiny mosquito or something smaller. Some disbelievers mocked the Quran for mentioning such insignificant creatures, but Allah clarifies that all examples serve a purpose. The small can teach us as much as the large; wisdom lies in the lesson, not the size of the example.",
    "As for the believers, they know that it is the truth from their Lord.": "True believers recognize the wisdom in every example Allah gives. They understand that whatever Allah says is truth, whether it involves mighty mountains or tiny insects. Their hearts are open to learning from any sign Allah provides.",
    "And as for the disbelievers, they argue, What does Allah mean by such a parable?": "The disbelievers, with their arrogant hearts, mock and question Allah's choice of examples. Instead of reflecting on the lesson, they ridicule the method. Their objection reveals their rejection of guidance rather than any intellectual concern.",
    "Through this test, He leaves many to stray, and guides many.": "These parables serve as a test: the humble-hearted benefit and are guided, while the arrogant reject and go further astray. The same verses guide some and misguide others, not because the verses are faulty, but because of the condition of the hearts receiving them.",
    "And He leaves none to stray except the rebellious—": "Those who are left astray are not random innocent people; they are the rebellious sinners who choose to reject truth. Allah's misguidance is a consequence of their rebellion, not an arbitrary punishment on the innocent."
  },
  27: {
    "those who violate Allah's covenant after it has been affirmed,": "The rebellious are identified by their breaking of commitments made to Allah. Every human being has a natural covenant with Allah to recognize Him as their Creator and worship Him alone. Breaking this covenant includes denying Allah, disobeying His commands, and refusing guidance after accepting it.",
    "break whatever ties Allah has ordered to be maintained,": "They sever the relationships and connections that Allah commanded to be upheld, such as family ties, kinship bonds, and the unity of the Muslim community. They bring division where Allah ordered unity, and they abandon obligations to relatives, neighbors, and fellow believers.",
    "and spread corruption in the land.": "Their actions cause corruption in society, including moral decay, injustice, oppression, and disorder. Instead of being sources of good, they become agents of harm.",
    "It is they who are the true losers.": "These people are the ultimate losers, though they may appear successful in worldly terms. They have lost the most valuable thing: their Hereafter and Allah's pleasure. This is the worst loss imaginable."
  },
  28: {
    "How can you deny Allah?": "This is a rhetorical question expressing astonishment at disbelief. Given all the evidence of Allah's power and mercy, how can anyone possibly deny Him? It is irrational and inexplicable.",
    "You were lifeless and He gave you life,": "Before you existed, you were nothing, not even a thought. Allah brought you into existence and gave you life. This alone should be sufficient proof of His power and your dependence on Him.",
    "then He will cause you to die": "After giving you life, He will take it away at the appointed time. Death comes to everyone, and no one can prevent it. This too is in Allah's hands.",
    "and again bring you to life,": "Then, on the Day of Resurrection, He will bring you back to life for judgment. The One who created you from nothing can easily recreate you. This is even easier for Him.",
    "and then to Him you will all be returned.": "Finally, everyone will return to Allah to be judged for their deeds. There is no escape from this meeting. Understanding this journey from non-existence, to life, to death, to resurrection, to judgment should make faith logical and disbelief absurd."
  },
  29: {
    "He is the One Who created everything in the earth for you.": "Allah created all that exists on earth for the benefit of humanity: the land, the seas, the animals, the plants, and all resources. Everything is designed to serve human needs and demonstrate Allah's generosity.",
    "Then He turned towards the heaven, forming it into seven heavens.": "After creating the earth and what is in it, Allah directed His will towards the sky and fashioned it into seven distinct heavens, each above the other. This demonstrates His systematic and purposeful creation.",
    "And He has perfect knowledge of all things.": "Allah knows everything: what was, what is, and what will be. Nothing is hidden from Him, whether it is in the heavens, the earth, or within the hearts of people. His knowledge is complete and perfect."
  },
  30: {
    "Remember when your Lord said to the angels, I am going to place a successive human authority on earth.": "Allah informed the angels of His plan to create humanity and place them on earth as His representatives, giving them authority and responsibility over the earth. This announcement shows the special status given to humans.",
    "They asked Allah, Will You place in it someone who will spread corruption there and shed blood": "The angels asked this question not out of objection but out of curiosity and seeking understanding. Perhaps they knew from previous creations (like the jinn) that beings with free will might cause corruption and violence. They wanted to understand Allah's wisdom.",
    "while we glorify Your praises and proclaim Your holiness?": "The angels mentioned their own worship as a way of expressing their dedication, not to boast or compare themselves to humans. They constantly glorify and sanctify Allah.",
    "Allah responded, I know what you do not know.": "Allah's answer indicates that there is wisdom in creating humanity that the angels could not perceive. Among humans would come prophets, righteous people, scholars, and those who worship Allah in ways that demonstrate the true beauty of faith. Allah knows the complete picture."
  },
  31: {
    "He taught Adam the names of all things,": "Allah gave Adam knowledge, specifically the names and nature of everything. This was unique knowledge that the angels did not possess. This teaching represented human capacity for learning, language, and intellect.",
    "then He presented them to the angels and said,": "Allah then displayed these things to the angels and asked them to identify them, demonstrating that Adam had been given something they did not have.",
    "Tell Me the names of these, if what you say is true?": "This was not to humiliate the angels but to show them the wisdom in creating Adam. If they thought they were more deserving of being on earth, let them demonstrate similar knowledge. This proved that Adam had a unique qualification."
  },
  32: {
    "They replied, Glory be to You!": "The angels immediately glorified Allah, acknowledging His perfection and their own limitations. This is the proper response when one realizes the limits of their knowledge.",
    "We have no knowledge except what You have taught us.": "They admitted they only know what Allah has given them. They did not possess inherent, independent knowledge. This humility is a model for us because all knowledge comes from Allah.",
    "You are truly the All-Knowing, All-Wise.": "The angels affirmed two of Allah's names: He is Al-Aleem (All-Knowing) and Al-Hakeem (All-Wise). His knowledge encompasses everything, and His decisions are always based on perfect wisdom."
  },
  33: {
    "Allah said, O Adam! Inform them of their names.": "Allah commanded Adam to demonstrate the knowledge he had been given by telling the angels the names of all things. This proved Adam's special capability.",
    "Then when Adam did, Allah said,": "After Adam successfully named everything, Allah addressed the angels with a reminder and lesson.",
    "Did I not tell you that I know the secrets of the heavens and the earth,": "Allah reminded them that He knows all that is hidden in the entire creation. Nothing escapes His knowledge, whether in the heavens or the earth.",
    "and I know what you reveal and what you conceal?": "Allah knows everything, both what beings express outwardly and what they hide within. Nothing is hidden from Him. This complete knowledge is why His decisions are always right, even when others might not initially understand."
  },
  34: {
    "And remember when We said to the angels, Prostrate before Adam,": "Allah commanded all the angels to prostrate to Adam. This was a prostration of respect and honor, not worship, because worship is for Allah alone. This act demonstrated Adam's elevated status among creation.",
    "so they all did—but not Iblis,": "All the angels obeyed Allah's command, but Iblis (Satan) refused. Iblis was among the angels due to his elevated status among the jinn, but he was originally a jinn, not an angel. His refusal stands in stark contrast to the angels' obedience.",
    "who refused and acted arrogantly,": "Iblis's refusal was rooted in pride. He considered himself superior to Adam because he was made from fire while Adam was made from clay. His arrogance prevented him from obeying Allah's direct command.",
    "becoming unfaithful.": "Through this act of disobedience driven by pride, Iblis became a disbeliever. His story teaches us that arrogance is one of the most dangerous sins because it can lead even someone close to Allah to reject Him. Pride was the first sin that led to disbelief."
  },
  35: {
    "We cautioned, O Adam! Live with your wife in Paradise": "Allah placed Adam and his wife, Hawwa (Eve), in Paradise, a place of comfort, beauty, and peace. They were honored guests in this blessed abode.",
    "and eat as freely as you please,": "They were given complete freedom to enjoy all the abundant blessings of Paradise, eating from any of its countless fruits and delights without restriction.",
    "but do not approach this tree,": "There was one limitation: they were forbidden from a specific tree. The nature of this tree is not specified, as the focus is on the test of obedience, not the identity of the tree. This single prohibition tested their willingness to obey Allah.",
    "or else you will be wrongdoers.": "If they disobeyed and ate from this tree, they would be wronging themselves by committing sin and facing its consequences. Allah clearly warned them of the outcome to give them every opportunity to succeed."
  },
  36: {
    "But Satan deceived them—leading to their fall from the blissful state they were in,": "Satan used tricks and false promises to mislead Adam and Eve, convincing them to eat from the forbidden tree. He swore false oaths and made the sin seem attractive, leading them to disobey Allah.",
    "and We said, Descend from the heavens to the earth as enemies to each other.": "As a consequence of their disobedience, Adam, Eve, and Satan were all commanded to leave Paradise and descend to earth. The enmity mentioned is primarily between humans and Satan, who is humanity's sworn enemy seeking to mislead them.",
    "You will find in the earth a residence and provision for your appointed stay.": "Earth became the temporary dwelling place for humanity. Here they would live, be tested, and eventually die after a fixed period determined by Allah. Though not Paradise, earth was made suitable for human life and sustenance."
  },
  37: {
    "Then Adam was inspired with words of prayer by his Lord,": "Allah, out of His mercy, taught Adam words of repentance. According to scholars, these words included: Our Lord, we have wronged ourselves. If You do not forgive us and have mercy on us, we will certainly be among the losers (Quran 7:23). Allah did not leave Adam without a way back.",
    "so He accepted his repentance.": "When Adam sincerely repented using these words, Allah forgave him. This shows that despite sin, the door of repentance is open. Adam's mistake did not permanently condemn him because his sincere return to Allah was accepted.",
    "Surely He is the Accepter of Repentance, Most Merciful.": "Allah is At-Tawwab (the One who accepts repentance again and again) and Ar-Raheem (the especially Merciful). No matter how many times someone falls into sin, if they sincerely repent, Allah accepts them. This gives hope to every sinner."
  },
  38: {
    "We said, Descend all of you!": "The command to descend to earth was repeated, confirming the transition of human life from Paradise to the worldly realm. This was the beginning of humanity's story on earth.",
    "Then when guidance comes to you from Me,": "Allah promised to send guidance throughout human history through prophets, scriptures, and signs. He would not leave humanity without direction.",
    "whoever follows it, there will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve.": "Those who accept and follow Allah's guidance will be protected from fear about the future and grief about the past. On the Day of Judgment and in the Hereafter, they will be secure and content. This is Allah's promise to the obedient."
  },
  39: {
    "But those who disbelieve and deny Our signs": "In contrast to the believers, those who reject faith and deny Allah's clear signs, whether in the Quran, in nature, or through the prophets, will face a different fate.",
    "will be the residents of the Fire.": "Their eternal dwelling will be Hellfire. They chose to reject guidance, so they will be placed in the destination of the rejectors.",
    "They will be there forever.": "Unlike worldly punishments that end, the Hellfire is eternal for the disbelievers. This severity matches the gravity of rejecting one's Creator after being given every opportunity to believe. This verse concludes the passage by establishing the ultimate stakes: eternal Paradise for the believers, eternal Hellfire for the disbelievers."
  },
  40: {
    "O children of Israel!": "Allah directly addresses the descendants of Prophet Yaqub (Jacob), peace be upon him, who was also known as Israel. This is a call to the Jewish community, reminding them of their special history with Allah and their ancestors who were prophets and righteous people. By addressing them this way, Allah reminds them of their noble lineage and the responsibilities that come with it.",
    "Remember My favours upon you.": "Allah commands them to recall and reflect upon the countless blessings He bestowed upon their ancestors and upon them. These favours include being rescued from Pharaoh's tyranny, receiving divine revelation through Moses, being provided with miraculous food and water in the desert, and being chosen as a nation to carry Allah's message. Remembering blessings leads to gratitude, and gratitude leads to more blessings and guidance. When we forget Allah's favours, we become ungrateful and arrogant.",
    "Fulfil your covenant and I will fulfil Mine,": "This refers to the agreement between Allah and the Children of Israel. Their part of the covenant was to worship Allah alone, follow His messengers including the final Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), and obey His commandments. In return, Allah promised them guidance, protection, and Paradise. This is like a contract—both parties have obligations. Allah always fulfils His promises, but humans often break theirs. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) said: \"The signs of a hypocrite are three: when he speaks, he lies; when he promises, he breaks it; and when he is entrusted, he betrays.\" (Bukhari & Muslim)",
    "and stand in awe of Me ˹alone˺.": "Allah commands them to fear Him alone and not to fear any human being, social pressure, or worldly loss when it comes to following the truth. This means giving Allah priority over everything else. Some of the Jewish scholars at the time of the Prophet knew he was the true messenger but feared losing their status and income if they accepted Islam. True fear of Allah means obeying Him even when it is difficult."
  },
  41: {
    "Believe in My revelations which confirm your Scriptures.": "Allah commands the People of the Book to believe in the Quran, which confirms the original message of the Torah and the Gospel. The Quran does not contradict the true teachings that came before; rather, it completes and perfects them. The coming of Prophet Muhammad was foretold in their scriptures, so accepting him should have been natural for them. This shows that all divine religions share the same core message: worship Allah alone and follow His guidance.",
    "Do not be the first to deny them": "This is a warning against being leaders in disbelief. The Jewish scholars in Madinah were among the first to encounter the Prophet's message, and their rejection influenced others. Being the first to reject truth carries a heavier burden because it sets a bad example and leads others astray. It is like someone who starts a harmful trend—they bear the sin of everyone who follows them in that wrongdoing.",
    "or trade them for a fleeting gain.": "Some scholars concealed or distorted the truth about the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) to maintain their positions, wealth, and influence among their people. They exchanged eternal guidance for temporary worldly benefits. This is a terrible trade because worldly gains are short-lived, while the Hereafter is eternal. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"Whoever learns knowledge by which Allah's pleasure is sought, but learns it only to gain worldly benefit, will not smell the fragrance of Paradise on the Day of Resurrection.\" (Abu Dawud)",
    "And be mindful of Me.": "Allah reminds them to be conscious of Him in all their actions and to fear the consequences of disobedience. Being mindful of Allah means remembering that He sees everything we do, hears everything we say, and knows everything we think. This awareness should prevent us from sinning and encourage us to do good."
  },
  42: {
    "Do not mix truth with falsehood": "This is a command against confusing people by blending true teachings with false ones. Some scholars would add their own interpretations or fabrications to divine teachings, making it difficult for ordinary people to distinguish between what Allah actually revealed and what humans invented. This is a serious crime because it corrupts guidance and leads people astray. For example, they might accept some descriptions of the Prophet while denying others, creating a distorted picture.",
    "or hide the truth knowingly.": "Even worse than mixing truth with falsehood is completely concealing the truth when you know it. Some Jewish scholars knew that Prophet Muhammad matched the description of the promised prophet in their scriptures, but they hid this information from their followers. Concealing knowledge that people need for their salvation is a grave sin. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"Whoever is asked about knowledge that he knows and conceals it, will be bridled with a bridle of fire on the Day of Resurrection.\" (Abu Dawud, Tirmidhi)"
  },
  43: {
    "Establish prayer,": "Allah commands them to perform prayer properly and consistently, not just occasionally or carelessly. Establishing prayer means praying at the correct times, fulfilling all the conditions and pillars, and praying with focus and humility. Prayer was obligatory in all divine religions, though the specific forms differed. This command also implies accepting the Islamic form of prayer, which includes the bowing and prostration that some had abandoned.",
    "pay alms-tax,": "Zakah is the obligatory charity that purifies wealth and helps those in need. It was also prescribed in previous religions. Paying zakah shows that we acknowledge Allah as the true owner of everything and that we care for our community. Refusing to pay it shows greed and a lack of faith. The command here invites them to practise this pillar as Muslims do.",
    "and bow down with those who bow down.": "This is an invitation to join the Muslim community in congregational prayer. Bowing (ruku) is a distinctive feature of Islamic prayer. By commanding them to bow with those who bow, Allah is telling them to become part of the Muslim ummah (community) and pray alongside the believers. Prayer in congregation has great rewards and builds brotherhood. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"Prayer in congregation is twenty-seven times better than prayer offered alone.\" (Bukhari & Muslim)"
  },
  44: {
    "Do you preach righteousness and fail to practice it yourselves,": "This is a powerful rhetorical question exposing the hypocrisy of those who tell others to do good while neglecting to do good themselves. Some Jewish scholars would advise people to follow the truth and even privately tell their relatives to follow Prophet Muhammad, yet they themselves would not accept Islam publicly. This is a universal lesson for everyone: we must practice what we preach. The Prophet (peace be upon him) described a person who teaches good but does not practice it as being like a candle that lights the way for others while burning itself out. On the Day of Judgment, such people will be thrown into the Fire, and their intestines will spill out as they walk in circles like a donkey turning a mill. (Bukhari & Muslim)",
    "although you read the Scripture?": "They had the Torah, which commanded them to follow truth and practise righteousness, yet they contradicted its teachings by their actions. Having knowledge makes the sin of not acting upon it even greater. A person who sins out of ignorance is different from one who sins while knowing better. Reading scripture should lead to transformation, not just information.",
    "Do you not understand?": "This question highlights the foolishness of their behaviour. How can intelligent people who read divine guidance act against it? Understanding should lead to action. If knowledge does not change our behaviour, then we have not truly understood. This is a wake-up call for all who have knowledge but do not act upon it."
  },
  45: {
    "And seek help through patience and prayer.": "When facing difficulties, whether in leaving sin, accepting truth, or enduring hardship, Allah prescribes two powerful tools: patience and prayer. Patience means persevering through difficulties without complaining, controlling oneself from sin, and continuing to obey Allah even when it is hard. Prayer connects us directly to Allah and provides strength, comfort, and guidance. The Prophet (peace be upon him) would turn to prayer whenever something distressed him. (Abu Dawud) These two together—patience and prayer—are the believer's greatest weapons against life's challenges.",
    "Indeed, it is a burden except for the humble—": "Allah acknowledges that maintaining patience and consistent prayer is difficult for most people. It feels heavy because it requires discipline, sacrifice of time and desires, and continuous effort. However, for those who have humility before Allah—those who recognize their weakness and Allah's greatness—it becomes easier and even enjoyable. Humility comes from knowing that we need Allah and that this life is temporary compared to the eternal Hereafter."
  },
  46: {
    "those who are certain that they will meet their Lord": "The humble ones are those who have firm belief that they will stand before Allah one day. This certainty transforms how they live. When you truly believe you will meet Allah and be accountable for every action, prayer becomes a joy rather than a burden, and patience becomes easier because you know the reward is coming. The word used here implies strong expectation, almost certainty. This meeting is not something they doubt but something they prepare for daily.",
    "and to Him they will return.": "Everything in this life is temporary; our true destination is back to Allah. This reminder puts worldly troubles in perspective. Whether we face loss, hardship, or temptation, knowing that we will return to Allah helps us endure. It also reminds us that there is no escape from accountability—everyone will return to their Creator to receive the results of their choices."
  },
  47: {
    "O Children of Israel! Remember ˹all˺ the favours I granted you": "Again Allah calls upon the descendants of Yaqub to remember His blessings. This repetition emphasizes the importance of gratitude and serves as an introduction to a detailed list of favours that will follow. Remembering blessings should lead to thankfulness, and thankfulness should lead to obedience. The more we recognize what Allah has given us, the more motivated we become to worship Him properly.",
    "and how I honoured you above the others.": "At a particular time in history, Allah chose the Children of Israel to receive prophethood, scripture, and special blessings above other nations of that era. They had an unbroken chain of prophets, were given the Torah, and witnessed incredible miracles. However, this honour came with responsibility. When they failed to uphold their covenant and rejected prophets—ultimately including Prophet Muhammad—this special status was no longer exclusive to them. This teaches us that honour with Allah is based on faith and righteous deeds, not lineage. As Allah says elsewhere: \"Indeed, the most noble of you in the sight of Allah is the most righteous of you.\" (Quran 49:13)"
  },
  48: {
    "Guard yourselves against the Day": "Allah commands them to protect themselves by preparing for the Day of Judgment through faith and good deeds. This day is certain, and preparation for it should be every person's priority. Fearing that Day means living in a way that will bring success when we stand before Allah.",
    "on which no soul will be of help to another.": "On the Day of Judgment, no person will be able to bear the burden of another or help them escape punishment. Even the closest relationships—parent and child, husband and wife, best friends—will be of no benefit. Each person will be concerned only with themselves. As Allah says: \"On that Day, a man will flee from his brother, his mother and his father, his wife and his children. For every person, on that Day, will have enough concern of his own.\" (Quran 80:34-37)",
    "No intercession will be accepted,": "Unlike in this world where connections and recommendations can help, on that Day no one can intercede for another except with Allah's permission. The false belief that simply being from a certain lineage or following certain scholars will guarantee salvation is rejected here. Intercession will only be granted to those whom Allah allows, and only for those with whom He is pleased. No unauthorized intercession will benefit anyone.",
    "no ransom taken,": "No amount of wealth or offering will be able to buy one's way out of punishment. If a person could offer the entire earth full of gold to ransom themselves, it would not be accepted. The currency of that Day is faith and good deeds, not material wealth. This destroys any notion that one can pay their way into Paradise or escape Hell through money.",
    "and no help will be given.": "There will be no external rescue or assistance for those who deserve punishment. No allies, protectors, or supporters will be able to save them from Allah's judgment. This comprehensive description removes every false hope that people might have about escaping accountability."
  },
  49: {
    "˹Remember˺ how We delivered you from the people of Pharaoh,": "Allah reminds the Israelites of the tremendous favour of rescuing their ancestors from the oppression of Pharaoh and his regime in Egypt. The Pharaoh of that time was one of the most tyrannical rulers in history, claiming divinity and enslaving the Israelites for generations. Allah's deliverance of them through Prophet Musa (Moses) was a miraculous act of mercy that they should never forget.",
    "who afflicted you with dreadful torment,": "The Egyptians under Pharaoh subjected the Israelites to severe persecution and humiliation. They were treated as slaves, forced into hard labour, and denied basic human dignity. The torment was continuous and degrading, designed to break their spirit and keep them subjugated.",
    "slaughtering your sons and keeping your women.": "Pharaoh ordered the killing of newborn Israelite boys because of a prophecy that a child from them would bring about his downfall. The girls were kept alive to serve as servants. This was genocide aimed at destroying the Israelite nation. Imagine the terror of mothers giving birth, not knowing if their child would be taken and killed. Yet even in these circumstances, Allah preserved baby Musa and raised him in Pharaoh's own palace—showing that Allah's plan cannot be stopped by human tyrants.",
    "That was a severe test from your Lord.": "This immense suffering was a trial from Allah. Tests come in different forms—sometimes through hardship and sometimes through ease. The Israelites' test through oppression was meant to strengthen their faith, make them turn to Allah, and prepare them for the blessings to come. After enduring such difficulty, they should have been deeply grateful when Allah rescued them and should have remained obedient to Him."
  },
  50: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when We parted the sea,": "This refers to the miraculous splitting of the Red Sea when Musa struck it with his staff by Allah's command. The water divided, creating dry pathways with walls of water on either side, allowing the Israelites to cross. This is one of the greatest miracles ever witnessed, demonstrating Allah's absolute power over nature. What seems impossible to humans is effortless for Allah.",
    "rescued you,": "The entire Israelite nation—men, women, children, and elderly—crossed safely to the other side. After generations of slavery and oppression, they were finally free. This rescue was entirely from Allah; no human power could have achieved it. Their deliverance should have created eternal gratitude in their hearts.",
    "and drowned Pharaoh's people before your very eyes.": "When Pharaoh and his army pursued the Israelites into the parted sea, Allah commanded the waters to return. The entire Egyptian army, including Pharaoh himself, was drowned while the Israelites watched from safety. This served multiple purposes: it completely eliminated the threat to the Israelites, demonstrated Allah's justice against oppressors, and provided a visual confirmation of Allah's power. Pharaoh, who had claimed to be god, was shown to be utterly helpless before the true God. Allah preserved Pharaoh's body as a sign for future generations, as mentioned in another verse: \"Today We will preserve your body so that you may become a sign for those after you.\" (Quran 10:92)"
  },
  51: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when We appointed forty nights for Moses,": "Allah called Musa to Mount Sinai for forty nights to receive the Torah and divine guidance. This was an immense honour for Musa and a crucial moment for the Israelites, as they were about to receive their scripture. During this period, the Israelites were left with Musa's brother Harun (Aaron), who was also a prophet.",
    "then you worshipped the calf in his absence,": "While Musa was away receiving revelation, a man named Samiri collected gold jewelry from the people and fashioned it into a golden calf that made a sound. He told the people this was their god and the god of Musa who had forgotten his lord. Shockingly, many Israelites began worshipping this idol. This happened shortly after they had witnessed Allah's miracles—the plagues in Egypt, the parting of the sea, the drowning of Pharaoh. How quickly they forgot and fell into the worst sin: associating partners with Allah.",
    "acting wrongfully.": "Their calf-worship was a tremendous wrong against themselves and against Allah. Despite seeing clear signs of Allah's oneness and power, they turned to worship a statue made from their own jewelry. This shows how dangerous it is to be away from prophetic guidance and how quickly people can go astray when they follow their desires. It also shows that witnessing miracles alone does not guarantee faith—the heart must be receptive and committed."
  },
  52: {
    "Even then We ˹still˺ forgave you": "Despite committing the gravest sin of polytheism, Allah still pardoned them when they repented. This demonstrates Allah's immense mercy and willingness to forgive. No sin is too great for Allah's forgiveness if the person sincerely repents. This should give hope to all sinners while also highlighting how merciful Allah was to the Israelites specifically—a mercy they should have appreciated more.",
    "so perhaps you would be grateful.": "The purpose of this forgiveness was to inspire gratitude in their hearts. When someone forgives us for a serious offense, we naturally feel indebted and grateful. Allah forgave them so they would recognize His mercy and respond with thankfulness and obedience. Unfortunately, as the coming verses will show, many of them failed to maintain this gratitude and continued in disobedience."
  },
  53: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when We gave Moses the Scripture—": "Allah blessed Musa with the Torah, a divine book containing guidance, laws, and wisdom for the Israelites. This was a tremendous favour—having direct revelation from Allah to guide them in every aspect of life. The scripture was meant to be their guide, their constitution, and their source of knowledge about Allah.",
    "the standard ˹to distinguish between right and wrong˺": "The Torah served as a furqan—a criterion to distinguish between truth and falsehood, lawful and unlawful, good and evil. Without divine guidance, humans often confuse right with wrong based on their desires or cultural influences. The scripture provided clear standards by which to judge all matters. This is one of the greatest blessings: knowing with certainty what pleases Allah and what displeases Him.",
    "that perhaps you would be ˹rightly˺ guided.": "The purpose of giving them the scripture was guidance—to show them the straight path leading to Allah's pleasure and Paradise. Allah did not leave them without direction; He gave them a complete guide. Whether they would follow it or not was their choice, but the means for guidance was provided. This shows Allah's care for humanity—He does not leave us to figure things out alone but sends revelation to guide us."
  },
  54: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when Moses said to his people, \"O my people! Surely you have wronged yourselves by worshipping the calf,": "When Musa returned from the mountain and found his people worshipping the golden calf, he was furious and deeply saddened. He confronted them, making clear that their idol worship was primarily a wrong against themselves. Sin harms the sinner most of all. They had damaged their relationship with Allah, tarnished their souls, and put themselves in danger of divine punishment.",
    "so turn in repentance to your Creator": "Musa called them to sincere repentance—to return to Allah, regret their actions, and seek forgiveness. Repentance (tawbah) literally means to turn back. They had turned away from Allah toward an idol; now they needed to turn back to Him. The use of \"Creator\" here reminds them that Allah made them, owns them, and has full authority over them—how could they worship something else?",
    "and execute ˹the calf-worshippers among˺ yourselves.": "The repentance required of them was severe: those who had remained faithful were commanded to execute those who had committed the idol worship. This was an extreme measure because the crime was extreme—associating partners with Allah after witnessing such clear signs. This ruling was specific to that nation at that time; it showed the seriousness of shirk (polytheism) and served as a means of purification for the community. Some scholars explain this was carried out, while others say it was a test of their willingness to obey, and Allah pardoned them before full execution.",
    "That is best for you in the sight of your Creator.\"": "Though the punishment seemed harsh, Musa explained it was better for them than carrying the sin into the Hereafter. Facing consequences in this world—even severe ones—is better than facing Allah's punishment in the next world, which would be far worse and eternal. This teaches us that sometimes what seems difficult is actually a mercy.",
    "Then He accepted your repentance.": "Allah, in His infinite mercy, accepted their repentance. Despite the enormity of their sin, His forgiveness was greater. This is one of the most hopeful messages in the Quran: Allah's mercy encompasses all things, and no sin is beyond His forgiveness for those who sincerely repent.",
    "Surely He is the Accepter of Repentance, Most Merciful.": "Allah is At-Tawwab—the One who constantly accepts repentance, who loves when His servants return to Him, and who facilitates their repentance. He is also Ar-Raheem—full of mercy for His servants. These two attributes together assure us that no matter how far we stray, the door of repentance is always open, and Allah is waiting to forgive."
  },
  55: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when you said, \"O Moses! We will never believe you until we see Allah with our own eyes,\"": "A group of seventy elders from the Israelites accompanied Musa to a meeting with Allah. Instead of being grateful for this honour, they made an audacious demand: they would not believe unless they could see Allah directly. This was extreme arrogance and showed a lack of understanding of Allah's majesty. Allah cannot be seen in this worldly life—not because of any deficiency in Him, but because human beings in their current state cannot bear it. Even Musa, when he requested to see Allah, was told: \"You cannot see Me.\" (Quran 7:143) Their demand was inappropriate and showed they wanted faith on their own terms rather than submitting to Allah's wisdom.",
    "so a thunderbolt struck you while you were looking on.": "As a consequence of their audacious demand, Allah sent a thunderbolt that struck them dead. They witnessed their own destruction—\"while you were looking on\"—meaning they saw it coming but could do nothing to stop it. This was a direct punishment for their arrogance and a demonstration of Allah's power. It served as a lesson that humans cannot dictate terms to Allah or demand things beyond what He has decreed."
  },
  56: {
    "Then We brought you back to life after your death,": "In an extraordinary act of mercy, Allah resurrected these seventy people after they had died. This was a miracle—bringing the dead back to life in this world, not on the Day of Judgment. Very few people in history have experienced death and then been returned to life. Allah gave them a second chance, an opportunity to correct their ways and be grateful.",
    "so that perhaps you would be grateful.": "The purpose of this resurrection was to inspire gratitude. Having experienced death—the ultimate consequence—and then being given life again, they should have been overwhelmed with thankfulness and completely devoted to Allah. This favour is mentioned to show how generous Allah was to the Israelites and how much He wanted them to succeed. Unfortunately, many continued in their ingratitude despite such extraordinary blessings."
  },
  57: {
    "And ˹remember when˺ We shaded you with clouds": "While the Israelites wandered in the desert after leaving Egypt, Allah provided them with clouds that shaded them from the scorching sun. Deserts are extremely hot during the day, and without shelter, survival would be very difficult. This miraculous shade was a special mercy, like a moving canopy that followed them wherever they went. No other nation received such a blessing.",
    "and sent down to you manna and quails,": "Allah provided them with miraculous food that required no farming, hunting, or cooking. Manna was a sweet, honey-like substance that appeared on trees and rocks every morning—ready to eat. Quails were birds that came to them in abundance, providing protein. They had a complete, nutritious diet delivered by Allah Himself, with no effort required on their part. This was like having catered meals in the middle of a barren desert.",
    "˹saying˺, \"Eat from the good things We have provided for you.\"": "Allah invited them to enjoy these pure, wholesome provisions. The food was not just sufficient but good—pleasant, nutritious, and blessed. This command to eat is also a reminder that the provisions came from Allah, not from their own efforts. They should eat with gratitude, recognizing the Giver behind the gifts.",
    "The evildoers ˹certainly˺ did not wrong Us, but wronged themselves.": "When some among them were ungrateful or complained about the food, they did not harm Allah in any way. Allah is completely self-sufficient and is not affected by human ingratitude. Rather, they harmed themselves by rejecting blessings and earning Allah's displeasure. This is a profound principle: our sins do not diminish Allah's kingdom at all, but they diminish us. Our obedience benefits us, and our disobedience harms us."
  },
  58: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when We said, \"Enter this city": "Allah commanded the Israelites to enter a city—often identified as Jerusalem or Jericho—which was blessed and would provide them with settlement after their years of wandering. This was another great favour: being given a land to call home.",
    "and eat freely from wherever you please;": "Once inside, they would have complete freedom to enjoy the city's provisions abundantly. No restrictions on where they could eat or how much—a life of ease and plenty awaited them. This generous offer showed Allah's kindness and desire to provide for them.",
    "enter the gate with humility,": "They were commanded to enter the city's gate while bowing or prostrating, showing humility and gratitude to Allah. This physical posture was meant to reflect inner submission. It was a simple requirement: enter humbly, acknowledging that this blessing came from Allah, not from their own power.",
    "saying, 'Absolve us.'": "Along with the humble posture, they were to say \"hittah,\" meaning \"relieve us of our sins\" or \"forgive us.\" This simple prayer of repentance, combined with their humble entry, would earn them forgiveness. Allah made the path to forgiveness easy for them—just enter humbly and ask for forgiveness.",
    "We will forgive your sins": "Allah promised that if they obeyed this simple command, He would forgive all their past sins. What a generous offer! All their previous mistakes could be wiped clean through this act of obedience and humility.",
    "and multiply the reward for the good-doers.\"": "Not only would they be forgiven, but those who excelled in goodness would receive additional rewards. Allah's generosity knows no bounds—He does not just forgive but increases blessings for those who strive to please Him."
  },
  59: {
    "But the wrongdoers changed the words they were commanded to say.": "Instead of saying \"hittah\" (forgive us) with humility, the wrongdoers among them mockingly changed the word to something else—some reports say they said \"hintah\" (wheat/grain), making a joke of it. They also changed their physical posture, entering arrogantly instead of humbly, some reportedly crawling on their backsides in mockery. This was deliberate disobedience and disrespect for Allah's command. Even when given an easy path to forgiveness, they chose rebellion.",
    "So We sent down a punishment from the heavens upon them": "As a consequence of their mockery and disobedience, Allah sent a punishment upon the wrongdoers. This could have been a plague, disease, or another calamity from the sky. They had rejected mercy, so they received punishment instead.",
    "for their rebelliousness.": "The punishment was a direct result of their fisq—their rebellion and breaking away from obedience. They were not punished arbitrarily but because of their own choices. This serves as a warning to all: mocking Allah's commands and deliberately disobeying when guidance is clear brings consequences."
  },
  60: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when Moses prayed for water for his people, We said, \"Strike the rock with your staff.\"": "In the desert, water is the most precious resource. When the Israelites needed water, Musa prayed to Allah, and Allah commanded him to strike a rock with his staff. The staff was the same one used to part the sea—an instrument of miracles by Allah's permission. This shows that prophets turn to Allah in times of need, and Allah responds to their prayers.",
    "Then twelve springs gushed out,": "From a single rock, twelve separate springs burst forth—enough water for the entire nation. The number twelve corresponded to the twelve tribes of Israel, descendants of the twelve sons of Prophet Yaqub. Each tribe had its own spring, eliminating any conflict over water resources. This was a perfect, organized miracle.",
    "˹and˺ each tribe knew its drinking place.": "Allah arranged matters so that every tribe had its designated water source. There was no confusion, no fighting, no competition for resources. This organization showed Allah's care for details and His ability to provide abundantly for everyone. It also taught them to be orderly and grateful.",
    "˹We then said,˺ \"Eat and drink of Allah's provisions,": "With miraculous food from the sky and miraculous water from the rock, they were commanded to enjoy these blessings while acknowledging they came from Allah. Every meal should remind us of the Provider. Saying \"Bismillah\" (in the name of Allah) before eating and \"Alhamdulillah\" (praise be to Allah) after eating fulfils this reminder.",
    "and do not go about spreading corruption in the land.\"": "Along with the blessings came a warning: do not cause corruption through ingratitude, sin, or injustice. When people are well-provided-for, they sometimes become arrogant and spread mischief. Allah warned them to use His blessings responsibly and remain obedient. This principle applies to all of us: blessings come with responsibility."
  },
  61: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when you said, \"O Moses! We cannot endure the same meal ˹every day˺.": "Despite receiving miraculous food from heaven, some Israelites complained about having the same diet daily. The manna and quails, though blessed and nutritious, did not satisfy their desires for variety. Instead of being grateful for divine provision, they grumbled. This shows how human desires are often insatiable—even miracles become ordinary when we lack gratitude.",
    "So ˹just˺ call upon your Lord on our behalf, He will bring forth for us some of what the earth produces of herbs, cucumbers, garlic, lentils, and onions.\"": "They demanded ordinary vegetables instead of heavenly food. They wanted herbs, cucumbers, garlic, lentils, and onions—common foods that required farming and effort, foods associated with their life of servitude in Egypt. They essentially preferred what slaves ate over what Allah specially provided for them.",
    "Moses scolded ˹them˺, \"Do you exchange what is better for what is worse?": "Musa was astonished at their request. They were trading superior, miraculous provision for inferior, ordinary food. This is like someone offered a gourmet meal refusing it and asking for scraps instead. Their request showed ingratitude and misplaced priorities.",
    "˹You can˺ go down to any village and you will find what you have asked for.\"": "Musa told them that such ordinary foods were available in any town. They did not need divine intervention for onions and garlic—these were common items. Their complaint was both ungrateful and foolish.",
    "They were stricken with disgrace and misery,": "As a consequence of their repeated disobedience and ingratitude, they were afflicted with lasting humiliation and poverty. This was not random misfortune but a direct result of their choices. Throughout history, when the Israelites disobeyed Allah, they faced consequences.",
    "and they invited the displeasure of Allah": "They earned Allah's anger upon themselves. His wrath was not arbitrary but was in response to their actions. When people persistently reject guidance and kill prophets, they bring divine anger upon themselves.",
    "for rejecting Allah's signs": "They denied and disbelieved in Allah's clear miracles and revelations, even though they witnessed them firsthand. This denial was not from ignorance but from arrogance and stubbornness.",
    "and unjustly killing the prophets.": "Throughout their history, some among the Israelites killed multiple prophets who came to guide them. This is one of the most serious crimes possible—murdering those sent by Allah with His message. Prophets like Zakariyya (Zechariah) and Yahya (John) were killed by their own people.",
    "This is ˹a fair reward˺ for their disobedience and violations.": "The disgrace and misery were just consequences of their disobedience and transgression against Allah's limits. When people consistently break divine laws and harm divine messengers, they face punishment. This is not injustice but divine justice."
  },
  62: {
    "Indeed, the believers, Jews, Christians, and Sabians—": "This verse addresses people from different religious backgrounds: Muslims (believers), Jews (those who followed Moses), Christians (followers of Jesus), and Sabians (an ancient monotheistic group). Allah acknowledges that different communities existed before Islam and addresses their ultimate fate.",
    "whoever ˹truly˺ believes in Allah and the Last Day and does good": "The criteria for success are clearly stated: genuine faith in Allah alone (not associating partners with Him), belief in the Day of Judgment (accountability for one's actions), and righteous deeds. These three elements are inseparable—true faith must produce good actions, and good actions must stem from proper belief. This was the standard for every nation in their respective time, following their prophet.",
    "will have their reward with their Lord.": "Those who meet these criteria will receive their reward from Allah. This means that followers of Moses who truly believed and obeyed before Jesus came will be rewarded. Followers of Jesus who truly believed and obeyed before Muhammad came will be rewarded. And now, after the coming of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), true belief requires accepting him as the final messenger. The verse emphasizes that Allah judges people fairly based on sincere faith and good deeds, not just labels.",
    "And there will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve.": "The believers will have no fear about what lies ahead and no sadness about what they left behind. In the Hereafter, they will be secure, free from anxiety about the future and regret about the past. This is the ultimate peace that every soul seeks. This promise applies to all who sincerely followed the truth available to them in their time."
  },
  63: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when We took a covenant from you": "Allah recalls the solemn agreement He made with the Israelites at Mount Sinai. A covenant is a binding contract with serious obligations. The Israelites pledged to follow the Torah, obey Allah's commands, and remain faithful to His guidance.",
    "and raised the mountain above you": "To emphasize the seriousness of this covenant, Allah miraculously lifted Mount Sinai and held it above their heads. Imagine looking up and seeing a massive mountain suspended over you! This extraordinary sign demonstrated Allah's power and the gravity of the commitment they were making. It was both a miracle and a warning.",
    "˹saying˺, \"Hold firmly to that ˹Scripture˺ which We have given you": "Allah commanded them to grasp the Torah with strength and determination, not treating it lightly. \"Hold firmly\" means to study it seriously, believe in it completely, and practice it diligently. Scripture should not be taken casually—it deserves our full attention and commitment.",
    "and observe its teachings": "They were told to remember and reflect on what the Torah contained—its laws, guidance, stories, and wisdom. Remembering includes memorizing, studying, teaching, and constantly bringing its lessons to mind. Knowledge forgotten is knowledge wasted.",
    "so perhaps you will become mindful ˹of Allah˺.\"": "The purpose of firmly holding the scripture and remembering its teachings is to develop taqwa—consciousness of Allah that leads to obeying Him and avoiding sin. This is the ultimate goal of all revelation: to produce God-conscious individuals who live righteously."
  },
  64: {
    "Yet you turned away afterwards.": "Despite the powerful covenant made under extraordinary circumstances, the Israelites eventually broke their promises and turned away from their obligations. After all the miracles, all the warnings, and all the blessings, they still chose disobedience. This shows how persistent human weakness can be and how quickly people can forget their commitments to Allah.",
    "Had it not been for Allah's grace and mercy upon you,": "Despite their violations, Allah did not destroy them. He continued to give them chances, send them prophets, and offer paths to repentance. His grace and mercy prevented their complete destruction.",
    "you would have certainly been of the losers.": "Without Allah's mercy, they would have been utterly ruined in this world and the next. This statement reminds them (and us) that we survive and thrive only because of Allah's continuous mercy, not because of our own righteousness. None of us can claim we deserve Allah's blessings—they are all from His grace."
  },
  65: {
    "You are already aware of those of you who broke the Sabbath.": "The Jewish community knew well the story of a group who violated the Sabbath—the day when they were forbidden to work or conduct business. This violation happened in a coastal town where the people were fishermen. Allah tested them by making fish abundant and visible on Saturdays but scarce on other days. Some people could not resist the temptation and devised tricks to catch fish on the Sabbath, technically violating the law while pretending to obey it.",
    "We said to them, \"Be disgraced apes!\"": "As punishment for their deliberate disobedience and deceptive tactics, Allah transformed them into apes. This was not just a metaphor but an actual physical transformation—they became apes, losing their human dignity. They lived as apes for a few days and then died, leaving no descendants. This punishment fit the crime: they behaved like animals in following their base desires, so they became animals. The word \"disgraced\" emphasizes that they were humiliated, driven away from honour and respect. This story is detailed more in Surah Al-A'raf (7:163-166)."
  },
  66: {
    "So We made their fate an example to present and future generations,": "This punishment was not just for the transgressors themselves but was designed to be a warning for everyone—those who witnessed it and all who would hear about it afterward. It serves as a deterrent, showing what happens when people try to deceive Allah or circumvent His laws through technicalities. Loopholes do not work with Allah; He knows our intentions.",
    "and a lesson to the God-fearing.": "For those who have taqwa (consciousness of Allah), this story provides a powerful lesson. They learn to take Allah's commands seriously, to avoid the temptation of finding ways around religious obligations, and to fear the consequences of disobedience. The God-fearing benefit from the mistakes of others and take heed before falling into similar traps."
  },
  67: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when Moses said to his people, \"Allah commands you to sacrifice a cow.\"": "This is the story from which Surah Al-Baqarah (The Cow) gets its name. Musa conveyed Allah's clear command to slaughter a cow. The context, as revealed later in the story, was a murder case that needed divine intervention to solve. A man had been killed, and the killer was unknown. Allah prescribed this sacrifice as the means to reveal the truth.",
    "They replied, \"Are you mocking us?\"": "Instead of simply obeying the prophet's command, they responded with suspicion and disrespect. They questioned whether Musa was joking with them. This reaction showed a lack of trust in their prophet and a reluctance to obey without questioning. A believing community should respond to their prophet's commands with immediate acceptance.",
    "Moses responded, \"I seek refuge in Allah from acting foolishly!\"": "Musa firmly denied any mockery. Prophets do not joke about Allah's commands or play games with religion. He sought refuge in Allah from being among the ignorant—those who mock sacred matters. His response rebuked their inappropriate attitude and reaffirmed the seriousness of the divine command."
  },
  68: {
    "They said, \"Call upon your Lord to clarify for us what type ˹of cow˺ it should be!\"": "Instead of obeying the simple command to sacrifice any cow, they began asking for unnecessary details. This was not a sincere desire for clarification but a way of stalling and making things difficult for themselves. Each question they asked narrowed their options and made the task harder.",
    "He replied, \"Allah says, 'The cow should neither be old nor young but in between.": "Allah specified that the cow should be of middle age—not an old cow past its prime, nor a young heifer, but one in between. This specification came because they asked, not because it was originally required. If they had simply sacrificed any cow when first commanded, it would have sufficed.",
    "So do as you are commanded!'\"": "After providing the clarification, Musa urged them to just obey. This refrain emphasizes that the focus should be on obedience, not endless questioning. The more they asked, the more complicated the task became—a lesson about the dangers of excessive questioning and delay in religious matters."
  },
  69: {
    "They said, \"Call upon your Lord to specify for us its colour.\"": "Not satisfied with the age specification, they asked about the colour. Again, this question was unnecessary and only served to make their task more difficult. They were making a simple command complicated through their own doing.",
    "He replied, \"Allah says, 'It should be a bright yellow cow—pleasant to see.'\"": "The cow was to be distinctly bright yellow—a rare and beautiful colour that would make it pleasing to look at. Now they needed not just any middle-aged cow, but a bright yellow one. Such a cow would be rare and potentially expensive, a consequence of their excessive questioning."
  },
  70: {
    "Again they said, \"Call upon your Lord so that He may make clear to us which cow,": "Still not ready to obey, they asked for even more details. This persistent questioning revealed their reluctance to comply. It is as if they were looking for excuses not to do it.",
    "for all cows look the same to us.": "They claimed confusion, saying cows looked alike to them and they needed more clarification to identify the right one. This excuse was weak—they had been given specific criteria (middle-aged, bright yellow), which should have been enough to identify a suitable cow.",
    "Then, Allah willing, we will be guided ˹to the right one˺.\"": "They finally added \"Allah willing\" (insha'Allah), expressing hope that with all these clarifications, they would finally be guided to find the cow. The addition of \"insha'Allah\" showed some recognition of their dependence on Allah's guidance, though their excessive questioning had already demonstrated a problematic attitude."
  },
  71: {
    "He replied, \"Allah says, 'It should have been used neither to till the soil nor water the fields;": "More specifications: the cow must never have been used for farm work. Most cows were working animals, used for ploughing fields or operating water wheels. Finding a cow that was kept without working was rare.",
    "wholesome and without blemish.'\"": "The cow must also be perfect and healthy, without any spots, marks, or defects of any kind—a pure yellow cow with no other colours. Now they needed a middle-aged, bright yellow, never-worked, perfectly unblemished cow. Such an animal would be extraordinarily rare and expensive.",
    "They said, \"Now you have come with the truth.\"": "Finally, they acknowledged the description was clear enough. Ironically, they implied that the previous descriptions were not \"the truth\"—when in fact any cow would have been acceptable at the beginning. Their statement showed their problematic attitude throughout.",
    "Yet they still slaughtered it hesitantly!": "Even after all the clarifications, they complied reluctantly, barely bringing themselves to do it. They dragged their feet even in obedience. According to some reports, they paid a very high price for this specific cow because it was the only one that matched all the criteria. Their questioning cost them dearly. The lesson is clear: when Allah commands something, obey promptly without excessive questioning, or the task will become harder."
  },
  72: {
    "˹This is˺ when a man was killed and you disputed who the killer was,": "Now the context is revealed. A murder had occurred among the Israelites, and there was a dispute about who committed the crime. Everyone was blaming others, and the real killer was hidden among them. The community needed divine intervention to solve the case.",
    "but Allah revealed what you concealed.": "Allah knew who the murderer was, even though humans could not figure it out. Nothing is hidden from Allah. The cow sacrifice was the means by which Allah would expose the truth that people were trying to hide. Allah always brings hidden things to light when He wills."
  },
  73: {
    "So We instructed, \"Strike the dead body with a piece of the cow.\"": "After slaughtering the cow, they were commanded to take a piece of it and strike the dead body of the murdered man. This was a unique instruction that set up a miracle.",
    "This is how ˹easily˺ Allah brings the dead to life,": "When they struck the corpse with the cow's part, the dead man came back to life temporarily. He was able to identify his killer before dying again. This miracle demonstrated Allah's power to resurrect the dead—a preview of the resurrection on the Day of Judgment. If Allah can bring one person back to life, He can bring everyone back on the Last Day.",
    "showing you His signs": "This entire event—from the command to sacrifice a cow, through the resurrection of the murdered man—was a series of signs demonstrating Allah's power, knowledge, and authority. Signs are meant to strengthen faith and prove truth.",
    "so that you may understand.": "The purpose of showing signs is to stimulate understanding and reflection. Witnessing such miracles should lead to belief in Allah's power over life and death, trust in His prophets, and acceptance of accountability in the Hereafter. Those who truly understand will respond with faith and obedience."
  },
  74: {
    "Even then your hearts became hardened like a rock or even harder,": "Despite witnessing such an extraordinary miracle—a dead man coming back to life—their hearts still became hard and unresponsive to faith. Heart-hardness is a spiritual disease where signs and reminders no longer affect a person. They see miracles but remain unmoved. This is worse than rocks, which are at least naturally hard.",
    "for some rocks gush rivers;": "Allah gives examples of how even rocks can be more responsive than hardened hearts. Some rocks have rivers gushing from them—water, the source of life, flowing abundantly. The twelve springs from the rock for the Israelites is an example.",
    "others split, spilling water;": "Other rocks crack open to release water—perhaps not rivers, but at least some water comes forth. Even these rocks are not completely unresponsive.",
    "while others are humbled in awe of Allah.": "Some rocks fall from mountain heights out of fear of Allah—showing a kind of natural submission to the Creator. Mountains and rocks have a form of awareness that we may not fully understand. If rocks can show awe of Allah, how much more should human hearts—given consciousness and guidance—respond to Him?",
    "And Allah is never unaware of what you do.": "This is a warning: even if hearts become hard and unresponsive, Allah sees everything. He is fully aware of people's actions, attitudes, and intentions. Nothing escapes His knowledge. Those with hard hearts should not think they are getting away with anything—Allah is watching and recording."
  },
  79: {
    "So woe to those who distort the Scripture with their own hands": "\"Woe\" (wayl) is a severe warning indicating destruction and punishment. Allah condemns those who physically wrote fabrications, altered texts, or added their own interpretations into the scripture, passing them off as divine revelation. They literally used their own hands to corrupt Allah's words—changing, adding, or removing content from the original revelation. This is one of the worst crimes imaginable: putting human words in Allah's mouth.",
    "then say, \"This is from Allah\"—": "After corrupting the text, they would claim it was from Allah Himself. They attributed their lies and fabrications to the Creator of the universe. This is not just lying; it is lying about Allah, which is far worse than any ordinary lie. They gave their own words divine authority to deceive people.",
    "seeking a fleeting gain!": "Their motivation was worldly benefit—money, status, power, or social influence. They traded eternal truth for temporary gains. Religious scholars who change Allah's teachings for money, popularity, or political advantage fall into this category. No amount of worldly benefit is worth corrupting divine guidance. The gain is described as \"fleeting\" because all worldly things are temporary compared to the eternal consequences.",
    "So woe to them for what their hands have written,": "The first woe is for the act of writing falsehood and attributing it to Allah. Their hands physically committed this crime, and they will be held accountable for every false word they wrote.",
    "and woe to them for what they have earned.": "The second woe is for the profits and benefits they gained from this corruption. Every payment they received, every position they secured, every advantage they obtained through this deception adds to their punishment. They face double doom: for the crime itself and for profiting from it."
  },
  80: {
    "˹Some of˺ the Jews claim, \"The Fire will not touch us except for a number of days.\"": "Some among the Jewish community held a belief that even if they entered Hell, it would only be for a limited period—some said forty days (the time their ancestors worshipped the calf), others said seven days, and others had different numbers. This belief gave them false security, making them less concerned about sins and less motivated to follow the truth. It is a dangerous delusion that minimizes the seriousness of disobedience and the reality of eternal punishment.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Have you taken a pledge from Allah—": "Allah instructs the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) to challenge this claim. He asks: Do you have a covenant or promise from Allah guaranteeing limited punishment? Did Allah actually tell you this, or are you making it up?",
    "for Allah never breaks His word—": "If Allah had actually made such a promise, He would certainly fulfill it, because Allah never breaks His promises. His word is absolute truth. So if they had a genuine divine guarantee, they could rely on it completely.",
    "or are you ˹just˺ saying about Allah what you do not know?\"": "The alternative is that they are inventing claims about Allah without any basis—speaking about divine matters without knowledge or authority. This is exactly what they were doing: creating comfortable beliefs to justify their disobedience, with no scriptural foundation. Making claims about Allah without evidence is a serious sin."
  },
  81: {
    "But no! Those who commit evil": "Allah refutes their false claim with \"bala\" (but no!)—a strong negation. The reality is very different from their wishful thinking. Those who earn sins, who actively pursue wrongdoing and accumulate evil deeds, face a different fate.",
    "and are engrossed in sin": "This describes people whose sins have surrounded them completely—they are trapped in a cycle of wrongdoing with no escape. Their sins have become their identity; they are consumed by disobedience. This particularly refers to major sins like disbelief and polytheism, which, if a person dies upon without repentance, doom them eternally.",
    "will be the residents of the Fire.": "Such people will not just visit the Fire briefly; they will be its permanent inhabitants. They will dwell in Hell, not as temporary guests but as permanent residents.",
    "They will be there forever.": "This is the key point refuting their claim. For those who die upon disbelief and major sins without repentance, the punishment is eternal—not forty days, not seven days, but forever. There is no exit date for the disbelievers in Hell. This is the terrifying reality that comfortable false beliefs try to hide."
  },
  82: {
    "And those who believe and do good": "In contrast to the previous verse, here are the successful ones: those who combine genuine faith with righteous actions. Belief alone is not enough without good deeds, and good deeds without proper belief are not accepted. Both are necessary and inseparable.",
    "will be the residents of Paradise.": "These believers will inhabit Paradise—not as visitors but as permanent dwellers. Just as the disbelievers are residents of Hell, the believers are residents of Paradise.",
    "They will be there forever.": "The believers' stay in Paradise is eternal, just as the disbelievers' stay in Hell is eternal. Both eternities are real. This contrast shows that the ultimate outcomes are permanent and based on one's faith and actions in this temporary life. The choices we make here determine our forever."
  },
  83: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when We took a covenant from the children of Israel ˹stating˺,": "Allah recalls another covenant made with the Israelites, this one containing specific commandments covering both worship and social ethics. These were clear obligations they agreed to fulfill.",
    "\"Worship none but Allah;": "The first and most fundamental obligation: pure monotheism. Worship belongs exclusively to Allah, with no partners, intermediaries, or rivals. This is the foundation of all divine religions and the core message of every prophet.",
    "be kind to parents,": "After the rights of Allah come the rights of parents. Children must treat their parents with excellence (ihsan)—not just basic respect but going above and beyond in kindness, service, and care. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) emphasized that a parent's pleasure is connected to Allah's pleasure. This commandment appears repeatedly in the Quran, highlighting its importance.",
    "relatives, orphans and the needy;": "The circle of kindness expands: relatives deserve connection and support; orphans (children who have lost their fathers) need protection and care since they have no provider; and the needy (poor people) require assistance. This creates a society where vulnerable members are protected and supported.",
    "speak kindly to people;": "Beyond material help, the covenant included speaking good words to all people—not just family or fellow believers but everyone. Good speech includes being polite, honest, gentle, and encouraging. Words can heal or hurt, and believers are commanded to use them for good. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"A good word is charity.\" (Bukhari)",
    "establish prayer;": "Regular, proper prayer was obligated upon them, just as it is upon Muslims. Prayer maintains the connection with Allah and reminds us throughout the day of our purpose and obligations.",
    "and pay alms-tax.\"": "Zakah—obligatory charity for the poor—was also part of their covenant. Wealth is purified through sharing, and society is strengthened when the wealthy support the needy.",
    "But you ˹Israelites˺ turned away—except for a few of you—": "Despite agreeing to all these beautiful commandments, most of them broke the covenant and turned away. Only a small minority remained faithful. This pattern of making promises and breaking them characterized much of their history.",
    "and were indifferent.": "Their turning away was not due to forgetfulness but deliberate indifference. They knew what was required but chose to ignore it. This willful neglect is worse than ignorance."
  },
  84: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when We took your covenant that you would neither shed each other's blood": "Another part of the covenant prohibited killing members of their own community. Murder is absolutely forbidden, and the sanctity of life is paramount. \"Each other's blood\" emphasizes communal unity—they were one people and harming each other was like harming themselves.",
    "nor expel each other from their homes,": "They also pledged not to drive their own people from their homes. Forced displacement is a serious crime that destroys families and communities. This covenant protected every member's right to security in their home.",
    "you gave your pledge and bore witness.": "They formally accepted these terms and testified to their commitment. This was not an imposed rule but an agreement they willingly made with full awareness. Their own acknowledgment would stand as evidence against them when they violated it."
  },
  85: {
    "But here you are, killing each other and expelling some of your people from their homes,": "Allah exposes their blatant violation of the covenant. The Jewish tribes in Madinah before and during the Prophet's time had allied themselves with different Arab tribes. When these Arab tribes fought each other, the Jewish allies would fight alongside them—sometimes Jews killing Jews and expelling them from their homes. They literally violated everything they had pledged.",
    "aiding one another in sin and aggression;": "They actively helped others commit sins and transgress against their own people. Instead of standing together, they chose tribal alliances over religious brotherhood, participating in attacks against fellow Israelites.",
    "and when those ˹expelled˺ come to you as captives, you still ransom them—": "Here is the contradiction: after fighting against their own people, expelling them, and helping kill them, when these same people were captured by others and brought to them, they would pay to free them. They would ransom Jewish captives because the Torah commanded them to free their brethren from captivity.",
    "though expelling them was unlawful for you.": "They obeyed the command to ransom captives but violated the command not to expel them in the first place! How could they fight them, exile them, help kill them, and then turn around and ransom them, claiming to follow scripture? This selective obedience exposed their hypocrisy.",
    "Do you believe in some of the Scripture and reject the rest?": "This penetrating question exposes their approach to religion: picking and choosing which parts to follow based on convenience. They followed what suited them and ignored what did not. This is not true faith but manipulation of religion for personal interests.",
    "Is there any reward for those who do so among you other than disgrace in this worldly life": "The consequence for this selective belief is humiliation in this world. Throughout history, they faced various forms of disgrace and subjugation because of their violations. Their worldly status suffered due to their disobedience.",
    "and being subjected to the harshest punishment on the Day of Judgment?": "The punishment in the Hereafter will be even worse—the most severe torment. Those who pick and choose from Allah's commands, obeying what suits them and rejecting what doesn't, face the worst consequences.",
    "For Allah is never unaware of what you do.": "Again the reminder: Allah sees everything. He is not ignorant of their contradictory behaviour, their violations, and their hypocrisy. Every action is recorded and will be accounted for."
  },
  86: {
    "These are the ones who trade the Hereafter for the life of this world.": "Their fundamental error was prioritizing temporary worldly gains over eternal success. They sold their eternal home for this brief life. This is the worst trade anyone can make—exchanging Paradise for the fleeting pleasures and advantages of this world. Like selling a palace for a tent, or a diamond for glass.",
    "So their punishment will not be reduced,": "Because of this terrible trade, they will receive no reduction or lightening of their punishment. There will be no relief, no breaks, no gradual decrease. The punishment remains at full intensity forever.",
    "nor will they be helped.": "No one will come to their rescue. No allies, no intercessors (without Allah's permission), no saviors. They will be completely alone in facing the consequences of their choices. In this world, they sought worldly allies and benefits; in the Hereafter, none of that will help them."
  },
  87: {
    "Indeed, We gave Moses the Book": "Allah confirms that He blessed Musa with the Torah—a comprehensive scripture containing guidance, laws, and wisdom. This was a tremendous blessing showing Allah's care for the Israelites.",
    "and sent after him successive messengers.": "After Musa, Allah did not leave the Israelites without guidance. He sent prophet after prophet in succession—Dawud (David), Sulayman (Solomon), Ilyas (Elijah), Alyasa (Elisha), Yunus (Jonah), Zakariyya (Zechariah), Yahya (John), and many others. No nation received as many prophets as the Israelites did.",
    "And We gave Jesus, son of Mary, clear proofs": "Isa (Jesus), son of Maryam, was given bayyinat—clear proofs and miracles—including healing the blind and lepers, raising the dead by Allah's permission, and informing people of what they ate and stored in their homes. These miracles clearly proved his prophethood and should have convinced the Israelites to follow him.",
    "and supported him with the holy spirit.": "Isa was strengthened with Ruh al-Qudus, which most scholars identify as the angel Jibreel (Gabriel). This angelic support helped Isa in his mission, protected him from his enemies, and enabled him to perform miracles. Having such divine support should have made his message undeniable.",
    "Why is it that every time a messenger comes to you ˹Israelites˺ with something you do not like,": "Here is the accusation: whenever a prophet brought teachings that conflicted with their desires—whether commanding something they disliked or forbidding something they enjoyed—they refused to accept it. Their criterion was not truth but personal preference.",
    "you become arrogant,": "Instead of submitting to divine guidance, they became proud and arrogant, thinking themselves above following the prophets. Arrogance is the root cause of disbelief—refusing to humble oneself before Allah's message.",
    "rejecting some and killing others?": "Their arrogance led to two responses: some prophets they merely rejected and denied; others they actually killed. Zakariyya and Yahya (John the Baptist) were among those murdered by their own people. They attempted to kill Isa but Allah saved him. This pattern of prophet-rejection and prophet-killing is a grave indictment."
  },
  88: {
    "They say, \"Our hearts are unreceptive!\"": "When called to faith, they would excuse themselves by claiming their hearts were covered or wrapped—unable to receive guidance. They presented this as if they had no choice in the matter, as if their hearts were naturally incapable of accepting truth. This was an excuse to avoid responsibility.",
    "In fact, Allah has condemned them for their disbelief.": "Allah refutes their excuse. Their hearts are not naturally unreceptive; rather, Allah has cursed them because of their persistent disbelief. It is their own repeated rejection of truth that caused their hearts to become sealed. They chose disbelief first, and then Allah sealed their hearts as a consequence. The curse is not arbitrary but is the result of their choices.",
    "They have but little faith.": "Because of this curse, only very few among them come to true faith. Their community produces few genuine believers. This is not because faith is impossible for them but because their historical pattern of rejection has created spiritual consequences that make faith rare among them."
  },
  89: {
    "Although they used to pray for victory ˹by means of the Prophet˺ over the polytheists,": "Before Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) came, the Jewish communities in Arabia would tell the Arab polytheists: \"A prophet is coming soon, and when he comes, we will follow him and defeat you with his help.\" They used the coming of the final prophet as a threat against their enemies and a source of hope for themselves. They knew from their scriptures that a prophet was expected.",
    "when there came to them a Book from Allah which they recognized,": "When the Quran was revealed and Prophet Muhammad came—matching the descriptions in their own scriptures—they recognized him. Some Jewish scholars openly admitted he was the prophet they were waiting for. They knew it was the truth they had been anticipating.",
    "confirming the Scripture they had ˹in their hands˺,": "The Quran confirmed the original message of the Torah, validating their own religion's core teachings. It was not a foreign or contradictory message but a continuation and completion of what they already had.",
    "they rejected it.": "Despite recognition, despite anticipation, despite confirmation—they rejected the Quran and the Prophet. Why? Because he was not from among them; he was an Arab, not an Israelite. Their tribal pride could not accept a non-Jewish prophet, even though they knew he was genuine. Jealousy and ethnic pride overcame their recognition of truth.",
    "So may Allah's condemnation be upon the disbelievers.": "Allah pronounces His curse upon those who reject truth after recognizing it. This is the worst form of disbelief—knowing something is true and still refusing it. The curse means removal from Allah's mercy and deserving of punishment."
  },
  90: {
    "Miserable is the price they have sold their souls for—": "Allah expresses how terrible their bargain was. They exchanged their souls—their eternal salvation—for something worthless. What price could ever be worth selling one's soul and eternal happiness?",
    "denying Allah's revelation": "The transaction was this: they rejected what Allah had revealed—the Quran and the prophethood of Muhammad—and in exchange received nothing of real value.",
    "and resenting Allah for granting His grace to whoever He wills of His servants!": "Their reason for rejection was resentment and jealousy (baghy). They were angry that Allah chose an Arab to be the final prophet instead of someone from their lineage. They objected to Allah's decision to bestow His favour upon whomever He chose. This is objecting to Allah's divine will—a form of arrogance that questions the Creator's right to make decisions.",
    "They have earned wrath upon wrath.": "Their rejection brought not just single wrath but compounded anger from Allah. One layer of wrath for rejecting previous prophets and another for rejecting the final one. Their accumulated sins brought accumulated punishment. Wrath upon wrath—layers of divine displeasure.",
    "And such disbelievers will suffer a humiliating punishment.": "Their punishment in the Hereafter will be both painful and humiliating. It will not just be physical torment but complete degradation. Those who were too proud to accept the truth will be utterly humiliated. Pride leads to humiliation; humility before Allah leads to honour."
  },
  91: {
    "When it is said to them: \"Believe in what Allah has revealed,\"": "When the Jews were invited to believe in the Quran and accept Islam, they needed to respond. The invitation was clear: accept what Allah has now revealed through His final messenger.",
    "they reply, \"We only believe in what was sent down to us,\"": "Their excuse was that they only follow what was revealed to their own nation—the Torah. They used loyalty to their scripture as a reason to reject the new revelation. This sounds religious but is actually a form of tribalism disguised as faith.",
    "and they deny what came afterwards,": "They reject everything revealed after the Torah—including the Gospel of Isa and now the Quran. But their Torah itself told them to follow future prophets and to accept the final messenger when he came.",
    "though it is the truth confirming their own Scriptures!": "The Quran does not contradict the original Torah; it confirms its core message while completing the guidance. Rejecting the Quran is, in effect, rejecting what their own scripture pointed toward.",
    "Ask ˹them, O Prophet˺, \"Why then did you kill Allah's prophets before, if you are ˹truly˺ believers?\"": "Allah instructs the Prophet to expose their false claim. If they truly believed in what was revealed to them, why did their ancestors kill prophets who also came with Torah-based guidance? Prophets like Zakariyya and Yahya were from among them, taught the same Torah, yet were killed. This proves their rejection is not about loyalty to scripture but about following their desires. They rejected prophets even from their own tradition when those prophets challenged their wrongdoing."
  },
  92: {
    "Indeed, Moses came to you with clear proofs,": "Musa brought undeniable miracles and evidence: the staff turning into a serpent, his hand glowing white, the ten plagues on Egypt, the parting of the sea, water from the rock, manna and quails, and more. The evidence for his prophethood was overwhelming.",
    "then you worshipped the calf in his absence,": "Despite witnessing all these clear proofs, they turned to worshipping a golden calf the moment Musa went to receive the Torah. This shows how quickly they could abandon truth when left without direct prophetic supervision.",
    "acting wrongfully.": "Their calf-worship was pure wrongdoing—against Allah, against themselves, and against their covenant. Even loyalty to Musa himself could not prevent them from this transgression. This historical pattern is cited to show that rejecting the new prophet Muhammad is consistent with their ancestors' behaviour of rejecting or disobeying even their own prophets."
  },
  93: {
    "And when We took your covenant and raised the mountain above you ˹saying˺,": "Allah recalls again the dramatic covenant at Mount Sinai, when the mountain was lifted over them as a sign of the covenant's seriousness.",
    "\"Hold firmly to that ˹Scripture˺ which We have given you and obey,\"": "They were commanded to take the Torah seriously and to hear (and obey) its teachings. The command to \"hear\" implies to listen with the intention to follow.",
    "they answered, \"We hear and disobey.\"": "Their response, whether spoken or demonstrated through actions, was: \"We hear but we will not obey.\" Some scholars say they actually uttered these words mockingly; others say their actions were equivalent to saying this. Either way, they acknowledged receiving the command but refused to follow it.",
    "The love of the calf was rooted in their hearts because of their disbelief.": "Their attachment to the golden calf had penetrated deep into their hearts. Even after the calf incident was over, the love of that idol—representing their love of material things and their tendency toward disobedience—remained ingrained in them. This is described as being \"absorbed\" into their hearts, like liquid absorbed into something, because of their disbelief. Their rejection of truth allowed false attachments to take root.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"How evil is what your ˹so-called˺ belief prompts you to do, if you ˹actually˺ believe ˹in the Torah˺!\"": "The Prophet is told to challenge them: If this is what your faith produces—disobedience, calf-worship, rejection of prophets—then what a miserable faith it is! If you truly believed in the Torah, you would follow its guidance, accept the prophets it predicted, and obey Allah. Their claim of faith is contradicted by their actions."
  },
  94: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"If the ˹eternal˺ Home of the Hereafter with Allah is exclusively for you ˹Israelites˺ out of all humanity,": "Some among the Jews claimed that Paradise was reserved for them alone, that they were Allah's chosen people who would definitely enter Heaven regardless of their actions. They believed in their exclusive salvation.",
    "then wish for death if what you say is true!\"": "Allah challenges them with a simple test: if you are so certain of your place in Paradise, you should eagerly want to leave this world and reach your guaranteed reward. If Paradise is truly waiting for you, death should be welcome, not feared. This is a powerful challenge that exposes the hollowness of their claim."
  },
  95: {
    "But they will never wish for that because of what their hands have done.": "Allah declares that they will never accept this challenge. Deep down, they know the reality. Their deeds—rejecting prophets, distorting scripture, choosing worldly gains over truth—have earned them punishment, not Paradise. They fear what awaits them after death because they know their actions do not merit Paradise.",
    "And Allah has ˹perfect˺ knowledge of the wrongdoers.": "Allah knows their inner state, their hidden fears, and their true beliefs. Though they publicly claim exclusive salvation, internally they fear the consequences of their wrongdoing. Allah, the All-Knowing, is fully aware of who the wrongdoers are and what they truly deserve."
  },
  96: {
    "You will surely find them clinging to life more eagerly than any other people,": "Far from wishing for death, they are the most desperate people to stay alive. More than any other group, they cling to this worldly life. This excessive love of life exposes their lack of certainty about the Hereafter. Those who truly believe in Paradise do not fear death but prepare for it.",
    "even more than polytheists.": "They are even more attached to life than the mushrikeen (polytheists), who might be expected to fear death since they have no clear belief in a positive afterlife. But these People of the Book, who claim guaranteed Paradise, are even greedier for life than idol-worshippers. This is a powerful indictment of their false claims.",
    "Each one of them wishes to live a thousand years.": "Their desire for long life is so intense that each individual wishes to live a thousand years. This hyperbolic wish shows extreme attachment to this world and extreme fear of what comes after.",
    "But even if they were to live that long, it would not save them from the punishment.": "Even if they got their wish and lived a millennium, it would not save them from Allah's punishment. Eventually, every soul must face death and accountability. Delaying death does not cancel it. Their sins would still catch up with them, and their extended life would only mean more sins accumulated.",
    "And Allah is All-Seeing of what they do.": "Allah sees their behaviour, their clinging to life, their fear of the Hereafter, and their actions that earn punishment. Nothing escapes His observation. Their public claims of faith and their private fears are all known to Him."
  },
  97: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Whoever is an enemy of Gabriel": "Some Jews claimed that their rejection of Islam was because the angel Jibreel (Gabriel) brought the revelation to Muhammad. They claimed Jibreel was their enemy because he brought punishment and destruction, while they preferred Mikael (Michael) who brought blessings. They used this as an excuse to reject the Quran.",
    "should know that he revealed this ˹Quran˺ to your heart by Allah's Will,": "The Prophet is told to respond: Jibreel did not act independently; he brought the revelation by Allah's permission and command. Being angry at Jibreel is actually being angry at Allah's decision. The angel is just a messenger carrying out Allah's orders. The Quran came to the Prophet's heart—meaning it was revealed to him, settled in his heart, and he understood and memorized it.",
    "confirming what came before it—": "The Quran confirms and validates the previous scriptures—the Torah and Gospel in their original forms. It is not a contradictory message but a continuation.",
    "a guide and good news for the believers.\"": "The Quran serves as guidance (huda), showing the straight path, and good news (bushra), promising rewards and Paradise for those who believe and follow it. For believers, the Quran is the greatest blessing, not something to hate because of which angel delivered it."
  },
  98: {
    "Whoever is an enemy of Allah, His angels, His messengers, Gabriel, and Michael,": "Allah expands the issue: enmity toward any of Allah's angels or messengers is serious. Jibreel and Mikael are specifically mentioned, highlighting that both are noble angels of Allah. You cannot claim to love one and hate the other when both serve Allah. Hating Jibreel while claiming to accept Mikael is inconsistent and unacceptable.",
    "then ˹let them know that˺ Allah is certainly the enemy of the disbelievers.": "The consequence is severe: whoever takes Allah or any of His noble servants as enemies, Allah Himself becomes their enemy. And who can survive having Allah as an enemy? This is a terrifying warning. The disbelievers who reject based on arbitrary excuses about angels have made the Lord of all existence their adversary."
  },
  99: {
    "Indeed, We have sent down to you ˹O Prophet˺ clear revelations.": "Allah affirms that the Quran's verses are bayyinat—clear, manifest proofs that leave no reasonable doubt. They are not ambiguous or confusing but are crystal clear in their message and evidence.",
    "˹But˺ none will deny them except the rebellious.": "Only the fasiqoon—those who have left the bounds of obedience, who are rebellious and corrupt—reject such clear signs. Normal people with sincere hearts accept clear truth. It takes active rebellion against truth to reject verses that are so obviously divine. This emphasizes that rejection is not due to lack of evidence but due to moral failure."
  },
  100: {
    "Why is it that every time they make a covenant, a group of them casts it aside?": "This rhetorical question highlights their habitual covenant-breaking. Whether covenants with Allah at Sinai, agreements with prophets, or treaties with the Muslims in Madinah—a pattern emerges of making promises and then violating them. This is not occasional but consistent behaviour.",
    "In fact, most of them do not believe.": "The root cause is lack of true faith. Those who genuinely believe in Allah honor their commitments. The majority among them lacked sincere faith, which is why breaking covenants was so easy for them. Belief produces trustworthiness; disbelief produces treachery."
  },
  101: {
    "Now, when a messenger from Allah has come to them—": "Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) came to them with clear credentials, fulfilling descriptions in their own scriptures about the final messenger.",
    "confirming their own Scriptures—": "The Prophet and the Quran confirmed the truth of the Torah's original message, validating their religion's core teachings rather than abolishing them.",
    "some of the People of the Book cast the Book of Allah behind their backs": "Instead of embracing the confirmation, a group of them threw the Book of Allah behind their backs—a metaphor for complete rejection and deliberate ignorance. They literally turned their backs on divine guidance.",
    "as if they did not know.": "They acted as if they had never read their own scriptures predicting this prophet, as if they were completely ignorant of the signs. But their ignorance was feigned—they knew but pretended not to know. This willful ignorance is worse than genuine ignorance because it involves active deception of oneself and others."
  },
  102: {
    "They ˹instead˺ followed the magic promoted by the devils during the reign of Solomon.": "Instead of following the Book of Allah, some turned to magic that devils had spread during Prophet Sulayman's (Solomon's) time. The devils falsely attributed magic to Sulayman's kingdom, claiming he used sorcery to control his vast empire. People became fascinated with this magic and pursued it.",
    "Never did Solomon disbelieve, rather the devils disbelieved.": "Allah clears Sulayman's name. He was a noble prophet and king who never practiced magic or disbelief. The disbelief and magic came from the devils (shayateen), not from Sulayman. Accusing a prophet of magic is slander. Sulayman's power came from Allah, not from sorcery.",
    "They taught magic to the people,": "The devils actively taught magic to human beings, spreading this knowledge of evil. Magic is not a neutral skill but a path to disbelief, involving dealings with jinn and seeking power through forbidden means.",
    "along with what had been revealed to the two angels, Hârût and Mârût, in Babylon.": "In Babylon (ancient Iraq), Allah sent two angels, Harut and Marut, as a test for the people. These angels were given knowledge that could be used as magic. This was a trial to see who would remain faithful and who would pursue forbidden knowledge.",
    "The two angels never taught anyone without saying, \"We are only a test ˹for you˺, so do not abandon ˹your˺ faith.\"": "Before teaching anyone, the angels explicitly warned: \"We are a test—learning this will be an act of disbelief, so don't lose your faith over this.\" They gave clear warning that proceeding meant leaving the fold of faith. This made the choice clear and removed any excuse of ignorance.",
    "Yet people learned ˹magic˺ that caused a rift ˹even˺ between husband and wife;": "Despite the warnings, people still learned magic, using it for harmful purposes. One of the most mentioned harms is separating spouses—causing divorce and destruction of families through sorcery. Marriage is sacred, and magic that breaks it is among the worst uses of such knowledge.",
    "although their magic could not harm anyone except by Allah's Will.": "This is a crucial point: magic has no independent power. It can only affect someone if Allah permits it. This does not make magic less sinful—the practitioner is still guilty—but it reminds believers that ultimate control belongs to Allah alone. With proper faith, prayers, and protection, one can be safe from magic's effects by Allah's permission.",
    "They learned what harmed them and did not benefit them—": "The knowledge of magic only brought them harm—in this world through its evil consequences and in the Hereafter through punishment. It provided no lasting benefit. This is the nature of forbidden knowledge: it may seem powerful but ultimately destroys the one who pursues it.",
    "although they already knew that whoever buys into magic would have no share in the Hereafter.": "They were not ignorant of the consequences. They knew that pursuing magic meant forfeiting their place in Paradise. They made this choice with full knowledge, which makes their sin worse. They knowingly traded their eternal salvation for temporary worldly power.",
    "Miserable indeed was the price for which they sold their souls, if only they knew!": "Allah expresses how terrible their bargain was. They sold their souls—their eternal happiness—for magic that harms and does not benefit. If they truly understood the reality of what they traded, they would never have made such a deal. But their short-sightedness blinded them to the terrible consequences."
  },
  103: {
    "If only they were faithful and mindful ˹of Allah˺,": "Had they chosen faith and taqwa (consciousness of Allah that leads to obedience) instead of magic and disbelief, their outcome would have been entirely different. The alternative path was available to them—they just chose wrongly.",
    "there would have been a better reward from Allah,": "Allah's reward for faith and righteousness is infinitely better than anything magic could provide. The blessings of Paradise, Allah's pleasure, and eternal happiness far surpass any temporary power or worldly gain from sorcery.",
    "if only they knew!": "If they truly comprehended the value of what they gave up versus what they gained, they would have made a different choice. Their ignorance was not about facts but about wisdom—they did not truly understand value and consequence. This closing phrase is both sad and instructive: true knowledge leads to choosing Allah's path over any forbidden alternative."
  },
  135: {
    "The Jews and Christians each say, \"Follow our faith to be ˹rightly˺ guided.\"": "Both communities were calling people to their particular version of religion, each claiming exclusive possession of guidance. The Jews told people to become Jewish, and the Christians told people to become Christian, each insisting their path alone led to salvation. This created confusion and competition between the two.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"No! We follow the faith of Abraham, the upright—": "The Prophet is instructed to reject both sectarian invitations and point to something more fundamental: the millah (way/faith) of Ibrahim. Ibrahim was a hanif—one who turned away from all falsehood toward pure truth, inclining only toward Allah. His religion predates both Judaism and Christianity as distinct institutions. By returning to Ibrahim, Muslims claim the original, pure monotheism that both groups should have maintained.",
    "who was not a polytheist.\"": "Ibrahim was absolutely free from shirk (associating partners with Allah). He rejected the idols of his people and maintained pure monotheism. This subtle point challenges both communities: if you claim to follow Ibrahim, why have elements of your practice deviated from his pure monotheism? Christians with their Trinity and Jews with their excessive attachment to ancestry and law both moved away from Ibrahim's simple, pure submission to Allah alone."
  },
  136: {
    "Say, ˹O believers,˺ \"We believe in Allah": "Muslims begin their declaration of faith with belief in Allah—the foundation of everything. Without proper belief in Allah, nothing else matters.",
    "and what has been revealed to us;": "Muslims believe in the Quran, the final revelation sent to Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him). This is their direct scripture.",
    "and what was revealed to Abraham, Ishmael, Isaac, Jacob, and his descendants;": "Muslims also believe in the revelations given to these earlier prophets. The Asbat (descendants/tribes) refers to the twelve tribes of Israel and the prophets among them. Muslims do not reject these earlier figures but honor them.",
    "and what was given to Moses, Jesus, and other prophets from their Lord.": "Muslims believe in the Torah given to Musa and the Gospel given to Isa, as well as revelations given to all other prophets. This comprehensive belief system accepts all genuine divine guidance throughout history.",
    "We make no distinction between any of them.": "Muslims do not discriminate among prophets—accepting some while rejecting others. All prophets brought the same essential message and deserve equal respect as Allah's messengers. This contrasts with those who accept some prophets (like Moses) but reject others (like Jesus or Muhammad).",
    "And to Allah we all submit.\"": "The declaration concludes with submission (islam) to Allah. This is the essence of the faith of all prophets: belief in Allah and submission to His will. Muslims are not a new religious group but the continuation of this timeless tradition of submission."
  },
  137: {
    "So if they believe in what you believe, then they will indeed be ˹rightly˺ guided.": "The path to guidance is clear: if the Jews and Christians adopt the same comprehensive faith that Muslims have—believing in all prophets and submitting to Allah—they will be guided. Guidance is not about ethnic identity but about correct belief and submission.",
    "But if they turn away, they are simply opposed ˹to the truth˺.": "If they reject this inclusive faith and insist on their sectarian positions, they are in shiqaq—opposition, dissension, and conflict with the truth. Their turning away reveals that their objection is not based on sincere seeking of truth but on stubbornness and divisiveness.",
    "But Allah will spare you their evil.": "Allah reassures the believers that He will protect them from the harm these opponents might cause. Muslims need not fear those who oppose the truth; Allah is their protector and will suffice against all enemies.",
    "For He is the All-Hearing, All-Knowing.": "Allah hears everything they say and plot, and He knows everything in their hearts. This comprehensive knowledge means nothing escapes Him, and His protection is based on complete awareness of all threats."
  },
  138: {
    "This is the ˹natural˺ Way of Allah.": "The word \"sibghah\" literally means a dye or color that completely permeates something. Allah's sibghah is the natural disposition (fitrah) of true faith that should color a person's entire being. Just as dye completely transforms a fabric, true faith should completely transform a person. Some scholars also connect this to the Christian practice of baptism—Allah is saying that the real purification is not a ritual washing but being completely immersed in Allah's guidance.",
    "And who is better than Allah in ordaining a way?": "This rhetorical question asserts that no one can prescribe a better path than Allah. Human-made religions and philosophies are inferior to Allah's guidance. Any path other than His is deficient.",
    "And we worship ˹none but˺ Him.": "The believers declare their exclusive devotion to Allah. All worship—prayer, obedience, love, fear, hope—is directed to Him alone. This is the practical manifestation of accepting Allah's way."
  },
  139: {
    "Say, \"Would you dispute with us about Allah,": "The Prophet is told to challenge those who argue about religious matters. Why dispute about Allah when the facts are clear?",
    "while He is our Lord and your Lord?": "Allah is Lord of all—Muslims, Jews, Christians, and everyone else. He is not the exclusive property of any group. Disputes based on claiming exclusive ownership of Allah or His favor are baseless.",
    "We are accountable for our deeds and you for yours.": "Each group is responsible for its own actions. Muslims will be judged for what they do, and others will be judged for what they do. This separates accountability and prevents arguments about who is better based on ancestry.",
    "And we are devoted to Him ˹alone˺.": "Muslims declare their ikhlās—sincere, exclusive devotion to Allah without any partners or intermediaries. This pure devotion is what distinguishes true faith from contaminated or divided loyalties."
  },
  140: {
    "Or do you claim that Abraham, Ishmael, Isaac, Jacob, and his descendants were all Jews or Christians?\"": "This exposes an anachronistic claim. Judaism as a religion came after Musa, and Christianity came after Isa—both long after Ibrahim, Ismail, Ishaq, and Yaqub. How could these patriarchs be Jews or Christians when those religions did not yet exist in their institutional forms? They were simply muslims—submitters to Allah.",
    "Say, \"Who is more knowledgeable: you or Allah?\"": "Allah, who knows all history and all truth, has declared these patriarchs were neither Jews nor Christians but followers of pure monotheism. Human claims cannot override divine knowledge.",
    "Who does more wrong than those who hide the testimony they received from Allah?": "Some among the People of the Book knew the truth about these prophets and about the coming of Muhammad but concealed this knowledge. Hiding testimony from Allah is among the worst wrongs because it deprives people of guidance.",
    "And Allah is never unaware of what you do.": "A reminder that Allah sees their concealment and all their deeds. Nothing is hidden from Him, and all will be accountable."
  },
  141: {
    "That was a community that had already gone before.": "This verse is repeated from earlier (verse 134), emphasizing its importance. The past generations have passed away. Their time is over.",
    "For them is what they earned": "Those earlier people will receive the consequences of their deeds—good or bad. Their account is with Allah.",
    "and for you is what you have earned.": "Current people are judged by their own deeds, not by their ancestors' status. Claiming descent from righteous people provides no automatic benefit.",
    "And you will not be accountable for what they have done.": "No one will be questioned about another's deeds. Each soul bears its own burden. This repeated emphasis destroys any notion of inherited spiritual merit or guaranteed salvation through lineage."
  },
  142: {
    "The foolish among the people will ask, \"Why did they turn away from the direction of prayer they used to face?\"": "When the qiblah (prayer direction) was changed from Jerusalem to Mecca, critics objected. The Jews saw it as rejection of their heritage, the hypocrites saw it as inconsistency, and the polytheists saw it as confusion. Allah calls these critics \"sufaha\" (foolish, lacking understanding) because they failed to comprehend the wisdom behind divine commands. Muslims had prayed toward Jerusalem for about sixteen or seventeen months after the migration to Madinah.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"The east and west belong ˹only˺ to Allah.": "All directions belong to Allah. No direction is inherently sacred; sanctity comes from Allah's designation. When Allah commands facing Jerusalem, that becomes sacred; when He commands facing Mecca, that becomes sacred. The location does not limit Allah; rather, He determines which location is honored.",
    "He guides whoever He wills to the Straight Path.\"": "The change of qiblah is part of Allah's guidance. He guides people not according to human preferences but according to His wisdom. Those whom He guides understand and accept; those who are foolish object and criticize."
  },
  143: {
    "And so We have made you ˹believers˺ an upright community": "The Muslim ummah is described as \"ummatan wasatan\"—a middle, balanced, just community. They avoid extremes of the Jews (who focused heavily on law and rejected later prophets) and Christians (who exceeded bounds regarding Jesus). Muslims are moderate in belief and practice, balanced between worldly life and spiritual pursuits.",
    "so that you may be witnesses over humanity": "This balanced community will serve as witnesses over other nations on the Day of Judgment. They witnessed the truth and conveyed it, so they can testify about whether other nations received the message. This is an enormous responsibility.",
    "and that the Messenger may be a witness over you.": "Just as Muslims witness over other nations, the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) will be a witness over the Muslim ummah—testifying about whether they followed his guidance.",
    "We assigned your former direction of prayer only to distinguish those who would remain faithful to the Messenger from those who would lose faith.": "The original qiblah of Jerusalem was a test. When the change came to Mecca, it revealed who truly followed the Prophet versus who had other attachments. Some might have accepted Islam partly because of shared practice with Jews; the change exposed where true loyalty lay.",
    "It was certainly a difficult test except for those ˹rightly˺ guided by Allah.": "The change was hard—people had prayed toward Jerusalem, some had died praying that way, and now everything changed. This difficulty was real, but those whom Allah guided found it easy to accept because they understood that obedience to Allah and His Messenger is what matters, not attachment to directions.",
    "And Allah would never discount your ˹previous acts of˺ faith.": "Muslims worried about prayers performed toward Jerusalem—were those prayers wasted? Allah reassures them: those prayers were valid acts of faith and will be fully rewarded. Allah does not waste the deeds of believers.",
    "Surely Allah is Ever Gracious and Most Merciful to humanity.": "Allah's attributes of ra'fah (compassion/graciousness) and rahmah (mercy) mean He understands human concerns and treats them gently. He did not invalidate past prayers or condemn people for following the previous command."
  },
  144: {
    "Indeed, We see you ˹O Prophet˺ turning your face towards heaven.": "The Prophet longed to pray toward the Kaaba, the house built by Ibrahim. He would look toward the sky, hoping for revelation changing the qiblah. Allah saw this heartfelt desire—not spoken as a demand but expressed through hopeful glances.",
    "Now We will make you turn towards a direction ˹of prayer˺ that will please you.": "Allah grants the Prophet's wish, showing His love and care for His Messenger. The new qiblah would please him because it connected to Ibrahim's legacy and distanced Muslim practice from Jewish claims.",
    "So turn your face towards the Sacred Mosque ˹in Mecca˺—": "The command is clear: face the Masjid al-Haram in Mecca when praying. This mosque contains the Kaaba, the first house of worship established for humanity.",
    "wherever you are, turn your faces towards it.": "This applies universally—wherever Muslims are on earth, they face Mecca in prayer. This creates unity: billions of Muslims across centuries and continents all facing one point, all connected in worship.",
    "Those who were given the Scripture certainly know this to be the truth from their Lord.": "The Jews and Christians knew from their own texts that the change to Mecca was legitimate. Their scriptures contained prophecies about the shift of sacred center from Jerusalem to Mecca with the final Prophet. Their denial was despite knowledge, not due to ignorance.",
    "And Allah is never unaware of what they do.": "Allah knows their denial, their concealment of truth, and all their actions. They will be held accountable."
  },
  145: {
    "Even if you were to bring every proof to the People of the Book, they would not accept your direction ˹of prayer˺,": "Allah informs the Prophet that no amount of evidence will convince those who have decided to reject. Their rejection is not based on lack of proof but on stubbornness and prejudice. This saves the Prophet from exhausting himself trying to convince the unconvinceable.",
    "nor would you accept theirs;": "The Prophet will never adopt their qiblah after Allah has revealed the true direction. There is no compromise on divine commands.",
    "nor would any of them accept the direction ˹of prayer˺ of another.": "Even among themselves, Jews and Christians differ—Jews face Jerusalem, various Christian groups have different practices. They cannot agree among themselves yet criticize Muslim unity on this matter.",
    "And if you were to follow their desires after ˹all˺ the knowledge that has come to you, then you would certainly be one of the wrongdoers.": "This stern warning applies hypothetically—if the Prophet were ever to abandon divine guidance to follow their wishes (which he never would), he would be among the wrongdoers. This also warns all believers: abandoning certain knowledge to please others is serious wrongdoing."
  },
  146: {
    "Those We have given the Scripture recognize this ˹Prophet˺ as they recognize their own children.": "The Jewish and Christian scholars knew Prophet Muhammad as certainly as they knew their own sons. They recognized his description from their scriptures—his lineage, his characteristics, his city, his message. Abdullah ibn Salam, a famous Jewish convert, was asked about this verse and confirmed that he knew Muhammad more certainly than his own son because he could not be absolutely sure about his son, but he was absolutely certain about Muhammad from the scriptural descriptions.",
    "Yet a group of them hides the truth knowingly.": "Despite this certain recognition, many chose to conceal the truth. They knew he was the promised prophet but refused to admit it publicly. Their knowledge made their denial worse—they were not ignorant but dishonest."
  },
  147: {
    "˹This is˺ the truth from your Lord,": "Allah affirms that everything revealed—the prophethood of Muhammad, the change of qiblah, the guidance given—is absolute truth from the Lord. It is not opinion, not interpretation, but truth from the source of all truth.",
    "so do not ever be one of those who doubt.": "The Prophet (and by extension all believers) is commanded never to fall into doubt. When Allah has clarified something, no room remains for uncertainty. Doubt after clarity is a spiritual disease that must be avoided."
  },
  148: {
    "Everyone turns to their own direction ˹of prayer˺.": "Different religious communities have their own qiblahs—Jews toward Jerusalem, Muslims toward Mecca. This is acknowledged as a reality without condemning the existence of differences.",
    "So compete with one another in doing good.": "Rather than argue endlessly about directions, the focus should be on racing to do good deeds. Let each community demonstrate the value of their faith through excellent conduct. The real competition should be in righteousness, not in polemics.",
    "Wherever you are, Allah will bring you all together ˹for judgment˺.": "No matter where people are geographically or which direction they face, Allah will gather everyone on the Day of Judgment. Then the truth will be finally established, and all disputes will be settled.",
    "Surely Allah is Most Capable of everything.": "Gathering all of humanity from all places and all times is easy for Allah. His power encompasses everything."
  },
  149: {
    "Wherever you are ˹O Prophet˺, turn your face towards the Sacred Mosque.": "The command is repeated for emphasis. From any location on earth, when praying, face the Sacred Mosque in Mecca. This repetition underscores the importance and permanence of this ruling.",
    "This is certainly the truth from your Lord.": "Again, the divine origin is emphasized—this is not human preference but truth from Allah.",
    "And Allah is never unaware of what you ˹all˺ do.": "All actions, including the direction faced in prayer and the sincerity behind it, are known to Allah. This encourages careful adherence to the command."
  },
  150: {
    "Wherever you are ˹O Prophet˺, turn your face towards the Sacred Mosque. And wherever you ˹believers˺ are, face towards it,": "The command is given a third time, now explicitly including all believers, not just the Prophet. Everyone, everywhere, faces Mecca. This creates a unified ummah with a single focal point.",
    "so that people will have no argument against you,": "One wisdom behind the change to Mecca was removing grounds for criticism. The Jews might have argued Muslims were dependent on Jewish heritage. With Mecca as qiblah, Muslims have their own distinct identity connected to Ibrahim through Ismail, not through the Israelite line.",
    "except the wrongdoers among them.": "Some will still argue despite having no valid grounds—these are the wrongdoers who oppose truth regardless of evidence. Their objections are baseless.",
    "Do not fear them; fear Me,": "Muslims should not be intimidated by critics or enemies. The only being worthy of ultimate fear is Allah. Fear of people leads to compromise; fear of Allah leads to steadfastness.",
    "so that I may ˹continue to˺ perfect My favour upon you": "Obeying this command is part of Allah completing His blessings on the believers. Each act of obedience leads to more blessings and favors from Allah.",
    "and so you may be ˹rightly˺ guided.": "The purpose of all these commands is guidance. Following Allah's directions leads to being on the straight path, which leads to success in both worlds."
  },
  151: {
    "Since We have sent you a messenger from among yourselves—": "Allah reminds the believers of the immense blessing of having a messenger from their own people. Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) was an Arab, from their language, their culture, their community. This made understanding him easier and his example directly relatable. This was also the answer to Ibrahim's prayer in verse 129.",
    "reciting to you Our revelations,": "The Prophet recites the Quran—the direct words of Allah—to the people. This recitation is a continuous blessing, bringing divine guidance into their lives daily.",
    "purifying you,": "The Prophet purifies the believers—cleansing their beliefs from falsehood, their characters from vice, and their actions from sin. This purification (tazkiyah) transforms individuals and society.",
    "teaching you the Book and wisdom,": "Beyond recitation, the Prophet teaches the deeper meanings of the Quran (the Book) and the wisdom (hikmah) to apply it correctly. The Sunnah is this practical wisdom that shows how to live the Quran.",
    "and teaching you what you never knew—": "The Prophet brings knowledge that humanity could never discover on their own—matters of the unseen, details of the afterlife, proper worship of Allah. This knowledge elevates humanity beyond anything it could achieve independently."
  },
  152: {
    "remember Me; I will remember you.": "Allah makes an incredible promise: if you remember Him, He will remember you. Human remembrance of Allah means dhikr—mentioning Him, thinking of Him, worshipping Him. Allah's remembrance of us means honoring us, mentioning us to the angels, bestowing blessings upon us. The Prophet (peace be upon him) reported that Allah says: \"I am as My servant thinks of Me, and I am with him when he remembers Me. If he remembers Me in himself, I remember him in Myself; if he remembers Me in an assembly, I remember him in a better assembly.\" (Bukhari & Muslim)",
    "And thank Me,": "Gratitude (shukr) is obligatory. After mentioning all the blessings—the Messenger, the revelation, the purification, the knowledge—Allah commands thankfulness. Gratitude is shown through the heart (recognizing blessings), the tongue (praising Allah), and actions (using blessings in obedience).",
    "and never be ungrateful.": "Kufr here means ingratitude—denying or ignoring blessings. The greatest ingratitude is disbelieving in the One who gave the blessings. Believers must avoid both explicit disbelief and the more subtle ingratitude of taking blessings for granted."
  },
  153: {
    "O believers! Seek comfort in patience and prayer.": "Allah addresses the believers directly, teaching them how to face life's challenges. The two tools prescribed are sabr (patience) and salah (prayer). Patience means steadfastness in obeying Allah, perseverance in avoiding sin, and endurance during hardship. Prayer connects the believer to Allah, provides spiritual strength, and puts problems in perspective. Together, these two form the believer's essential toolkit for navigating difficulties.",
    "Allah is truly with those who are patient.": "This is a profound promise: Allah's special companionship (ma'iyyah) is with the patient ones. He supports them, guides them, protects them, and helps them through their trials. Knowing Allah is with you transforms how you experience difficulty."
  },
  154: {
    "Never say that those martyred in the cause of Allah are dead—": "This was revealed in connection with the martyrs of the early battles, particularly Badr. Muslims should not refer to those killed in Allah's cause as simply \"dead\" (amwat). This term implies cessation and loss, which does not capture their reality.",
    "in fact, they are alive!": "Martyrs are alive with a special life granted by Allah. Their souls are in a blessed state, enjoying provision from Allah. Another verse (3:169) elaborates: \"Do not think of those who are killed in Allah's cause as dead. Rather, they are alive with their Lord, receiving provision.\"",
    "But you do not perceive it.": "This life of martyrs is beyond our perception. We cannot see or feel their experience with our physical senses. It belongs to the realm of the unseen (ghayb), which we accept through faith in Allah's word."
  },
  155: {
    "We will certainly test you with a touch of fear": "Allah guarantees that trials will come—this is certain. Fear is one form: fear of enemies, fear of the unknown, general anxiety about the future.",
    "and famine": "Hunger and scarcity of food are another test. Whether through poverty, drought, or other circumstances, people will experience hunger.",
    "and loss of property,": "Wealth may decrease through business failure, theft, natural disasters, or other means. Financial hardship is a common test.",
    "life,": "Loss of loved ones through death is among the most painful tests. Life is taken through illness, accidents, conflict, and natural death.",
    "and crops.": "Agricultural loss—whether from drought, flood, pests, or disease—affects food supply and livelihood. These natural calamities test faith.",
    "Give good news to those who patiently endure—": "Despite listing these difficulties, Allah immediately offers good news (bashir) to those who respond with patience. The test is not punishment but an opportunity for reward."
  },
  156: {
    "who, when faced with a disaster, say,": "The patient ones are identified by their response to calamity. When musibah (disaster/affliction) strikes, they have a specific response—not cursing fate or despairing, but speaking words of faith.",
    "\"Surely to Allah we belong": "\"Inna lillahi\"—we belong to Allah. Everything we have—our wealth, our children, our lives—belongs to Him. He lent these things to us temporarily. When He takes something back, He is simply reclaiming what was always His. Understanding this ownership transforms how we experience loss.",
    "and to Him we will ˹all˺ return.\"": "\"Wa inna ilayhi raji'un\"—and we will return to Him. Death is not the end; it is a return to our origin. Since we are going back to Allah anyway, losing things along the way is natural. This perspective places every loss in the context of our ultimate journey to Allah. This phrase, known as istirja', is recommended to say during any difficulty or loss."
  },
  157: {
    "They are the ones who will receive Allah's blessings": "The patient receive salawat from Allah—blessings, praise, and mercy from the Lord of all worlds. When Allah sends salah upon someone, it means He mentions them with praise to the angels and bestows special favors upon them.",
    "and mercy.": "Along with blessings comes rahmah—the comprehensive mercy of Allah. This mercy protects them, comforts them, and rewards them. Receiving both blessings and mercy is the greatest honor.",
    "And it is they who are ˹rightly˺ guided.": "The patient ones are muhtadun—the rightly guided. Their patience during trials demonstrates true guidance. Anyone can claim faith when things are easy; patience during difficulty proves genuine guidance. This is the ultimate success: having Allah's blessings, His mercy, and being counted among the guided."
  },
  158: {
    "Indeed, ˹the hills of˺ Ṣafa and Marwah are among the symbols of Allah.": "Safa and Marwah are two small hills near the Kaaba in Mecca. They are sha'a'ir—symbols, landmarks, and rites of Allah's religion. They hold significance because of Hajar's (Hagar's) story: when Ibrahim left her and baby Ismail in the barren valley, she ran between these hills searching for water until Allah caused Zamzam to spring forth. This desperate, faithful search is commemorated in the Hajj and Umrah rituals.",
    "So whoever performs the pilgrimage or minor pilgrimage,": "Hajj is the major pilgrimage with specific days and rites; Umrah is the lesser pilgrimage that can be performed any time. Both involve circling the Kaaba (tawaf) and walking between Safa and Marwah (sa'i).",
    "let them walk between ˹the two hills˺.": "This walking back and forth, called sa'i, commemorates Hajar's search. The phrase \"la junaha 'alayhi\" (no blame/sin on him) was revealed because some Muslims worried about performing this ritual since the pre-Islamic Arabs had placed idols on these hills. Allah clarified that sa'i is legitimate worship, not connected to the pagan practices that were eliminated.",
    "And whoever does good willingly,": "Beyond the obligatory rituals, whoever volunteers additional good deeds will be rewarded. This applies to extra acts of worship during pilgrimage and generally to all voluntary righteousness.",
    "Allah is truly Appreciative,": "Allah is Shakir—appreciative of good deeds, acknowledging them, and rewarding them generously. He does not overlook any act of worship or kindness.",
    "All-Knowing.": "Allah is Aleem—fully aware of all deeds, intentions, and circumstances. He knows the sincerity behind actions and rewards accordingly."
  },
  159: {
    "Those who hide the clear proofs and guidance that We have revealed—": "This refers primarily to the scholars among the People of the Book who concealed information about Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) and other truths found in their scriptures. They hid clear evidence (bayyinat) and guidance (huda) that Allah had revealed. Their crime was deliberate suppression of truth that people needed for their salvation.",
    "after We made it clear for humanity in the Book—": "Allah had made these truths clear in the previous scriptures—the Torah and Gospel. The information was not ambiguous; it was plainly stated. These scholars knew the truth but chose to hide it from others, often to protect their status or material interests.",
    "will be condemned by Allah": "The consequence is la'nah (curse) from Allah Himself. Being cursed by Allah means being expelled from His mercy, cut off from His blessings, and destined for punishment. This is the most severe condemnation possible.",
    "and ˹all˺ those who condemn.": "Beyond Allah's curse, they will be cursed by all who have the capacity to curse—angels, prophets, righteous people, and even animals and inanimate objects on the Day of Judgment. The entire creation will condemn those who hid guidance from humanity."
  },
  160: {
    "As for those who repent,": "Allah opens the door of hope. Despite the severity of hiding knowledge, sincere repentance (tawbah) can erase the sin. Repentance means feeling genuine regret, stopping the wrong action, and resolving never to return to it.",
    "mend their ways,": "Repentance must be accompanied by islah—correction and reform. They must fix what they damaged through their concealment. This includes changing their behavior and working to undo the harm caused.",
    "and let the truth be known,": "Specifically for the sin of hiding knowledge, repentance requires disclosure. They must make clear (bayyanu) what they previously hid. The antidote to concealment is revelation. They must now actively share the truth they once suppressed.",
    "they are the ones to whom I will turn ˹in forgiveness˺,": "Allah promises to accept their repentance. \"Atoobu 'alayhim\" means Allah turns toward them with forgiveness, acceptance, and restored relationship. The curse is lifted when the conditions are met.",
    "for I am the Accepter of Repentance, Most Merciful.": "Allah describes Himself with two beautiful names: At-Tawwab (the One who repeatedly accepts repentance) and Ar-Raheem (the Most Merciful). These names give hope that no matter how severe the sin, Allah's door is open for those who sincerely return."
  },
  161: {
    "Surely those who disbelieve and die as disbelievers": "This describes the worst outcome: dying in a state of disbelief. Life offers chances to repent, but once death comes while one is still in kufr (disbelief), the opportunity ends. The key phrase is \"die as disbelievers\"—it is the state at death that determines the outcome.",
    "are condemned by Allah, the angels, and all of humanity.": "The curse upon them is comprehensive: from Allah (the Lord of all), from the angels (the noble servants of Allah), and from all of humanity (an-nas ajma'in). On the Day of Judgment, even other disbelievers will curse each other. The consensus of all creation will be against those who died in disbelief."
  },
  162: {
    "They will be in Hell forever.": "Khalideen—eternally, without end. For those who die upon disbelief, Hell is their permanent residence. There is no exit, no parole, no termination of sentence.",
    "Their punishment will not be lightened,": "The punishment will not decrease over time. There is no getting used to it, no reduction for good behavior, no gradual relief. It remains at full intensity forever.",
    "nor will they be delayed ˹from it˺.": "They will not be given respite or postponement. No delays, no breaks, no temporary relief. The punishment is immediate upon judgment and continuous thereafter. This comprehensive description removes any false hope about the afterlife for those who reject faith."
  },
  163: {
    "Your God is ˹only˺ One God.": "This is the fundamental declaration of tawhid (monotheism). There is only one deity worthy of worship for all of humanity. Not multiple gods, not local gods, not tribal gods—but one universal God for everyone.",
    "There is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Him—": "La ilaha illa Huwa—the testimony of faith. No deity has any right to worship except Allah. All other objects of worship are false and powerless. This negates all forms of polytheism and idolatry.",
    "the Most Compassionate, Most Merciful.": "Ar-Rahman, Ar-Raheem—the two names emphasizing Allah's mercy. The one true God is not distant or harsh but overwhelmingly merciful. His mercy encompasses all creation. Recognizing Allah's oneness should lead to comfort and hope because this one God is defined by mercy."
  },
  164: {
    "Indeed, in the creation of the heavens and the earth;": "The vast cosmos above and the intricate earth below are signs of Allah. The heavens with their countless stars, galaxies, and precise orbits; the earth with its perfect conditions for life—all point to a wise Creator.",
    "the alternation of the day and the night;": "The regular cycle of day and night, perfectly balanced for human activity and rest, is no accident. The precise tilt of the earth, its rotation creating this rhythm—this is design, not chance.",
    "the ships that sail the sea for the benefit of humanity;": "Ships floating on water, carrying people and goods across oceans, demonstrate Allah's arrangement of nature for human benefit. Water's density, wind patterns, and human ingenuity to harness them are all from Allah.",
    "the rain sent down by Allah from the skies, reviving the earth after its death;": "The water cycle—evaporation, cloud formation, rain—brings dead land back to life. Barren ground becomes green and productive. This revival is a sign of Allah's power and a preview of resurrection.",
    "the scattering of all kinds of creatures throughout;": "The diversity of life—animals, insects, birds, sea creatures—spread across the earth is another sign. Each species is designed for its environment, and all are sustained by Allah.",
    "the shifting of the winds;": "Winds change direction and intensity, bringing weather patterns, pollinating plants, and making sailing possible. This controlled variability shows purposeful design.",
    "and the clouds drifting between the heavens and the earth—": "Clouds suspended between sky and earth, carrying billions of tons of water, moving where Allah directs them—this is another marvel of creation.",
    "˹in all of this˺ are surely signs for people of understanding.": "These natural phenomena are ayat—signs pointing to Allah. But they benefit only those who use their intellect ('aql). People of understanding reflect on creation and recognize the Creator. Those who ignore these signs waste their rational faculty."
  },
  165: {
    "Still there are some who take others as Allah's equal—": "Despite all the clear signs, some people take andad—rivals, equals, or partners—alongside Allah. These could be idols, powerful humans, ideologies, desires, or anything else given the devotion that belongs only to Allah.",
    "they love them as they should love Allah—": "The problem is misdirected love. These people give to their false gods the intense, devoted love that should be reserved for Allah alone. They prioritize these rivals, obey them, fear them, and hope in them as if they were divine.",
    "but the ˹true˺ believers love Allah even more.": "In contrast, genuine believers have the most intense love for Allah. Their love for Allah exceeds all other loves. This is the hallmark of true faith: Allah comes first in the heart. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"None of you truly believes until I am more beloved to him than his child, his parent, and all people.\" (Bukhari & Muslim) And Allah deserves even greater love.",
    "If only the wrongdoers could see the ˹horrible˺ punishment ˹awaiting them˺,": "Allah wishes the wrongdoers could witness what awaits them. If they saw the reality of the punishment, they would immediately abandon their false attachments.",
    "they would certainly realize that all power belongs to Allah": "They would understand that the rivals they worshipped have no power at all. All quwwah (power, strength, might) belongs exclusively to Allah. Their idols cannot help themselves, let alone their worshippers.",
    "and that Allah is indeed severe in punishment.": "They would also realize how severe Allah's punishment is. His punishment matches His power—unlimited and overwhelming. This realization would transform their priorities, but by then it would be too late."
  },
  166: {
    "˹Consider the Day˺ when those who misled others will disown their followers—": "On the Day of Judgment, the leaders who were followed—whether religious authorities, political figures, or others who led people astray—will disown (tabarra'a) their followers. The verb implies total dissociation and rejection. They will say, \"I have nothing to do with you.\"",
    "when they face the torment—": "This disowning happens when they see the punishment. Facing the reality of Hell, all earthly loyalties evaporate. Self-preservation becomes the only concern.",
    "and the bonds that united them will be cut off.": "The asbab—ties, connections, relationships—that bound leaders and followers will be completely severed. All the networks of influence, dependency, and loyalty that existed in this world will be dissolved. No one will help anyone else; each person faces judgment alone."
  },
  167: {
    "The ˹misled˺ followers will cry, \"If only we could have a second chance,": "The followers express their desperate wish: if only they could return to the world and live again. They want a karrah—a return, another opportunity.",
    "we would disown them as they disowned us.\"": "They would repay the betrayal by disowning their former leaders just as they have been disowned. But this wish is futile—there is no return, no second chance.",
    "And so Allah will make them remorseful of their misdeeds.": "Allah will show them their deeds as sources of intense regret (hasarat). Everything they did in following falsehood will become a source of burning regret. They will see clearly how they wasted their lives.",
    "And they will never ˹be able to˺ leave the Fire.": "Despite their regret, despite their wishes, they will never exit the Fire. The door is closed forever. Regret without opportunity for change is the essence of Hell's torment."
  },
  168: {
    "O humanity! Eat from what is lawful and good on the earth": "Allah addresses all people (ya ayyuha an-nas), not just believers. The command is to eat what is halal (lawful, permitted) and tayyib (good, pure, wholesome). Allah has made the earth's provisions available for human consumption, but within boundaries. Food should be both legally permissible and qualitatively good.",
    "and do not follow Satan's footsteps.": "Instead of making haram things lawful or lawful things haram based on whims, people should avoid following Satan's path. \"Khutuwat\" (footsteps) suggests gradual progression—Satan does not lead people astray in one leap but step by step. First a small deviation, then another, until one is far from truth.",
    "He is truly your sworn enemy.": "Satan is an 'aduww mubeen—a clear, open, declared enemy. He has announced his intention to mislead humanity. Treating him as anything less than a mortal enemy is dangerous naivety. Everything he suggests ultimately leads to destruction."
  },
  169: {
    "He only incites you to commit evil": "Satan's commands lead to su' (evil, harm, wrongdoing). Everything he promotes ultimately causes harm to individuals and society.",
    "and indecency,": "He pushes toward fahsha' (indecency, shameful acts, immorality). This includes sexual immorality, obscenity, and anything that violates human dignity and decency.",
    "and to claim against Allah what you do not know.": "Perhaps the worst thing Satan promotes is speaking about Allah without knowledge. This includes making up religious rulings, attributing false teachings to Allah, and claiming to know Allah's will without revelation. All false religions and distorted teachings stem from this Satanic suggestion."
  },
  170: {
    "When it is said to them, \"Follow what Allah has revealed,\"": "When called to follow divine revelation—the Quran and authentic teachings—some people resist. They are invited to base their beliefs and practices on Allah's guidance.",
    "they reply, \"No! We ˹only˺ follow what we found our forefathers practicing.\"": "Their excuse is tradition. They cling to ancestral practices, cultural customs, and inherited beliefs without questioning their validity. Their criterion is not truth but familiarity.",
    "˹Would they still do so,˺ even if their forefathers had ˹absolutely˺ no understanding or guidance?": "Allah challenges this blind following. What if their ancestors had no understanding ('aql) and no guidance (huda)? Following people who themselves were lost makes no sense. Tradition alone does not validate beliefs—truth does. Every generation is responsible for seeking truth, not merely inheriting errors."
  },
  171: {
    "The example of the disbelievers ˹not responding to the Messenger's warning˺ is like a flock not comprehending the calls and cries of the shepherd.": "This powerful analogy compares the disbelievers to animals that hear sounds but do not understand meaning. A shepherd calls to his sheep; they hear noise but do not comprehend the words or intent. Similarly, disbelievers hear the Prophet's message but refuse to process its meaning.",
    "˹They are wilfully˺ deaf, dumb and blind": "Though they have physical senses, their spiritual faculties are disabled. They are deaf to truth, mute in acknowledging it, and blind to guidance. These are chosen disabilities—they have rendered their faculties useless through rejection.",
    "so they have no understanding.": "Because they have shut down their spiritual senses, they cannot use their intellect properly. True understanding requires open hearts and sincere seeking, which they have abandoned."
  },
  172: {
    "O believers! Eat from the good things We have provided for you.": "Now Allah addresses believers specifically (ya ayyuha alladhina amanu). They are commanded to eat from tayyibat—good, pure, wholesome provisions. Allah is the provider (razaqnakum), and believers should enjoy what He has given.",
    "And give thanks to Allah": "Gratitude (shukr) is the proper response to provision. Every meal should be accompanied by thankfulness to the One who provided it. This is expressed through saying \"Bismillah\" before eating and \"Alhamdulillah\" after.",
    "if you ˹truly˺ worship Him ˹alone˺.": "True worship of Allah includes acknowledging Him as the source of provisions. If you genuinely worship Him alone, you will be grateful to Him alone for His blessings. Ingratitude contradicts the claim of worship."
  },
  173: {
    "He has only forbidden you ˹to eat˺ carrion,": "Maytah is an animal that died without proper slaughter—whether from disease, accident, or natural death. Such meat is forbidden because of health concerns and the lack of proper slaughter invoking Allah's name.",
    "blood,": "Flowing blood (dam) is prohibited. This does not include blood that remains in meat after proper slaughter but refers to blood as a consumed substance.",
    "swine,": "Pig meat (lahm al-khinzeer) is completely forbidden. This includes all pork products regardless of how the pig was raised or slaughtered. The prohibition is categorical.",
    "and what is slaughtered in the name of any other than Allah.": "Any animal slaughtered with a name other than Allah's invoked upon it is forbidden. This includes animals sacrificed to idols, saints, or anything else. The act of slaughter must be dedicated to Allah alone.",
    "But if someone is compelled by necessity—": "Allah provides an exception: in cases of genuine necessity (idtirar), such as starvation with no lawful food available, these prohibitions may be lifted temporarily.",
    "neither driven by desire nor exceeding immediate need—": "Two conditions apply: the person must not be eating haram out of desire (baghin) for it, and must not exceed (adin) what is necessary to survive. They should eat only enough to preserve life.",
    "they will not be sinful.": "Under these conditions, consuming otherwise forbidden food carries no sin. This demonstrates Islam's practical approach: laws exist for human benefit, and life preservation takes precedence in emergencies.",
    "Surely Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "Allah is Ghafoor (forgiving) and Raheem (merciful). His laws are not meant to cause hardship. His forgiveness covers cases of genuine necessity, and His mercy is reflected in the flexibility He provides."
  },
  174: {
    "Indeed, those who hide Allah's revelations,": "This refers to religious scholars who conceal what Allah has revealed—whether about the Prophet Muhammad, rulings of the scripture, or any divine guidance. They know the truth but suppress it.",
    "trading them for a fleeting gain": "Their motive is worldly benefit—money, status, popularity, political advantage. They sell eternal truth for temporary gain. Whatever they receive is \"thamanan qaleelan\" (a small, insignificant price) compared to what they lose.",
    "consume nothing but fire into their bellies.": "The money they earn through hiding knowledge will transform into fire in their stomachs. What seemed like nourishment becomes torment. This is a vivid image of how haram earnings turn to punishment.",
    "Allah will neither speak to them on the Day of Judgment,": "Being ignored by Allah is terrifying. He will not speak to them with words of mercy or pleasure. No divine communication, no acknowledgment—complete rejection.",
    "nor will He purify them.": "Allah will not purify them from their sins or praise them in any way. They will remain stained by their corruption with no cleansing.",
    "And they will suffer a painful punishment.": "Beyond the silent rejection, they face actual painful torment. Concealing knowledge for profit results in multiple layers of punishment."
  },
  175: {
    "They are the ones who trade guidance for misguidance": "They had guidance in their possession—knowledge of truth, scripture, prophecies—and they exchanged it for misguidance. They chose to be lost rather than share the light they had.",
    "and forgiveness for punishment.": "They traded the opportunity for Allah's forgiveness for guaranteed punishment. What an irrational exchange! They gave up Paradise for Hell.",
    "How persistent are they in pursuit of the Fire!": "This exclamation expresses amazement at their stubbornness. How much patience (sabr) they have for earning Hell! If they applied the same persistence to truth, they would succeed. But they work hard toward their own destruction."
  },
  176: {
    "That is because Allah has revealed the Book in truth.": "The punishment is justified because Allah revealed the Book with truth (bil-haqq). The scripture is not ambiguous or false—it is clear truth. Those who distort or hide it cannot claim confusion as an excuse.",
    "And surely those who differ regarding it are totally engrossed in opposition.": "Those who dispute about the Book—denying parts, distorting others, fighting over interpretations for selfish purposes—are in shiqaq ba'eed (far-reaching opposition/schism). They have strayed extremely far from truth and unity."
  },
  177: {
    "Righteousness is not in turning your faces towards the east or the west.": "This verse addresses the dispute about qiblah direction. True righteousness (birr) is not merely about which direction one faces in prayer. While facing the correct qiblah is obligatory, obsessing over directions while neglecting the substance of faith misses the point. This also addresses those who thought ritual direction alone made them righteous.",
    "Rather, the righteous are those who believe in Allah,": "True birr begins with belief in Allah—proper monotheism, acknowledging His existence, names, attributes, and rights.",
    "the Last Day,": "Belief in the Day of Judgment, accountability, resurrection, Paradise, and Hell is essential. This belief shapes behavior because actions have eternal consequences.",
    "the angels,": "Belief in angels as Allah's noble servants who carry out His commands is part of complete faith.",
    "the Books,": "Belief in all divinely revealed scriptures—the Torah, Gospel, Psalms, Quran, and others—in their original, uncorrupted forms.",
    "and the prophets;": "Belief in all prophets sent by Allah, from Adam to Muhammad (peace be upon them all), without distinguishing by accepting some and rejecting others.",
    "who give charity out of their cherished wealth": "Moving from belief to action: spending money despite loving it. Giving wealth that is dear to you (ala hubbihi) demonstrates true generosity, not just giving what you do not need.",
    "to relatives, orphans, the poor, ˹needy˺ travellers, beggars, and for freeing captives;": "The recipients of charity are listed: family members in need, orphaned children, poor people, travelers who are stranded, those who ask for help, and freeing slaves or captives. This comprehensive list covers various vulnerable groups.",
    "who establish prayer,": "Prayer must be established—not just performed occasionally but maintained with regularity, proper conditions, and devotion.",
    "pay alms-tax,": "Zakah, the obligatory charity, must be paid. This purifies wealth and fulfills a community obligation.",
    "and keep the pledges they make;": "Fulfilling promises and contracts is essential. When they commit to something, they follow through. Trustworthiness is a marker of true righteousness.",
    "and who are patient in times of suffering,": "Ba'sa refers to poverty, hardship, and difficult circumstances. The righteous remain patient during financial troubles.",
    "adversity,": "Darra' refers to illness, physical pain, and personal harm. Patience during health problems and bodily suffering is required.",
    "and in ˹the heat of˺ battle.": "Heen al-ba's refers to the intensity of combat. Maintaining patience and steadfastness when facing enemies in battle is the ultimate test of resolve.",
    "It is they who are true ˹in faith˺,": "Those who combine all these elements are the sadiqoon—the truthful ones. Their faith is genuine, proven by both belief and action.",
    "and it is they who are mindful ˹of Allah˺.": "They are also the muttaqoon—those with taqwa, consciousness of Allah that leads to obeying Him and avoiding His displeasure. This comprehensive verse defines complete righteousness in Islam."
  },
  178: {
    "O believers! ˹The law of˺ retaliation is set for you in cases of murder—": "Qisas (retaliation, equal punishment) is prescribed for murder cases. The principle is equality: the punishment should match the crime. This law protects life by creating a strong deterrent.",
    "a free man for a free man, a slave for a slave, and a female for a female.": "This phrase addressed a specific pre-Islamic Arab practice where powerful tribes would demand more than equal retaliation—killing multiple people or someone of higher status to avenge their dead. Islam established equality: only the killer is accountable, regardless of social status. The mention of categories addresses the specific context while establishing the principle of equal justice.",
    "But if the offender is pardoned by the victim's guardian,": "The victim's family has the option to pardon (afw) the killer. This introduces mercy into the system. The heirs of the victim can choose forgiveness over execution.",
    "then blood-money should be decided fairly": "If pardon is granted, diyah (blood money, compensation) should be determined according to what is ma'roof (fair, customary, reasonable). The amount varies based on circumstances and is established by Islamic jurisprudence.",
    "and payment should be made courteously.": "The killer must pay the diyah with ihsan—excellence, courtesy, and good grace. No delays, no reluctance, no resentment. The payment should be made kindly and promptly.",
    "This is a concession and a mercy from your Lord.": "The option of pardon and blood money is takhfeef (lightening, relief) and rahmah (mercy) from Allah. Previous laws may have required only execution; Islam provides alternatives. This balances justice with mercy.",
    "But whoever transgresses after that will suffer a painful punishment.": "If someone accepts blood money then still seeks to harm or kill the pardoned person, they become a transgressor deserving severe punishment. Once a settlement is reached, it must be honored."
  },
  179: {
    "There is ˹security of˺ life for you in ˹the law of˺ retaliation, O people of reason,": "This profound statement explains the wisdom behind qisas. In retaliation, there is hayah (life, protection of life). How? Because knowing that murder leads to execution deters potential killers. The death penalty for murder saves lives by preventing murders. This seems paradoxical but is deeply logical—hence the address to \"people of reason\" (ulu al-albab).",
    "so that you may become mindful ˹of Allah˺.": "The purpose of this law, like all of Allah's laws, is to develop taqwa (God-consciousness). When people understand that actions have consequences and that Allah has established just systems, they become more mindful of Him and more careful in their conduct."
  },
  180: {
    "It is prescribed that when death approaches any of you—": "This verse establishes the importance of making a will before death. When a person senses death is near, they should prepare their affairs.",
    "if they leave something of value—": "If the person has khayr (wealth, property, assets) to leave behind, a will becomes important. Those with nothing to leave are not addressed by this ruling.",
    "a will should be made in favour of parents and immediate family": "The wasiyyah (bequest) should include parents and close relatives. This verse was revealed before the detailed inheritance laws of Surah An-Nisa. After those verses, the inheritance shares of parents and relatives were fixed by Allah. However, bequests remain relevant for relatives who are not heirs (such as non-Muslim relatives) or for charitable purposes. The will cannot change the fixed shares but can allocate up to one-third for others.",
    "with fairness.": "Any bequest must be bil-ma'roof—fair, reasonable, and just. One cannot use a will to harm heirs or create injustice.",
    "˹This is˺ an obligation on those who are mindful ˹of Allah˺.": "Making a fair will is an obligation (haqqan) upon the muttaqeen—those who have taqwa. Dying without proper arrangements shows neglect of this duty."
  },
  181: {
    "But whoever changes the will after hearing it,": "If witnesses or executors alter the will after the deceased has made it—changing amounts, adding beneficiaries, removing others—they commit a sin.",
    "the blame will only be on those who made the change.": "The sin falls entirely on those who tampered with the will, not on the deceased who made it in good faith. The deceased is cleared; the corruptors bear the guilt.",
    "Indeed, Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing.": "Allah hears what the deceased said and knows what the executors changed. Nothing is hidden from Him. Those who alter wills may deceive humans but cannot deceive Allah."
  },
  182: {
    "Whoever suspects an error or an injustice in the will": "If someone notices that the will contains janaf (unintentional error, bias) or ithm (intentional sin, deliberate injustice), they may intervene. Perhaps the dying person made a mistake or was unfair to some heirs.",
    "and brings about a ˹fair˺ settlement among the parties": "If this person facilitates islah (reconciliation, correction) among the affected parties—helping them reach a fair agreement that corrects the problem—they have done good.",
    "will not be sinful.": "This person bears no sin for \"changing\" the will because they are correcting an error or injustice, not corrupting a fair will. The previous verse prohibited malicious changes; this verse permits beneficial corrections.",
    "Surely Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "Allah is Ghafoor and Raheem—forgiving and merciful. He forgives honest mistakes and appreciates those who work to establish justice, even if it means adjusting the deceased's instructions."
  },
  183: {
    "O believers! Fasting is prescribed for you—": "Allah addresses the believers directly, announcing that fasting (siyam) has been made obligatory upon them. The word \"kutiba\" (prescribed/written) indicates this is a firm obligation, not optional. Fasting means abstaining from food, drink, and marital relations from dawn until sunset with the intention of worship.",
    "as it was for those before you—": "Fasting is not a new practice invented for Muslims. Previous nations and followers of earlier prophets also had fasting prescribed for them. This provides comfort—you are not alone in this obligation—and establishes fasting as a universal form of worship throughout religious history. Adam, Musa, Isa, and their followers all fasted in some form.",
    "so perhaps you will become mindful ˹of Allah˺.": "The purpose of fasting is to develop taqwa—consciousness of Allah that leads to obeying His commands and avoiding His prohibitions. Fasting trains self-discipline: if you can abstain from lawful things (food, drink) for Allah's sake, you can more easily abstain from unlawful things. Fasting purifies the soul, controls desires, and reminds us of our dependence on Allah. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"Fasting is a shield.\" (Bukhari & Muslim)"
  },
  184: {
    "˹Fast a˺ prescribed number of days.": "The fasting is for \"ayyaman ma'doodat\"—a counted, limited number of days. This refers to the month of Ramadan (29 or 30 days). It is not year-round or indefinite but a specific period, making it manageable.",
    "But whoever of you is ill or on a journey, then ˹let them fast˺ an equal number of days ˹after Ramaḍân˺.": "Allah provides exemptions showing His mercy. The sick (whose fasting would worsen their condition or delay recovery) and travelers (who face hardship) may skip fasting during Ramadan but must make up the missed days later. This flexibility prevents harm while maintaining the obligation.",
    "For those who can only fast with extreme difficulty,": "This addresses those who find fasting extremely hard—such as the elderly, chronically ill, or pregnant/nursing women who cannot make up fasts later. The phrase \"yuteequnahu\" refers to those who can barely manage it with great strain.",
    "compensation can be made by feeding a needy person ˹for every day not fasted˺.": "Instead of fasting, they pay fidyah—feeding one poor person for each day missed. This allows those unable to fast to still participate in the spirit of Ramadan through charity.",
    "But whoever volunteers to give more, it is better for them.": "If someone feeds more than one poor person per day or gives more generously, it is better for them. Extra charity brings extra reward.",
    "And to fast is better for you, if only you knew.": "Despite the exemptions, fasting itself remains superior for those who can manage it. The spiritual, physical, and psychological benefits of fasting make it the preferred option. If people truly understood fasting's benefits, they would choose it whenever possible."
  },
  185: {
    "Ramaḍân is the month in which the Quran was revealed": "This verse reveals why Ramadan is special: it is the month when the Quran began to be revealed to Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him). The first verses came down on Laylat al-Qadr (the Night of Decree) in this blessed month. This connection between Ramadan and Quran makes the month sacred.",
    "as a guide for humanity": "The Quran is \"hudan lin-nas\"—guidance for all people, not just Arabs or Muslims. It shows the path to success in this life and the next, applicable to every human being.",
    "with clear proofs of guidance and the standard ˹to distinguish between right and wrong˺.": "The Quran contains bayyinat (clear proofs, evident signs) and is a furqan (criterion distinguishing truth from falsehood, right from wrong). It leaves no confusion about what Allah wants from humanity.",
    "So whoever is present this month, let them fast.": "The ruling is clear: anyone who witnesses Ramadan—meaning they are alive and present when the month arrives—must fast. This is an obligation without ambiguity.",
    "But whoever is ill or on a journey, then ˹let them fast˺ an equal number of days ˹after Ramaḍân˺.": "The exemption is repeated for emphasis: sick and traveling people make up missed fasts later. The obligation remains but is postponed for those with valid excuses.",
    "Allah intends ease for you, not hardship,": "This is a fundamental principle of Islamic law: Allah wants yusr (ease) for His servants, not 'usr (hardship). The exemptions demonstrate this mercy. Islam's rules are designed to be manageable, not burdensome.",
    "so that you may complete the prescribed period": "The exemptions help people complete the full number of fasting days one way or another—either in Ramadan or by making up days later. The goal is that everyone fulfills the obligation.",
    "and proclaim the greatness of Allah for guiding you,": "After completing Ramadan, Muslims declare Allah's greatness (takbeer), especially on Eid. This proclamation acknowledges His guidance in prescribing this beneficial worship and enabling them to complete it.",
    "and perhaps you will be grateful.": "The ultimate outcome should be gratitude (shukr)—thankfulness to Allah for the gift of guidance, the blessing of Ramadan, and the ability to worship Him."
  },
  186: {
    "When My servants ask you ˹O Prophet˺ about Me:": "This verse came when some companions asked the Prophet whether Allah was near (so they could whisper to Him) or far (so they should call out loudly). The placement of this verse among the fasting verses is significant—Ramadan is a time of intense dua (supplication), and Allah reassures fasting believers of His nearness.",
    "I am truly near.": "Allah answers directly without saying \"say\" (qul) as in most other responses—emphasizing the intimacy and immediacy of His presence. He is qareeb—near to all His servants, hearing their prayers, aware of their conditions. This nearness is not physical but in knowledge, hearing, and response.",
    "I respond to one's prayer when they call upon Me.": "Allah promises to answer dua. \"Ujeeb\" means He responds to every prayer. This response may come in different forms: giving what was asked, giving something better, averting harm, or storing reward for the Hereafter. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"Any Muslim who makes a supplication containing nothing sinful or severing family ties, Allah will give him one of three things: He will give him what he asked, store it for him in the Hereafter, or avert equivalent harm from him.\" (Ahmad)",
    "So let them respond ˹with obedience˺ to Me": "There is a reciprocal relationship: Allah responds to our prayers, and we should respond to His commands with obedience. \"Falyastajeeboo lee\" means they should answer Allah's call by following His guidance.",
    "and believe in Me,": "Proper belief (iman) in Allah—His existence, His attributes, His promises—is the foundation for effective dua. Calling upon Allah requires believing in Him.",
    "perhaps they will be guided ˹to the Right Way˺.": "Through this combination—calling upon Allah, obeying Him, and believing in Him—people attain rushd (right guidance, maturity, righteousness). This spiritual development is the goal of the believer's relationship with Allah."
  },
  187: {
    "It has been made permissible for you to be intimate with your wives during the nights preceding the fast.": "In early Islam, marital relations were forbidden during Ramadan nights after one had slept. This was very difficult. Allah eased this ruling, making intimacy permissible throughout the night until dawn. This shows Islam's realistic approach to human needs.",
    "Your spouses are a garment for you as you are for them.": "This beautiful metaphor describes the marriage relationship. Spouses are like libaas (garments) to each other: providing covering, protection, warmth, comfort, beautification, and intimacy. Just as clothes are closest to the body, spouses are closest to each other. This mutual description emphasizes equality and reciprocity in marriage.",
    "Allah knows that you were deceiving yourselves.": "Some companions, struggling with the previous strict rules, had been intimate with their wives at night despite knowing it was prohibited after sleeping. Allah knew their struggle and weakness—\"takhtanoona anfusakum\" means they were betraying/cheating themselves by falling into what was then forbidden.",
    "So He has accepted your repentance and pardoned you.": "Allah forgave those who had slipped and accepted their repentance. This shows His mercy—rather than simply punishing, He lifted the difficult restriction and pardoned past mistakes.",
    "So now you may be intimate with them and seek what Allah has prescribed for you.": "The permission is now explicit and clear. \"Seek what Allah has prescribed\" refers to seeking children through lawful intimacy. Marriage and procreation are blessed purposes.",
    "˹You may˺ eat and drink until you see the light of dawn breaking the darkness of night,": "The time for suhoor (pre-dawn meal) extends until the \"white thread\" (light of dawn) becomes distinct from the \"black thread\" (darkness of night). This poetic description means until the first light of true dawn (fajr) appears on the horizon. The Prophet (peace be upon him) encouraged taking suhoor, saying: \"Take suhoor, for indeed there is blessing in suhoor.\" (Bukhari & Muslim)",
    "then complete the fast until nightfall.": "Once dawn begins, fasting starts and continues until \"layl\" (night)—meaning until sunset. The fast is then broken with iftar. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"When night comes from this side and day departs from this side and the sun has set, then the fasting person should break their fast.\" (Bukhari & Muslim)",
    "Do not be intimate with your spouses while you are meditating in the mosques.": "Those performing i'tikaf (spiritual retreat in the mosque, especially in the last ten days of Ramadan) must not have marital relations even at night. I'tikaf requires remaining in the mosque, and intimacy would invalidate it.",
    "These are the limits set by Allah, so do not exceed them.": "These rules are hudood Allah—boundaries set by Allah. The phrase \"la taqrabooha\" (do not approach them) means stay well away from the boundaries, not just avoid crossing them. This creates a safety margin.",
    "This is how Allah makes His revelations clear to people, so they may become mindful ˹of Him˺.": "Allah clarifies His rules so people understand and can develop taqwa. Clear guidance enables proper obedience, which builds God-consciousness."
  },
  188: {
    "Do not consume one another's wealth unjustly,": "Allah prohibits taking others' property through batil (falsehood, invalid means)—theft, fraud, cheating, gambling, interest, or any illegitimate method. \"Amwalakum baynakum\" (your wealth among yourselves) treats the community's wealth as interconnected; harming anyone's wealth affects everyone.",
    "nor deliberately bribe authorities": "\"Tudloo biha ilal-hukkam\" means casting or lowering your wealth to judges—giving bribes to officials or judges. The imagery is of lowering a bucket into a well; here it is lowering bribes to reach corrupt judges.",
    "in order to devour a portion of others' property,": "The purpose of bribery is to illegally obtain someone else's wealth. A person knows they have no legitimate claim but uses corrupt means to win a false judgment in their favor.",
    "knowing that it is a sin.": "This sin is committed knowingly (wa antum ta'lamoon). They are fully aware that the property belongs to someone else and that their claim is false. Deliberate sin with full knowledge is worse than sin from ignorance. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"Whoever takes a piece of land unjustly will be sunk into the earth on the Day of Resurrection to the depth of seven earths.\" (Bukhari & Muslim)"
  },
  189: {
    "They ask you ˹O Prophet˺ about the phases of the moon.": "People asked about the ahillah (crescents/moon phases)—why the moon changes shape throughout the month. This question could have been about astronomy, but Allah directs the answer to practical benefit.",
    "Say, \"They are a means for people to determine time and pilgrimage.\"": "The lunar phases serve as mawaqeet—time markers for people. The Islamic calendar is lunar, so the moon's phases determine months, fasting periods, Hajj times, and other religious observances. This practical purpose is more beneficial to know than astronomical details.",
    "Righteousness is not in entering your houses from the back doors.": "Some Arabs had a superstitious practice: when in ihram (pilgrimage state), they would not enter their homes through the front door but climbed over walls or entered from the back, thinking this was pious. Allah rejects this as false righteousness.",
    "Rather, righteousness is to be mindful ˹of Allah˺.": "True birr (righteousness) is taqwa—being conscious of Allah and following His commands. It is not about invented rituals or superstitions but about genuine obedience to Allah.",
    "So enter your homes through their ˹proper˺ doors,": "The simple, practical instruction: use the proper entrances. Do not invent hardships or rituals that Allah did not prescribe.",
    "and be mindful of Allah so you may be successful.": "Taqwa leads to falah (success, prosperity). Real success comes through sincere worship, not superstitious practices."
  },
  193: {
    "Fight against them ˹if they persecute you˺ until there is no more persecution,": "The objective of fighting is to end fitnah—persecution, religious oppression, and the prevention of people practicing their faith. The goal is not conquest or forced conversion but the removal of barriers to religious freedom.",
    "and ˹your˺ devotion will be to Allah ˹alone˺.": "When persecution ends, people can worship Allah freely. \"Wa yakoonad-deenu lillah\" means religion/worship will be for Allah alone, without coercion or interference. People can choose their faith without fear.",
    "If they stop ˹persecuting you˺, let there be no hostility except against the aggressors.": "If the enemy ceases hostility, Muslims must stop fighting. \"Intahaw\" (they stop) triggers the end of combat. Any further aggression is prohibited. Only active aggressors (zalimeen) may be fought; when aggression stops, so does the response."
  },
  194: {
    "˹There will be retaliation in˺ a sacred month for ˹an offence in˺ a sacred month,": "The sacred months (Dhul-Qa'dah, Dhul-Hijjah, Muharram, and Rajab) were traditionally times of truce. If enemies violate this sanctity by attacking Muslims in a sacred month, Muslims may respond in kind. The sanctity is reciprocal.",
    "and all violations will bring about retaliation.": "All hurumat (sacred things, sanctities) follow the principle of qisas (equal retaliation). If your sanctities are violated, you may respond proportionally.",
    "So, if anyone attacks you, retaliate in the same manner.": "The response must be proportional—\"bimithli\" (in the same manner/measure). Excessive retaliation is forbidden. If they killed one, you may not kill many. If they took property, you may not take more.",
    "˹But˺ be mindful of Allah,": "Even in combat and retaliation, taqwa must guide actions. Fear Allah and do not exceed limits.",
    "and know that Allah is with those mindful ˹of Him˺.": "Allah supports the muttaqeen—those who maintain God-consciousness even in difficult situations like war. His support guarantees ultimate success."
  },
  195: {
    "Spend in the cause of Allah": "Infaq (spending) in Allah's cause includes funding defense, supporting warriors, helping the poor, and all charitable expenditure for the sake of Allah.",
    "and do not let your own hands throw you into destruction ˹by withholding˺.": "\"Tahlukah\" (destruction) comes from withholding what should be spent. If Muslims fail to spend on defense, they invite military defeat. If they fail to give charity, they harm society. Stinginess leads to collective destruction. Alternatively, this warns against reckless behavior that leads to certain death without benefit.",
    "And do good, for Allah certainly loves the good-doers.": "Beyond meeting obligations, believers should excel (ihsan) in all things. Allah loves the muhsineen—those who go beyond the minimum to do excellent work in worship and dealing with others."
  },
  196: {
    "Complete the pilgrimage and minor pilgrimage for Allah.": "Once Hajj or Umrah is begun, it must be completed with all its rituals. Dedication should be purely for Allah—not for showing off, worldly recognition, or any purpose other than pleasing Allah.",
    "But if prevented ˹from proceeding˺, then ˹offer˺ whatever sacrificial animals you can afford.": "If something prevents completion—illness, enemy obstruction, or other valid excuse—the pilgrim exits ihram by offering a hadiy (sacrificial animal) according to their means. This could be a sheep, goat, cow, or camel.",
    "And do not shave your heads until the sacrificial animal reaches its destination.": "Head-shaving marks the exit from ihram and cannot be done until the sacrifice is complete. The animal must reach its place of slaughter first.",
    "But if any of you is ill or has a scalp ailment ˹requiring shaving˺, then compensate either by fasting, charity, or a sacrificial offering.": "If someone must shave their head early due to illness or head lice, they pay fidyah: either fasting three days, feeding six poor people, or offering a sacrifice. This provides flexibility for those with genuine needs.",
    "In times of peace, you may combine the pilgrimage and minor pilgrimage": "When safe to travel, performing Umrah then Hajj in the same season (tamattu') is permitted. The pilgrim exits ihram after Umrah, then re-enters for Hajj.",
    "then make the sacrificial offering you can afford.": "Those performing tamattu' must offer a sacrifice as gratitude for the convenience of combining both pilgrimages.",
    "Whoever cannot afford that ˹offering˺, let them fast three days during pilgrimage and seven after returning ˹home˺—completing ten.": "Those who cannot afford an animal fast instead: three days during Hajj (preferably before the Day of Arafah) and seven days after returning home. Total: ten days of fasting as substitute.",
    "These offerings are for those who do not live near the Sacred House.": "The tamattu' rules and sacrifice requirement apply to those coming from outside Mecca's vicinity. Residents of Mecca perform Hajj ifrad (Hajj only) without this additional sacrifice.",
    "And be mindful of Allah, and know that Allah is severe in punishment.": "Pilgrimage is serious worship requiring taqwa. Violations and negligence in Hajj face consequences. Allah is shadeedul-'iqab—severe in punishment for those who transgress."
  },
  197: {
    "˹Commitment to˺ pilgrimage is made in appointed months.": "Hajj takes place during \"ashhurun ma'loomat\"—known months: Shawwal, Dhul-Qa'dah, and the first ten days of Dhul-Hijjah. These are the designated times for entering ihram with intention for Hajj.",
    "Whoever commits to ˹performing˺ pilgrimage, let them stay away from intimate relations,": "Once in ihram for Hajj, rafath (sexual relations and explicit speech) is prohibited. This applies until completing the Hajj rites.",
    "foul language,": "Fusooq includes all sins, disobedience, and immoral behavior. A pilgrim must maintain exceptional moral conduct.",
    "and arguments during pilgrimage.": "Jidal (quarreling, arguing) must be avoided. Hajj is about peace, unity, and devotion. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"Whoever performs Hajj and does not engage in rafath or fusooq will return [free from sin] as on the day his mother bore him.\" (Bukhari & Muslim)",
    "Whatever good you do, Allah ˹fully˺ knows of it.": "Every good deed, even small ones, is recorded. Allah's knowledge is complete and encouraging—no good action is wasted.",
    "Take ˹necessary˺ provisions ˹for the journey˺—": "Pilgrims should prepare adequately for the journey with food, supplies, and money. Some early Muslims would travel without provisions, claiming trust in Allah, but this was corrected.",
    "surely the best provision is righteousness.": "While physical provisions are necessary, the most important zad (provision) is taqwa (righteousness, God-consciousness). This provision benefits in this life and carries into the Hereafter.",
    "And be mindful of Me, O people of reason!": "Allah calls upon the intelligent (ulul-albab) to exercise their reason by fearing Him. True intelligence leads to taqwa; ignoring Allah is foolishness regardless of intellectual capacity."
  },
  198: {
    "There is no blame on you for seeking the bounty of your Lord ˹during this journey˺.": "Engaging in lawful trade during Hajj is permitted. Some companions worried that buying and selling during pilgrimage was inappropriate. Allah clarified that earning halal income is not sinful. Hajj can include business activities as long as they do not compromise the worship.",
    "When you return from 'Arafât,": "Standing at Arafat on the 9th of Dhul-Hijjah is the essential pillar of Hajj. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"Hajj is Arafah.\" (Tirmidhi) After sunset, pilgrims proceed (afadtum—flow forth) toward Muzdalifah.",
    "praise Allah near the sacred place": "At Mash'ar al-Haram (Muzdalifah), pilgrims should remember Allah through dhikr, dua, and prayer. They spend the night there and pray Fajr before proceeding to Mina.",
    "and praise Him for having guided you,": "Remembrance should include gratitude for Allah's guidance—showing you the Hajj rituals, the straight path, and Islam itself.",
    "for surely before this ˹guidance˺ you were astray.": "Before Islam, the Arabs were in dalaalah (misguidance)—worshipping idols, practicing jahiliyyah customs. Allah's guidance transformed them. Hajj reminds pilgrims of this blessing of guidance."
  },
  199: {
    "Then go forth with the rest of the pilgrims.": "The Quraysh used to consider themselves superior and would not go to Arafat with common pilgrims, stopping at Muzdalifah instead. Allah commanded them to join all Muslims at Arafat and proceed equally. No one is superior in Hajj—all wear the same simple clothes and perform the same rituals.",
    "And seek Allah's forgiveness.": "Istighfar (seeking forgiveness) should accompany all Hajj rites. The pilgrimage is an opportunity for complete forgiveness of sins. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"There is no day on which Allah frees more people from Hell than the Day of Arafah.\" (Muslim)",
    "Surely Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "Allah is Ghafoor (repeatedly forgiving) and Raheem (especially merciful). His forgiveness is vast, and Hajj performed properly earns complete pardoning of past sins."
  },
  200: {
    "When you have fulfilled your sacred rites, praise Allah as you used to praise your forefathers ˹before Islam˺, or even more passionately.": "After completing the Hajj rituals, pilgrims should engage in abundant dhikr (remembrance of Allah). The pre-Islamic Arabs would gather after Hajj and boast about their ancestors' achievements. Allah redirects this energy: instead of praising your forefathers, praise Allah—and with even greater intensity. All glory belongs to Him, not to human lineages.",
    "There are some who say, \"Our Lord! Grant us ˹Your bounties˺ in this world,\"": "Some people only ask Allah for worldly things—wealth, health, status, pleasure. Their dua is limited to this temporary life.",
    "but they will have no share in the Hereafter.": "Those who only seek worldly gains, ignoring the Hereafter, will have no portion (khalaq) in Paradise. Their focus on dunya (worldly life) at the exclusion of akhirah (Hereafter) leads to eternal loss."
  },
  201: {
    "Yet there are others who say, \"Our Lord! Grant us the good of this world": "The wise believers ask for hasanah (goodness) in this world—which includes health, halal provision, beneficial knowledge, a righteous spouse, good children, and all forms of worldly blessing.",
    "and the Hereafter,": "They also ask for hasanah in the Hereafter—Paradise, Allah's pleasure, seeing His Face, and all eternal rewards.",
    "and protect us from the torment of the Fire.\"": "They seek protection from Hell's punishment. This comprehensive dua covers both positive seeking (good in both worlds) and protection from harm (Hell). The Prophet (peace be upon him) frequently made this dua, and it is recommended for Muslims to recite it often. (Bukhari & Muslim)"
  },
  202: {
    "It is they who will receive a ˹heavenly˺ reward for the good they have done.": "Those who seek both worlds with proper balance will receive their naseeb (portion) from what they earned through their good deeds and prayers. They get the best of both worlds.",
    "Surely Allah is swift in reckoning.": "Allah's hisab (accounting) is quick. He will rapidly calculate everyone's deeds and distribute rewards. The Day of Judgment, despite judging billions, will be swift for Allah. This also reminds us that the Hereafter is approaching quickly—we should prepare now."
  },
  203: {
    "And remember Allah during ˹these˺ appointed days.": "These \"ayyam ma'doodat\" (numbered days) refer to the Days of Tashreeq—11th, 12th, and 13th of Dhul-Hijjah. During these days, pilgrims stay in Mina, stone the jamarat (pillars), and engage in dhikr, especially the takbeer (Allahu Akbar) after prayers.",
    "Whoever departs swiftly on the second day is not sinful,": "Pilgrims who leave Mina on the 12th of Dhul-Hijjah (after stoning the jamarat) commit no sin. This option makes Hajj easier for those who need to leave early.",
    "neither are those who stay behind ˹till the third—seeking additional reward˺,": "Those who stay until the 13th and complete all stoning rituals also commit no sin—and they earn additional reward for the extra worship. Staying longer is better but not obligatory.",
    "so long as they are mindful ˹of their Lord˺.": "The permissibility of both options applies to those who have taqwa. The intention matters—one should choose based on capability and sincerity, not laziness or negligence.",
    "And be mindful of Allah,": "The final reminder about taqwa encapsulates all the Hajj teachings. Every ritual should be performed with God-consciousness.",
    "and know that to Him you will ˹all˺ be gathered.": "All of humanity will be gathered before Allah for judgment. Hajj is a preview of this gathering—millions from all nations, dressed simply, standing before their Lord. Let this remind us of the ultimate gathering on the Day of Resurrection."
  },
  204: {
    "There are some ˹hypocrites˺ who impress you with their views regarding worldly affairs": "Allah warns about a dangerous type of person—the eloquent hypocrite. Their speech (qawluhu) is impressive and pleasing to hear. They speak beautifully about worldly matters, appearing intelligent, concerned, and sincere. They know how to say what people want to hear.",
    "and openly call upon Allah to witness what is in their hearts,": "To make themselves more convincing, they invoke Allah as witness to their sincerity. They swear by Allah that they truly believe, that their intentions are pure. This religious posturing makes them appear devout and trustworthy.",
    "yet they are your worst adversaries.": "Despite their pleasant words and religious oaths, they are \"aladdul-khisam\"—the most stubborn and fierce opponents. Their enmity is the most dangerous because it is hidden behind a mask of friendship. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"The most hated person to Allah is the most quarrelsome.\" (Bukhari) This description is said to refer to a specific hypocrite, Al-Akhnas ibn Shurayq, but applies to all who share these traits."
  },
  205: {
    "And when they leave ˹you˺, they strive throughout the land to spread mischief in it": "When these hypocrites leave the Prophet's presence—or when they gain authority—they work actively to cause fasad (corruption, mischief). Their true nature emerges away from public scrutiny. They undermine society through their actions.",
    "and destroy crops and cattle.": "Their corruption affects both agriculture (harth—crops, cultivation) and livestock (nasl—offspring, cattle). These represent the foundations of livelihood and community welfare. Destroying them harms everyone. This could be literal destruction or metaphorical—ruining livelihoods, breaking families, corrupting future generations.",
    "Allah does not like mischief.": "Allah explicitly declares His dislike for fasad (corruption). This simple statement carries enormous weight: those who spread corruption are earning Allah's displeasure. Since Allah loves justice, mercy, and righteousness, corruption opposes everything He loves."
  },
  206: {
    "When it is said to them, \"Fear Allah,\"": "When someone advises them to have taqwa (God-consciousness), to repent and reform, to fear Allah's punishment—this good advice triggers an ugly response.",
    "pride carries them off to sin.": "Instead of accepting the advice humbly, pride (izzah) seizes them. Their arrogance leads them deeper into sin rather than away from it. Their ego cannot tolerate being corrected. Pride is the barrier that prevents repentance.",
    "Hell will be their proper place.": "\"Fa hasbuhu jahannam\"—Hell is sufficient for them, meaning it is their fitting destination. Their arrogance and corruption earn them this outcome.",
    "What an evil place to rest!": "\"Bi'sal-mihad\"—what a terrible resting place! Mihad usually means a bed or cradle—a place of rest and comfort. Hell is sarcastically called their \"resting place,\" highlighting the horror: instead of rest, they will have torment."
  },
  207: {
    "And there are those who would dedicate their lives to Allah's pleasure.": "In contrast to the hypocrites, there are believers who \"yashri nafsahu\"—sell/trade themselves. They give everything, including their lives, seeking Allah's pleasure (mardaat-illah). They sacrifice worldly comforts, risk danger, and devote themselves entirely to Allah. This verse reportedly refers to Suhayb ar-Rumi, who gave up all his wealth to escape Mecca and migrate to Madinah, but it applies to all sincere believers willing to sacrifice for Allah.",
    "And Allah is Ever Gracious to ˹His˺ servants.": "Allah is Ra'oof—extremely compassionate, gentle, and kind to His servants. Those who sacrifice for Him will never lose. His compassion ensures that every sacrifice is rewarded abundantly. The contrast is stark: hypocrites earn Hell; sincere believers earn Allah's special compassion."
  },
  208: {
    "O believers! Enter into Islam wholeheartedly": "Allah commands believers to enter into \"as-silm\" (Islam/peace/submission) \"kaffah\" (completely, entirely, wholly). This means accepting Islam in its totality—not picking and choosing which parts to follow. Some early converts from Judaism wanted to maintain some Jewish practices; this verse clarifies that Islam must be accepted fully. One cannot be partially Muslim, following prayer but ignoring charity, or fasting but engaging in prohibited transactions.",
    "and do not follow Satan's footsteps.": "Again the warning about \"khutuwat ash-shaytan\" (Satan's footsteps). Satan leads people astray gradually—one small step at a time. First a small compromise, then another, until one is far from the straight path. Complete submission to Islam is the protection against this gradual deviation.",
    "Surely he is your sworn enemy.": "Satan is an open, declared enemy. He has clearly announced his intention to mislead humanity. Treating him as anything less than a mortal enemy is dangerous foolishness. Full commitment to Islam is the best defense against his attacks."
  },
  209: {
    "If you falter after receiving the clear proofs,": "\"Zalaltum\" means to slip, stumble, or deviate. If believers slip into error after receiving bayyinat (clear proofs, evident guidance), they should know the consequences. The proofs have been made clear; deviation afterward is inexcusable.",
    "then know that Allah is indeed Almighty, All-Wise.": "Allah is Azeez (Almighty, Powerful, Invincible) and Hakeem (All-Wise). His might means He can punish those who deviate, and His wisdom means His judgment is always correct. This combination is a warning: Allah has the power to punish and the wisdom to know who deserves it."
  },
  210: {
    "Are they waiting for Allah ˹Himself˺ to come to them in the shade of clouds, along with the angels?": "This rhetorical question challenges the disbelievers: What are they waiting for? Are they delaying belief until the Day of Judgment itself, when Allah's command comes and the angels descend? By then, it will be too late for faith to benefit them. Allah's \"coming\" here refers to His command and judgment coming, as understood in a manner befitting His majesty.",
    "˹If He did˺, then the matter would be settled ˹at once˺.": "When that Day comes, \"qudiya al-amr\"—the matter is decided, finished, concluded. No more chances for repentance, no more time for faith. Everything will be final. The time for action is now, not when judgment arrives.",
    "And to Allah ˹all˺ matters will be returned ˹for judgment˺.": "All affairs ultimately return to Allah for final judgment. Nothing escapes His reckoning. Every deed, intention, and choice will be brought before Him."
  },
  211: {
    "Ask the Children of Israel how many clear signs We have given them.": "The Prophet is told to ask the Israelites to count the innumerable clear signs they received: miracles through Musa, parting of the sea, manna and quails, the Torah, prophets after prophets. Their history is full of bayyinat (clear signs).",
    "And whoever trades Allah's favour—after receiving it—˹for disbelief˺": "Despite receiving countless blessings, some exchanged Allah's favor (His guidance, signs, blessings) for disbelief. Trading ni'mah (divine favor) for kufr (disbelief) is the worst exchange imaginable.",
    "should know that Allah is indeed severe in punishment.": "Allah is shadeedul-'iqab—severe in punishment. Those who reject His blessings face serious consequences. This warning applies to everyone who receives guidance but chooses to reject it."
  },
  212: {
    "The life of this world has been made appealing to the disbelievers,": "Worldly life (hayat ad-dunya) has been beautified and made attractive to those who disbelieve. They become captivated by material pleasures, wealth, status, and temporary enjoyments. This beautification is a test—it distracts them from the Hereafter.",
    "and they mock the believers.": "Because disbelievers are focused on worldly success, they often ridicule believers who may be poorer or less powerful in worldly terms. They cannot understand why anyone would sacrifice worldly gain for something unseen.",
    "Those who are mindful ˹of Allah˺ will rank above them on the Day of Judgment.": "The tables will turn completely. The muttaqeen (God-conscious believers) will be elevated above the disbelievers on the Day of Judgment. Worldly rankings are temporary and often inverted in the Hereafter.",
    "And Allah provides for whoever He wills without limit.": "Allah's provision (rizq) is given without hisab (accounting/limit) to whomever He wills. In this world, He may give abundantly to disbelievers as a test; in the Hereafter, He gives limitlessly to believers. His provision cannot be calculated or restricted."
  },
  213: {
    "Humanity had once been one community ˹of believers before they lost faith˺.": "In the beginning, humanity was united upon one way—the natural monotheism (fitrah). Some scholars say this refers to the time of Adam, others to the period before significant deviation occurred. Eventually, people diverged into different beliefs and practices.",
    "Then Allah raised prophets as deliverers of good news and as warners,": "To guide humanity back, Allah sent prophets. They served as mubashireen (bringers of good news about Paradise and rewards) and mundhireen (warners about Hell and punishment). Both functions are necessary—hope and fear work together to motivate righteousness.",
    "and revealed to them the Scriptures in truth to judge among people regarding their disputes.": "Along with prophets came divine scriptures containing truth (bil-haqq). These books provided objective standards to resolve disputes. Without revelation, people have no authoritative reference point for truth.",
    "And no one disputed the Scriptures except the very people who received them after clear proofs had come to them—out of jealousy.": "Ironically, the disputes about scripture came from those who received it, not outsiders. After clear proofs (bayyinat) came to them, they still disagreed—not from confusion but from baghyan (jealousy, rivalry, transgression). Envy and selfish interests caused them to reject clear truth.",
    "Then Allah, by His grace, has guided the believers to the truth regarding those disputes.": "Despite all the disputes, Allah guided sincere believers to the truth. By His permission and grace, those who genuinely sought truth found it. The believers were guided to the correct position on matters others disputed.",
    "And Allah guides whoever He wills to the Straight Path.": "Guidance is ultimately from Allah. He guides whomever He wills to the sirat al-mustaqeem. Human effort matters, but divine guidance is essential. Those who sincerely seek truth receive Allah's guidance."
  },
  214: {
    "Do you think you will be admitted into Paradise without being tested like those before you?": "This rhetorical question challenges any assumption that Paradise is easily attained. Entry into Jannah requires passing tests. Previous believers faced severe trials; current believers cannot expect exemption.",
    "They were afflicted with suffering and adversity": "Past believers experienced ba'sa (poverty, material hardship) and darra (illness, physical harm, personal loss). Life was not comfortable for the righteous of previous generations.",
    "and were so ˹violently˺ shaken": "They were \"zulzilu\"—shaken violently, tested to their core. This shaking was not gentle; it was severe enough to test their very foundations.",
    "that ˹even˺ the Messenger and the believers with him cried out, \"When will Allah's help come?\"": "The trials were so intense that even the prophets and the strongest believers wondered when Allah's help would arrive. This shows the severity of tests faced by previous generations—not to express doubt, but to plead for relief.",
    "Indeed, Allah's help is ˹always˺ near.": "The answer comes immediately: Allah's help is qareeb (near). No matter how dark the situation, divine assistance is close. This gives hope to all believers facing difficulty. The darkest hour comes just before dawn, and Allah's victory comes when people have been tested to their limits."
  },
  215: {
    "They ask you ˹O Prophet in˺ what ˹way˺ they should donate.": "The companions asked the Prophet what they should spend in charity. This shows their eagerness to give—they wanted guidance on how to give properly.",
    "Say, \"Whatever donations you give are for parents, relatives, orphans, the poor, and ˹needy˺ travellers.": "The answer prioritizes recipients: parents come first (even if wealthy, they deserve gifts and support), then relatives, then orphans who have no providers, then the poor (masakeen), then travelers stranded without resources. This order establishes family as the first priority for charity, then expanding circles of community need.",
    "Whatever good you do is certainly well known to Allah.\"": "Allah is Aleem (fully knowing) of every good deed. Nothing is hidden from Him. This encourages charity by assuring that no good act is wasted or unnoticed."
  },
  216: {
    "Fighting has been made obligatory upon you ˹believers˺, though you dislike it.": "Qital (fighting in Allah's cause) is prescribed (kutiba), making it obligatory when necessary. Allah acknowledges human nature: fighting is kurhun (disliked, hateful) to people. No sane person enjoys warfare, danger, and bloodshed. But sometimes it is necessary for defense, justice, and protecting the community.",
    "Perhaps you dislike something which is good for you": "Here is a profound wisdom: our feelings about something do not determine its true value. We may hate something that is actually beneficial—like bitter medicine that heals, or difficult training that strengthens, or warfare that protects the community and establishes justice.",
    "and like something which is bad for you.": "Conversely, we may love something that harms us—like excessive indulgence, comfort that weakens, or avoiding necessary hardship.",
    "Allah knows and you do not know.": "Allah's knowledge is complete; ours is limited. He knows the outcomes we cannot foresee. This is why following His guidance—even when it contradicts our preferences—is wise. Trust in Allah's wisdom is essential for believers."
  },
  217: {
    "They ask you ˹O Prophet˺ about fighting in the sacred months.": "The Quraysh criticized Muslims for a military encounter that occurred during a sacred month when a Muslim expedition killed an enemy. The sacred months traditionally prohibited warfare.",
    "Say, \"Fighting during these months is a great sin.": "Allah acknowledges that fighting in the sacred months is a serious (kabeer) sin. The sanctity of these months is confirmed.",
    "But hindering ˹others˺ from the Path of Allah, rejecting Him, and expelling the worshippers from the Sacred Mosque is ˹a˺ greater ˹sin˺ in the sight of Allah.": "However, the Quraysh's crimes are far greater: blocking people from Islam (sadd 'an sabeelillah), disbelief in Allah, and expelling Muslims from Mecca (the Sacred Mosque was their rightful home too). These ongoing crimes outweigh the single incident in the sacred month.",
    "For persecution is far worse than killing.": "Fitnah (religious persecution, oppression, turning people from their faith) is \"akbar min al-qatl\"—worse than killing. Killing ends physical life; fitnah destroys spiritual life. The Quraysh's systematic persecution of Muslims was a greater crime than the accidental sacred-month incident.",
    "And they will not stop fighting you until they turn you away from your faith—if they can.": "The enemy's goal is clear: they will keep fighting until they force Muslims to abandon Islam. This is their unwavering objective. Believers should understand what is at stake.",
    "And whoever among you renounces their own faith and dies a disbeliever,": "If someone apostatizes under this pressure—leaves Islam and dies in that state of disbelief—serious consequences follow.",
    "their deeds will become void in this life and in the Hereafter.": "Their good deeds are \"habitat\"—nullified, cancelled, wasted. Neither worldly benefit nor afterlife reward remains. Apostasy that ends in death upon disbelief erases everything.",
    "It is they who will be the residents of the Fire. They will be there forever.": "Such people become permanent inhabitants of Hell. This severe warning emphasizes the importance of maintaining faith under all circumstances."
  },
  218: {
    "Surely those who have believed, emigrated, and struggled in the Way of Allah—": "This verse honors three types of righteous action: iman (genuine belief), hijrah (emigration for Allah's sake, leaving home and comfort for faith), and jihad (striving/struggling in Allah's path through various means including defense of the community).",
    "they can hope for Allah's mercy.": "These believers \"yarjuna\"—they have legitimate hope for Allah's mercy. Their sacrifices earn them the right to expect divine reward. This hope is based on action, not wishful thinking.",
    "And Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "Allah is Ghafoor (forgiving, covering sins) and Raheem (merciful, blessing with good). For those who believe, emigrate, and strive, Allah's forgiveness and mercy are assured."
  },
  219: {
    "They ask you ˹O Prophet˺ about intoxicants and gambling.": "Companions asked about khamr (wine, intoxicants) and maysir (gambling). This was before the final prohibition, during the gradual process of weaning society off these practices.",
    "Say, \"There is great evil in both, as well as some benefit for people—": "Allah acknowledges reality: both have some benefits. Wine had trade value, social functions, and some perceived medical uses. Gambling redistributed wealth and created excitement. Islam does not deny these worldly benefits.",
    "but the evil outweighs the benefit.\"": "However, the sin (ithm) in both is greater than any benefit. Intoxicants destroy minds, families, and health. Gambling creates addiction, enmity, and financial ruin. The harms clearly outweigh any benefits. This verse began preparing hearts for the eventual complete prohibition that came later in Surah Al-Ma'idah (5:90-91).",
    "They ˹also˺ ask you what they should donate. Say, \"Whatever you can spare.\"": "Another question about charity: how much to give? The answer is \"al-'afw\"—the surplus, what is beyond your needs, what you can comfortably spare. This moderate approach prevents both stinginess and harmful excess.",
    "This is how Allah makes His revelations clear to you ˹believers˺, so perhaps you may reflect": "Allah clarifies guidance so people can reflect (tatafakkaroon). These rulings are not arbitrary but invite contemplation on their wisdom."
  },
  220: {
    "upon this world and the Hereafter.": "The reflection should encompass both dunya and akhirah. Islamic rulings consider benefits in both dimensions of existence.",
    "And they ask you concerning orphans.": "Another question about orphans. After verses warning against consuming orphans' wealth, some guardians became so afraid they completely separated orphans' food and property from their own, which created hardship.",
    "Say, \"Improving their condition is best.": "The priority is islah (improvement, reform) for the orphans. Whatever arrangement best serves their welfare is the right approach.",
    "And if you partner with them, they are bonded with you ˹in faith˺.": "If you mix your affairs with theirs—living together, sharing food and resources—there is no problem because they are your brothers in faith. Treating them like family is actually good, not problematic.",
    "And Allah knows who intends harm and who intends good.": "Allah distinguishes between al-mufsid (one who intends corruption, wants to exploit orphans) and al-muslih (one who intends improvement, genuinely cares for orphans). Intentions matter, and Allah knows them even if actions look similar externally.",
    "Had Allah willed, He could have made it difficult for you.": "Allah could have imposed strict, burdensome rules about orphan management that would make guardianship extremely difficult. His laws are merciful and practical.",
    "Surely Allah is Almighty, All-Wise.": "Allah is Azeez (powerful enough to impose hard rules) and Hakeem (wise enough to make appropriate, manageable rules). His legislation reflects both power and wisdom."
  },
  221: {
    "Do not marry polytheistic women until they believe;": "Marriage to mushrikāt (polytheist women—those who associate partners with Allah) is prohibited until they accept Islam. This includes idol-worshippers and pagans. However, People of the Book (Jews and Christians) have different rulings mentioned elsewhere in the Quran, where Muslim men may marry chaste women from among them (Quran 5:5).",
    "for a believing slave-woman is better than a free polytheist, even though she may look pleasant to you.": "A believing woman who is a slave has more value in Allah's sight than a free polytheist woman, regardless of how attractive or wealthy the polytheist woman might be. Faith is the most important quality in choosing a spouse. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"A woman is married for four things: her wealth, her lineage, her beauty, and her religion. Choose the one who is religious, may your hands be rubbed with dust [i.e., may you prosper].\" (Bukhari & Muslim)",
    "And do not marry your women to polytheistic men until they believe,": "Muslim women are forbidden from marrying mushrik (polytheist) men. This ruling is absolute—there are no exceptions. Unlike men, who may marry from People of the Book, Muslim women cannot marry non-Muslim men of any category.",
    "for a believing slave-man is better than a free polytheist, even though he may look pleasant to you.": "A male slave who is a believer is superior to a free polytheist man, regardless of the latter's appearance, status, or wealth. The criterion is faith. When Fatimah bint Qays asked the Prophet about marriage proposals, he guided her based on the men's character and faith, not their worldly status. (Muslim)",
    "They invite ˹you˺ to the Fire": "Polytheists, through their beliefs and practices, lead toward Hell. Living with a polytheist spouse creates constant spiritual danger—exposure to false beliefs, practices that contradict Islam, and raising children in confusion about faith.",
    "while Allah invites ˹you˺ to Paradise and forgiveness by His grace.": "In contrast, Allah invites to eternal success and His forgiveness. Marrying a believer supports your journey to Paradise; marrying a polytheist endangers it.",
    "He makes His revelations clear to the people so perhaps they will be mindful.": "Allah clarifies these rulings so people can remember and reflect (yatadhakkaroon). Understanding the wisdom behind marriage restrictions should lead to compliance and gratitude."
  },
  222: {
    "They ask you ˹O Prophet˺ about menstruation.": "Companions asked about the ruling regarding women during their monthly cycles (maheed). Different cultures had various taboos; Islam came to clarify the matter.",
    "Say, \"Beware of its harm!": "Menstruation is described as adha (harm, hurt, discomfort). This acknowledges the physical and emotional challenges women experience during this time. It is not impurity in the sense of being spiritually dirty, but a natural bodily process that requires special consideration.",
    "So keep away, and do not have intercourse with your wives during their monthly cycles until they are purified.": "Sexual intercourse is prohibited during menstruation. The phrase \"keep away\" (i'tazilu) means avoid sexual relations specifically, not abandoning or isolating women entirely. Other physical intimacy is permissible. The prohibition continues until they are \"purified\" (yathurna)—meaning until menstruation ends.",
    "When they purify themselves, then you may approach them in the manner specified by Allah.": "After menstruation ends and women perform ghusl (ritual bathing for purification), normal marital relations may resume. \"In the manner specified by Allah\" means in the lawful way—through the vagina, which is the natural place for intercourse as indicated in the next verse.",
    "Surely Allah loves those who always turn to Him in repentance": "Allah loves the tawwabeen—those who frequently repent. This includes those who repent from violating these marital boundaries and any other sins. Frequent repentance is a characteristic of believers.",
    "and those who purify themselves.": "Allah also loves the mutatahhireen—those who maintain physical and spiritual cleanliness. This includes performing proper purification rituals and avoiding spiritual and physical impurities."
  },
  223: {
    "Your wives are like farmland for you,": "This metaphor (harthun lakum) compares wives to farmland where seeds are planted. Just as farmland produces crops, wives bear children. The comparison emphasizes fertility, cultivation with care, and the productive purpose of marital relations. It is a respectful metaphor highlighting the nurturing aspect of the relationship.",
    "so approach them ˹consensually˺ as you please.": "\"Anna shi'tum\" (how/when you wish) means husbands may approach their wives in various ways and times, but always through the natural place (the vagina) as indicated by the farmland metaphor and the previous verse. This verse was revealed to clarify that various positions during intercourse are permissible, contrary to some Jewish teachings that restricted positions. However, anal intercourse remains absolutely prohibited in Islam. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"Do not approach women through the anus.\" (Ahmad, Tirmidhi)",
    "And send forth something good for yourselves.": "Before engaging in intimacy, send forth good deeds—this includes saying bismillah, making dua for righteous offspring, and ensuring mutual consent and kindness. The Prophet (peace be upon him) taught: \"If anyone of you intends to have intercourse with his wife, let him say: 'Bismillah, Allahumma jannibna ash-shaytana wa jannib ash-shaytana ma razaqtana' (In the name of Allah, O Allah, keep us away from Satan and keep Satan away from what You provide us).\" (Bukhari & Muslim)",
    "Be mindful of Allah,": "Even in intimate moments, maintain consciousness of Allah. Understand that marital relations are worship when done within Islamic boundaries and with proper intention.",
    "and know that you will meet Him.": "Remember that you will stand before Allah and be accountable for how you treated your spouse and whether you observed His limits in marital relations.",
    "And give good news to the believers.": "The believers who follow these guidelines receive good news—of righteous children, blessed marriages, and Allah's pleasure."
  },
  224: {
    "Do not use Allah's Name in your oaths as an excuse for not doing good,": "Do not make Allah's name an obstacle ('urdah—barrier, impediment) by swearing oaths that prevent you from doing good deeds. For example, if you swear \"By Allah, I will never speak to that person,\" and later reconciliation would be good, your oath should not prevent reconciliation.",
    "not guarding against evil,": "Your oaths should not become excuses for avoiding taqwa (avoiding sins and fulfilling obligations).",
    "or not making peace between people.": "If making peace (islah) between disputing parties is needed but you swore not to get involved, your oath should not prevent this good deed. Breaking such an oath and paying kaffarah (expiation) is better than using the oath to avoid righteousness.",
    "And Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing.": "Allah hears all oaths and knows the intentions behind them. He knows when oaths are used as legitimate commitments versus when they become barriers to good."
  },
  225: {
    "Allah will not hold you accountable for unintentional oaths,": "Laghw (unintentional, casual, slip-of-the-tongue oaths) do not require accountability. For example, if someone habitually says \"By Allah\" in normal speech without intending to swear formally, or if they swear thinking something is true but are mistaken, there is no sin or expiation required.",
    "but for what you intended in your hearts.": "Allah holds accountable for deliberate oaths—those made with intention and seriousness. The heart's intention determines the oath's binding nature.",
    "And Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Forbearing.": "Allah is Ghafoor (forgiving unintentional mistakes) and Haleem (forbearing, not quick to punish). His forbearance means He gives time for repentance and does not immediately punish errors."
  },
  226: {
    "Those who swear not to have intercourse with their wives must wait for four months.": "This addresses eela'—when a husband vows not to have sexual relations with his wife. In pre-Islamic times, men would take such vows to harm their wives without divorcing them, leaving women in limbo. Islam sets a limit: four months. After this period, the husband must either resume relations or grant divorce.",
    "If they change their mind, then Allah is certainly All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "If within the four months the husband breaks his vow and resumes marital relations (after paying kaffarah for breaking the oath if it was a formal oath), Allah forgives him. Resuming the relationship is encouraged as it is better for all parties."
  },
  227: {
    "But if they settle on divorce,": "If after four months the husband decides ('azamu) to proceed with divorce rather than resume relations, this is his right.",
    "then Allah is indeed All-Hearing, All-Knowing.": "Allah hears the pronouncement of divorce and knows the reasons and circumstances. He is fully aware of whether the decision is just or oppressive."
  },
  228: {
    "Divorced women must wait three monthly cycles ˹before they can remarry˺.": "After divorce (first or second revocable divorce, not the third final one), women must observe 'iddah—a waiting period of three quru' (menstrual cycles or periods of purity between menstruation, according to different scholarly opinions). This waiting period serves multiple purposes: ensuring the womb is empty (no pregnancy), allowing time for possible reconciliation, and maintaining dignity.",
    "It is not lawful for them to conceal what Allah has created in their wombs,": "Women must not hide pregnancy if it exists. Concealing pregnancy during 'iddah is a serious sin because it affects legal rights, inheritance, lineage, and potential reconciliation. Honesty is required from those who truly believe.",
    "if they ˹truly˺ believe in Allah and the Last Day.": "Belief in Allah and accountability on the Day of Judgment should prevent such deception. True faith produces honesty and integrity.",
    "And their husbands reserve the right to take them back within that period if they desire reconciliation.": "During the 'iddah, husbands have the right to revoke the divorce and resume the marriage without needing a new contract or dowry. This right exists if reconciliation (islah) is the intention—not to harm or play games with the wife.",
    "Women have rights similar to those of men equitably,": "Women have rights upon their husbands just as husbands have rights upon their wives. These rights should be fulfilled bil-ma'roof (equitably, fairly, according to what is good and recognized). This is a fundamental statement of gender equity in mutual obligations.",
    "although men have a degree ˹of responsibility˺ above them.": "Men have a darajah (degree, level) of added responsibility and authority in the family structure. This is not superiority in worth or spirituality but in functional leadership and accountability. Men are responsible for financial support, protection, and being the head of the household—with these responsibilities come authority and final decision-making in areas of disagreement. This structure is based on men's obligations, not oppression of women.",
    "And Allah is Almighty, All-Wise.": "Allah is Azeez (powerful, invincible—His rulings cannot be challenged) and Hakeem (All-Wise—His laws are perfectly designed for human welfare). The balance of rights and responsibilities reflects divine wisdom."
  },
  229: {
    "Divorce may be retracted twice,": "A man may pronounce divorce twice and still retain the right to revoke it during the 'iddah. These are the first and second divorces. After each, reconciliation is possible during the waiting period.",
    "then the husband must retain ˹his wife˺ with honour or separate ˹from her˺ with grace.": "After the second divorce and reconciliation (or when contemplating the third), the husband faces a clear choice: either keep the wife with imsak bil-ma'roof (retaining honorably, treating well) or grant tasreeh bil-ihsan (release with excellence, making separation easy and dignified). There is no room for harmful, indecisive, or abusive treatment.",
    "It is not lawful for husbands to take back anything of the dowry given to their wives,": "Men cannot reclaim any part of the mahr (dowry) they paid. The dowry is the wife's property. Taking it back is forbidden even if the marriage did not work out.",
    "unless the couple fears not being able to keep within the limits of Allah.": "An exception exists if both spouses fear they cannot maintain Allah's boundaries—meaning the relationship has deteriorated to the point where they might sin grievously (through hatred, abuse, or transgression).",
    "So if you fear they will not be able to keep within the limits of Allah, there is no blame if the wife compensates the husband to obtain divorce.": "In such cases, khul' (divorce initiated by the wife through compensation) is permitted. The wife may return the dowry or pay compensation to obtain release from an unbearable marriage. This gives women an exit from harmful situations.",
    "These are the limits set by Allah, so do not transgress them.": "All these divorce rulings are hudood Allah (Allah's boundaries). They must be respected and not exceeded.",
    "And whoever transgresses the limits of Allah, they are the ˹true˺ wrongdoers.": "Those who violate these boundaries—by taking back dowries unjustly, harming wives, or abusing divorce procedures—are the zalimoon (wrongdoers, oppressors) who wrong their own souls."
  },
  230: {
    "So if a husband divorces his wife ˹three times˺,": "If the husband pronounces the third and final divorce, the relationship is completely severed. This is talaq ba'in kubra—the major irrevocable divorce.",
    "then it is not lawful for him to remarry her": "After the third divorce, the ex-husband cannot simply remarry his ex-wife. She is permanently forbidden to him unless specific conditions are met.",
    "until after she has married another man and then is divorced.": "The only way remarriage becomes possible is if the ex-wife genuinely marries another man (not as a trick or arrangement), consummates that marriage, and then is naturally divorced or widowed from that second husband. Only then can the original couple consider remarrying. This severe restriction discourages frivolous use of triple divorce. The practice of tahleel (marrying someone temporarily just to make the original wife lawful again) is condemned by the Prophet (peace be upon him) who cursed both the one who marries for this purpose and the one for whom it is done. (Ibn Majah)",
    "Then it is permissible for them to reunite,": "After the intervening marriage ends naturally, the original couple may remarry if they both wish.",
    "as long as they feel they are able to maintain the limits of Allah.": "Remarriage should only occur if both believe they can now maintain Allah's boundaries—meaning they have matured, resolved previous issues, and can have a healthy relationship.",
    "These are the limits set by Allah, which He makes clear for people of knowledge.": "These detailed rulings are Allah's boundaries, made clear for those who have knowledge ('ilm) and seek to understand. Scholars and thoughtful believers recognize the wisdom in these regulations."
  },
  231: {
    "When you divorce women and they have ˹almost˺ reached the end of their waiting period,": "As the 'iddah approaches its conclusion, the husband must make a decision. This is the critical moment when reconciliation is still possible.",
    "either retain them honourably or let them go honourably.": "The two honorable options: retain (revoke the divorce) with good treatment, or release (let the divorce finalize) with dignity. Both must be done bil-ma'roof (honorably, fairly).",
    "But do not retain them ˹only˺ to harm them ˹or˺ to take advantage ˹of them˺.": "It is forbidden to revoke divorce with the intention of harming the wife—for example, taking her back just to abuse her, or repeatedly divorcing and revoking to keep her in endless limbo. This cruel game is explicitly prohibited.",
    "Whoever does that surely wrongs his own soul.": "Such abusive behavior harms the perpetrator's own soul. He damages himself spiritually and earns sin.",
    "Do not take Allah's revelations lightly.": "Do not treat Allah's laws (ayat) as a joke or something to manipulate. These are serious divine commands that must be respected.",
    "Remember Allah's favours upon you as well as the Book and wisdom He has sent down for your guidance.": "Recall Allah's blessings—He gave you guidance through the Quran and the Prophet's wisdom (Sunnah). These laws are blessings designed for your benefit, not burdens to evade.",
    "Be mindful of Allah,": "Maintain taqwa in all dealings, especially the vulnerable situation of divorce where oppression is easy.",
    "and know that Allah has ˹perfect˺ knowledge of all things.": "Allah knows every intention, every act of oppression, every manipulation. Nothing is hidden from His knowledge. This awareness should prevent wrongdoing."
  },
  232: {
    "When you have divorced women and they have reached the end of their waiting period,": "After the 'iddah is complete and divorce is final, women are free to remarry.",
    "do not prevent them from re-marrying their ex-husbands": "If a divorced woman and her ex-husband both wish to reconcile and remarry (after the waiting period, requiring a new contract), guardians must not prevent this reunion. The phrase \"la ta'duloohunna\" (do not prevent them) addresses male guardians (fathers, brothers) who sometimes blocked remarriage out of pride or stubbornness.",
    "if they come to an honourable agreement.": "If both parties agree to reunite bil-ma'roof (honorably, with good intentions and proper treatment), no one should obstruct this. This verse was revealed when a woman wanted to remarry her ex-husband after 'iddah, but her brother prevented it.",
    "This is enjoined on whoever has faith in Allah and the Last Day.": "This instruction applies to all who truly believe. Blocking a lawful, desired marriage contradicts faith and accountability.",
    "This is purer and more dignifying for you.": "Allowing people their freedom in these matters is azka (purer spiritually) and athar (cleaner, more dignifying morally). Controlling and manipulating others corrupts relationships and hearts.",
    "Allah knows and you do not know.": "Allah knows what is best for everyone involved. Human judgment is limited; trust Allah's wisdom in these rulings."
  },
  233: {
    "˹Divorced˺ mothers will breastfeed their offspring for two whole years,": "Mothers (including divorced ones) should nurse their children for hawlayn kamilayn (two complete years). This is the recommended duration for complete breastfeeding benefits.",
    "for those who wish to complete the nursing ˹of their child˺.": "The two years applies to those who want to complete the full nursing period. Weaning earlier by mutual agreement is permissible (as stated later in the verse).",
    "The child's father will provide reasonable maintenance and clothing for the mother ˹during that period˺.": "The father is obligated to provide the nursing mother with food (rizq) and clothing (kiswah) bil-ma'roof (reasonably, fairly, according to his means). This applies even if they are divorced—he supports her nursing work.",
    "No one will be charged with more than they can bear.": "Allah does not burden anyone beyond their capacity (wus'). A poor man is not required to provide like a wealthy one; obligations match capabilities.",
    "No mother or father should be made to suffer for their child.": "Neither parent should harm the other using the child as leverage. A mother should not refuse nursing to hurt the father; a father should not withhold support to hurt the mother. The child's welfare comes first.",
    "The ˹father's˺ heirs are under the same obligation.": "If the father dies, his heirs (those who will inherit from him) must continue supporting the child's nursing and maintenance. The responsibility transfers to those benefiting from his estate.",
    "But if both sides decide—after mutual consultation and consent—to wean a child, then there is no blame on them.": "If parents mutually agree (taradun—mutual consent) after consultation (tashawar) to wean before two years, this is permissible. Both conditions—mutual agreement and consultation about the child's best interest—are required.",
    "And if you decide to have your children nursed by a wet-nurse,": "Hiring another woman to nurse the child is permissible if needed or desired.",
    "it is permissible as long as you pay fairly.": "The wet-nurse must be paid appropriately (bil-ma'roof) for her service. Fair compensation for labor is required.",
    "Be mindful of Allah,": "In all these arrangements involving children, nursing, and finances, maintain taqwa.",
    "and know that Allah is All-Seeing of what you do.": "Allah sees how parents treat each other and their children. He observes whether they act justly or harm each other. This awareness should guide behavior."
  },
  234: {
    "As for those of you who die and leave widows behind,": "This addresses the situation of widows—women whose husbands have died.",
    "let them observe a waiting period of four months and ten days.": "Widows must observe 'iddah of four months and ten days before they can remarry. This is longer than the divorce waiting period. It allows time for grief, ensures no pregnancy, and maintains dignity. If the widow is pregnant, her waiting period extends until she gives birth.",
    "When they have reached the end of this period,": "Once the 'iddah is complete, the widow is free to make her own decisions.",
    "then you are not accountable for what they decide for themselves in a reasonable manner.": "After 'iddah, families and guardians have no right to control the widow's choices regarding remarriage or staying single, as long as her decisions are bil-ma'roof (reasonable, appropriate). She regains full autonomy.",
    "And Allah is All-Aware of what you do.": "Allah is Khabeer (thoroughly informed, aware of details) of all actions. He knows how widows are treated and whether their rights are respected."
  },
  235: {
    "There is no blame on you for subtly showing interest in ˹divorced or widowed˺ women": "During 'iddah, it is permissible to make indirect hints (ta'reed) about interest in marriage. For example, saying \"You are a good woman\" or \"I am looking for a wife\" without explicit proposal.",
    "or for hiding ˹the intention˺ in your hearts.": "Having the intention to propose after 'iddah ends is natural and not sinful. Allah knows people will think about these women.",
    "Allah knows that you are considering them ˹for marriage˺.": "Allah is aware of human nature and the natural attraction between people. He does not blame you for your thoughts and intentions.",
    "But do not make a secret commitment with them—": "Do not make secret engagements or private promises of marriage during 'iddah. This protects women from being bound during their waiting period.",
    "you can only show interest in them appropriately.": "Only indirect, respectful indication of interest (qawlan ma'roofan) is allowed—nothing explicit or binding.",
    "Do not commit to the bond of marriage until the waiting period expires.": "The actual marriage contract ('uqdat an-nikah) cannot be done until 'iddah is completely finished. The waiting period must be fully observed.",
    "Know that Allah is aware of what is in your hearts, so beware of Him.": "Allah knows your hidden intentions and desires. Be cautious (ihdharoohu) of violating His boundaries even secretly.",
    "And know that Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Forbearing.": "Despite the warnings, Allah is Ghafoor (forgiving of mistakes) and Haleem (forbearing, not quick to punish). If you slip but repent, His door is open."
  },
  236: {
    "There is no blame if you divorce women before the marriage is consummated or the dowry is settled.": "If divorce happens before intimacy and before fixing a specific dowry amount, there is no sin. This might occur during engagement or very early in marriage.",
    "But give them a ˹suitable˺ compensation—": "Even though no dowry was set, the woman deserves mut'ah (compensation, a parting gift). This maintains her dignity and compensates for the dissolution.",
    "the rich according to his means and the poor according to his.": "The compensation should match the man's financial capacity. A wealthy man gives more; a poor man gives what he can afford.",
    "A reasonable compensation is an obligation on the good-doers.": "Providing mata' bil-ma'roof (fair compensation) is mandatory upon the muhsineen (those who do good, who excel in righteousness). Good character requires fair treatment even when legally ending a relationship."
  },
  237: {
    "And if you divorce them before consummating the marriage but after deciding on a dowry,": "If a specific dowry was agreed upon but divorce happens before intimacy, a different ruling applies.",
    "pay half of the dowry,": "The husband must pay half of the agreed dowry. This is the minimum legal requirement.",
    "unless the wife graciously waives it": "The wife may choose to waive her right to half the dowry ('afawna—they forgive/waive). This is her choice, not an obligation.",
    "or the husband graciously pays in full.": "Alternatively, the husband may choose to pay the full dowry despite only being required to pay half. This is generosity on his part.",
    "Graciousness is closer to righteousness.": "Whoever forgives or gives more demonstrates 'afw (pardon, graciousness), which is closer to taqwa. Being generous in these situations reflects good character.",
    "And do not forget kindness among yourselves.": "Even when relationships end, maintain fadl (grace, kindness, generosity) toward each other. Don't let divorce destroy all decency.",
    "Surely Allah is All-Seeing of what you do.": "Allah sees how you treat each other during divorce. Generosity and fairness are recorded, as are stinginess and harm."
  },
  238: {
    "Observe the ˹five obligatory˺ prayers—": "Amid all the family law discussions, Allah commands maintaining the prayers (salawat). This is a crucial reminder: no matter what personal situations you face—divorce, marriage, disputes—never neglect prayer. Prayer is the foundation that keeps everything else in perspective.",
    "especially the middle prayer—": "As-salat al-wusta (the middle prayer) receives special emphasis. Scholars differ on which prayer this is: some say Fajr, others Asr, others Dhuhr. Regardless, one prayer is singled out for extra care, perhaps because it falls at a time when people are busy.",
    "and stand in true devotion to Allah.": "Stand in prayer with qunoot—devotion, obedience, humility, and focus. Prayer should not be mechanical but filled with genuine consciousness of Allah."
  },
  239: {
    "If you are in danger, pray on foot or while riding.": "In situations of fear or danger (khiftum), prayer may be performed while walking (rijalan) or riding (rukbanan). This is salat al-khawf (prayer during fear/danger), with simplified procedures to accommodate the situation.",
    "But when you are safe,": "When security (amintum) is restored and danger has passed, return to normal prayer procedures.",
    "˹take time to˺ remember Allah for teaching you what you did not know.": "Express gratitude to Allah for the guidance He has provided—teaching you how to pray in all circumstances. Before Islam, you did not have this complete guidance. Allah's comprehensive law covers every situation."
  },
  240: {
    "Those of you who die leaving widows should bequeath for them a year's maintenance without forcing them out.": "This verse originally recommended that men bequeath (wasiyyah) maintenance for their widows for one year, during which they could remain in the home. This was before the detailed inheritance laws were revealed in Surah An-Nisa. Later verses established fixed inheritance shares for widows, which is considered to have modified this ruling. However, the principle of caring for widows remains important.",
    "But if they choose to leave, you are not accountable for what they reasonably decide for themselves.": "If widows choose to leave the home before the year ends, this is their right. No one can force them to stay. Their choices for themselves (bil-ma'roof—within reasonable bounds) are their own.",
    "And Allah is Almighty, All-Wise.": "Allah is Azeez (powerful, whose rulings stand) and Hakeem (wise in legislation). These laws reflect perfect wisdom in caring for vulnerable women."
  },
  241: {
    "Reasonable provisions must be made for divorced women—": "Divorced women deserve mata' bil-ma'roof (appropriate provisions, compensation). This includes the unpaid dowry, the parting gift, and fair treatment.",
    "a duty on those mindful ˹of Allah˺.": "This is haqqan (an obligation, a right) upon the muttaqeen. Those with taqwa fulfill these duties even when legally they might evade them. True God-consciousness means being generous and fair, especially with those you are parting from."
  },
  242: {
    "This is how Allah makes His revelations clear to you,": "Allah clarifies His ayat (signs, verses, rulings) thoroughly. These family law provisions are detailed precisely to prevent oppression and confusion.",
    "so perhaps you will understand.": "The purpose is ta'qiloon—that you may use your intellect, understand the wisdom, and appreciate the justice in these laws."
  },
  243: {
    "Have you ˹O Prophet˺ not seen those who fled their homes in the thousands for fear of death?": "Allah presents a historical example of the Israelites. Thousands fled their homes fearing death, possibly from plague or enemy attack. They sought safety through flight rather than trusting Allah.",
    "Allah said to them, \"Die!\" then He gave them life.": "As a lesson, Allah caused them all to die, then resurrected them. This demonstrated that death comes by Allah's decree, not by location. Fleeing does not prevent what Allah has written. The resurrection showed Allah's power over life and death.",
    "Surely Allah is ever Bountiful to humanity,": "Allah is dhoo fadl (possessor of bounty) to all people. Resurrecting them was an act of divine grace, giving them another chance.",
    "but most people are ungrateful.": "Despite such clear miracles and blessings, most people remain ungrateful (la yashkuroon). They forget Allah's favors and fail to thank Him properly."
  },
  244: {
    "Fight in the cause of Allah,": "The command to fight (qatilu) in Allah's path follows the story of those who fled. The lesson: fleeing death is futile; when fighting is necessary for truth and justice, engage courageously.",
    "and know that Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing.": "Allah hears your words, intentions, and prayers. He knows your circumstances and rewards accordingly. This knowledge should give courage—Allah is aware of every sacrifice."
  },
  245: {
    "Who will lend to Allah a good loan": "Allah invites spending in His cause using the metaphor of qardan hasanan (a beautiful loan). Spending on charity, supporting fighters, helping the needy—all are \"loans\" to Allah.",
    "which Allah will multiply many times over?": "Allah promises to multiply the reward ad'afan katheeratan (many times over). The return is exponentially greater than the investment. One good deed can be multiplied ten times, seventy times, seven hundred times, or more. (Quran 2:261)",
    "It is Allah ˹alone˺ who decreases and increases ˹wealth˺.": "Allah controls rizq—He constricts (yaqbidu) wealth from some and expands (yabsutu) it for others according to His wisdom. Understanding this encourages spending; Allah can replace and increase what you give.",
    "And to Him you will ˹all˺ be returned.": "Ultimately, everyone returns to Allah for judgment. The wealth you keep stays behind; the good you send forth accompanies you."
  },
  246: {
    "Have you not seen those chiefs of the Children of Israel after Moses?": "Allah presents another Israelite story. After Prophet Musa's time, Israelite leaders (mala'—chiefs, notables) approached their prophet.",
    "They said to one of their prophets, \"Appoint for us a king, ˹and˺ we will fight in the cause of Allah.\"": "They asked their prophet (identified by some scholars as Prophet Samuel) to appoint a king to lead them in battle. They had been oppressed and wanted to fight to regain their freedom and land.",
    "He said, \"Are you not going to cower if ordered to fight?\"": "The prophet questioned their sincerity. Would they actually fight if commanded, or would they retreat in fear? He knew human weakness.",
    "They replied, \"How could we refuse to fight in the cause of Allah, while we were driven out of our homes and ˹separated from˺ our children?\"": "They insisted they had every reason to fight—they had lost their homes and been separated from their children. Their situation demanded jihad.",
    "But when they were ordered to fight, they fled, except for a few of them.": "When the actual order came, most abandoned their commitment. Only a small group (qaleelun) remained faithful. Their words proved empty when tested.",
    "And Allah has ˹perfect˺ knowledge of the wrongdoers.": "Allah knew the wrongdoers (zalimeen) who broke their promises. Nothing is hidden from His knowledge. This pattern of promising then retreating is a form of wrongdoing."
  },
  247: {
    "Their prophet told them, \"Allah has appointed Saul to be your king.\"": "The prophet announced that Allah chose Talut (Saul) as their king. This was divine selection, not human election.",
    "They protested, \"How can he be our king when some of us are more deserving of kingship than he,": "The people objected based on lineage. Saul was not from the royal or priestly tribes. They thought they had better claims to kingship.",
    "and he has not been blessed with vast riches?\"": "They also objected to his relative poverty. He was not wealthy, and they associated leadership with material wealth.",
    "He replied, \"Allah has chosen him over you": "The prophet explained that Allah's selection (istafa—chose, selected) overrides human preferences. Allah's choice is what matters, not human criteria.",
    "and blessed him with knowledge and stature.": "Allah gave Saul basta (abundance, breadth) in two areas: knowledge ('ilm—wisdom, understanding, leadership ability) and jism (physical body—height, strength, impressive presence). These qualities make him fit for kingship—more than wealth or lineage.",
    "Allah grants kingship to whoever He wills.": "Ultimate sovereignty belongs to Allah. He gives mulk (kingship, authority) to whomever He chooses according to His wisdom.",
    "And Allah is All-Bountiful, All-Knowing.": "Allah is Wasi' (vast in bounty, generous) and 'Aleem (knowing). He knows who deserves leadership and generously grants authority as He sees fit."
  },
  248: {
    "Their prophet further told them, \"The sign of Saul's kingship is that the Ark will come to you—": "As proof of Saul's legitimate kingship, a sign would appear: the return of at-tabut (the Ark, sacred chest). This Ark had been lost or taken by enemies.",
    "containing reassurance from your Lord": "The Ark contained sakeenah (tranquility, peace, reassurance) from Allah. Its presence brought spiritual calm and confidence.",
    "and relics of the family of Moses and the family of Aaron,": "Inside were baqiyyah (remnants, relics) from the families of Musa and Harun—possibly the tablets, Musa's staff, or other sacred items. These connected them to their prophetic heritage.",
    "which will be carried by the angels.": "Angels would carry the Ark back to them—a miraculous sign. The angelic involvement proved this was divine intervention.",
    "Surely in this is a sign for you, if you ˹truly˺ believe.\"": "This miraculous return was a clear ayah (sign) for those with genuine belief. Believers recognize divine signs; doubters reject even clear miracles."
  },
  249: {
    "When Saul marched forth with his army, he cautioned: \"Allah will test you with a river.": "As Saul led his army toward battle, he warned them of an upcoming test involving a river. This was both a physical and spiritual test.",
    "So whoever drinks ˹his fill˺ from it is not with me,": "Anyone who drank freely from the river would be dismissed from the army. This tested obedience and self-discipline.",
    "and whoever does not taste it—except a sip from the hollow of his hands—is definitely with me.\"": "Only those who refrained completely, or took just a handful (ghurfah—a scoop with the hand) would remain in the army. This small amount would quench thirst without indulgence.",
    "They all drank ˹their fill˺ except for a few!": "Most soldiers failed the test, drinking freely. Only a small group maintained discipline. This massively reduced Saul's army.",
    "When he and the ˹remaining˺ faithful with him crossed the river,": "Saul and the few who passed the test crossed the river, ready to face the enemy.",
    "they said, \"Now we are no match for Goliath and his warriors.\"": "Even among those who passed the test, some despaired when they saw Jalut (Goliath) and his powerful army. They felt overwhelmed by the odds.",
    "But those ˹believers˺ who were certain they would meet Allah reasoned,": "The strongest believers—those certain of meeting Allah and being accountable—had different reasoning. Their faith gave them perspective.",
    "\"How many times has a small force vanquished a mighty army by the Will of Allah!": "They remembered historical examples: small groups defeating large armies when Allah willed it. Victory depends on Allah's will, not numbers.",
    "And Allah is ˹always˺ with the steadfast.\"": "Allah's ma'iyyah (companionship, support) is with the sabireen (patient, steadfast). Those who persevere have divine support regardless of worldly odds."
  },
  250: {
    "When they advanced to face Goliath and his warriors, they prayed,": "As they went forth to battle, the believers made dua. Prayer before difficulty is the mark of believers.",
    "\"Our Lord! Shower us with perseverance,": "\"Afrigh 'alayna sabran\"—pour patience upon us abundantly. The verb suggests pouring liquid generously. They asked for overwhelming patience to face the terror of battle.",
    "make our steps firm,": "\"Thabbit aqdamana\"—make our feet firm, steady. This is both literal (don't let us flee) and metaphorical (keep us steadfast in faith and courage).",
    "and give us victory over the disbelieving people.\"": "They asked for nasr (victory, divine help) over the disbelievers. Their prayer combined requesting internal strength (patience, steadfastness) and external success (victory)."
  },
  251: {
    "So they defeated them by Allah's Will,": "Despite being outnumbered, they achieved victory bi-idhnillah (by Allah's permission). Allah granted success to the smaller, faithful army.",
    "and David killed Goliath.": "A young Dawud (David), who would later become a prophet and king, killed the giant Goliath. This was a defining moment—a youth defeating a feared warrior through faith and divine support.",
    "And Allah blessed David with kingship and wisdom": "Allah gave Dawud mulk (kingship) and hikmah (wisdom, prophethood). He became both a political and spiritual leader.",
    "and taught him what He willed.": "Allah taught Dawud special knowledge—how to make armor, the language of birds, the Psalms (Zabur), and other divinely granted knowledge.",
    "Had Allah not repelled a group of people by ˹the might of˺ another,": "Allah uses daf' (repelling)—He pushes back some people by means of others. Righteous people restrain evildoers; armies of truth fight armies of oppression.",
    "corruption would have dominated the earth,": "Without this divine system of checks and balances, fasad (corruption) would overwhelm the earth. Evil would go unchallenged and spread everywhere.",
    "but Allah is Gracious to all.": "Allah's grace (fadl) to humanity includes this system where good constrains evil, preventing total corruption. Fighting in Allah's cause serves this noble purpose."
  },
  252: {
    "These are Allah's revelations which We recite to you ˹O Prophet˺ in truth.": "All these stories—from family law to Israelite history—are ayat Allah (Allah's signs/verses) recited with truth (bil-haqq). They are not legends but true accounts with lessons.",
    "And you are truly one of the messengers.": "This concluding statement affirms Muhammad's prophethood. The fact that he can relate these detailed historical accounts without having studied them is itself evidence of his genuine prophethood. He is indeed among the mursaleen (messengers) sent by Allah."
  },
  253: {
    "We have chosen some of those messengers above others.": "Among all the prophets and messengers, Allah has given some fadl (preference, excellence) over others. This does not mean some are deficient—all prophets are noble and trustworthy—but some have been given higher ranks, greater trials, or more extensive missions. This is Allah's wisdom in His creation and selection.",
    "Allah spoke directly to some,": "Some prophets had the honor of direct speech (kalama) with Allah. The foremost example is Musa (Moses), who is called Kaleemullah (the one who spoke with Allah). Allah spoke to him directly without an intermediary angel.",
    "and raised some high in rank.": "Some prophets were elevated in darajat (ranks, degrees) above others. Muhammad (peace be upon him) is the highest in rank—he is the Seal of Prophets, the leader of all messengers, and was granted the Night Journey and Ascension.",
    "To Jesus, son of Mary, We gave clear proofs": "Isa (Jesus), son of Maryam, received bayyinat (clear proofs, miracles)—healing the blind and lepers, raising the dead by Allah's permission, and speaking from the cradle.",
    "and supported him with the holy spirit.": "Isa was strengthened with Ruh al-Qudus (the Holy Spirit), understood to be the angel Jibreel (Gabriel), who assisted him throughout his mission.",
    "If Allah had willed, succeeding generations would not have fought ˹among themselves˺ after receiving the clear proofs.": "Despite clear guidance from their prophets, people of later generations fought each other over religion. If Allah had willed to force unity, He could have. But He gave humans free will.",
    "But they differed—some believed while others disbelieved.": "People exercised their free choice: some accepted truth and believed; others rejected it and disbelieved. This division is a result of human choice, not divine coercion.",
    "Yet if Allah had willed, they would not have fought one another.": "The repetition emphasizes that Allah could prevent all conflict by removing free will, but this is not His way. He permits humans to choose.",
    "But Allah does what He wills.": "Ultimately, Allah's will prevails. He has willed to give humans freedom, test them, and judge them based on their choices. His wisdom in allowing free will serves a higher purpose—meaningful accountability."
  },
  254: {
    "O believers! Donate from what We have provided for you": "Allah commands spending (infaq) from the provisions He has given. Everything you have is from Allah—your wealth, time, skills. Spend from these blessings in His cause.",
    "before the arrival of a Day": "Urgency is emphasized: spend now, before the Day of Judgment arrives. Once that Day comes, the opportunity is gone forever.",
    "when there will be no bargaining,": "On that Day, there is no bay' (buying, selling, trading). You cannot negotiate, purchase good deeds, or trade your way into Paradise. All commercial transactions end with death.",
    "friendship,": "No khullah (close friendship) will benefit anyone. Even the closest friends cannot help each other. Worldly relationships have no power on that Day.",
    "or intercession.": "No shafa'ah (intercession) will occur except by Allah's permission, and it will not be granted for disbelievers. The intercessions people hope for will be unavailable to those who rejected faith.",
    "Those who disbelieve are ˹truly˺ the wrongdoers.": "The disbelievers (kafirun) are identified as the zalimun (wrongdoers, oppressors). The greatest wrong is disbelief—wronging one's own soul by rejecting the Creator."
  },
  255: {
    "Allah! There is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Him,": "The verse begins with the declaration of tawhid (monotheism). La ilaha illa Huwa—there is no deity except Him. This negates all false gods and affirms the One True God.",
    "the Ever-Living, All-Sustaining.": "Al-Hayy (the Ever-Living)—He has perfect, eternal life with no beginning or end. Al-Qayyum (the Self-Sustaining, the Sustainer of all)—He depends on nothing, yet everything depends on Him. He maintains all existence.",
    "Neither drowsiness nor sleep overtakes Him.": "Allah never experiences sinah (drowsiness) or nawm (sleep). He is eternally aware, watchful, and active. Unlike created beings who need rest, Allah never tires or becomes inattentive. His care for creation is constant.",
    "To Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth.": "Everything in existence belongs to Allah. He is the Owner (Malik) of all. Every atom, every creature, every phenomenon is His property and under His control.",
    "Who could possibly intercede with Him without His permission?": "No one can intercede (shafa'ah) before Allah except by His permission. This destroys false beliefs in unauthorized intercessors. Angels, prophets, and righteous people can only intercede if Allah allows, and only for those with whom He is pleased.",
    "He ˹fully˺ knows what is ahead of them and what is behind them,": "Allah's knowledge encompasses all—what is before creation (their future) and what is behind them (their past). Nothing is hidden from His knowledge. He knows what was, what is, and what will be.",
    "but no one can grasp any of His knowledge—except what He wills ˹to reveal˺.": "Humans cannot encompass (ihata) Allah's knowledge. We know only what He chooses to reveal through revelation or experience. His knowledge is infinite; ours is limited to what He grants.",
    "His Seat encompasses the heavens and the earth,": "The Kursi (Seat/Footstool) of Allah is so vast it encompasses the heavens and earth. Ibn Abbas described the Kursi as the place of Allah's feet, while the Throne (Arsh) is even greater. The immensity of the Kursi demonstrates Allah's magnificence.",
    "and the preservation of both does not tire Him.": "Maintaining (hifz) the heavens and earth does not cause Allah ya'uduhu (to tire, to burden Him). Creating and sustaining the universe is effortless for Him. He is never weary.",
    "For He is the Most High, the Greatest.": "Al-'Aliyy (the Most High)—above all creation in every sense: in essence, attributes, and rank. Al-'Adheem (the Greatest)—incomparably great, magnificent beyond description. This verse, known as Ayat al-Kursi, is the greatest verse in the Quran. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"The greatest verse in Allah's Book is Ayat al-Kursi.\" (Muslim)"
  },
  256: {
    "Let there be no compulsion in religion,": "La ikraha fid-deen—there is no coercion in religion. Faith cannot be forced because it is a matter of the heart. Forced belief is not genuine belief. Islam spreads through persuasion, evidence, and example, not through compulsion. This principle protects religious freedom and dignity.",
    "for the truth stands out clearly from falsehood.": "The reason compulsion is unnecessary: ar-rushd (right guidance, truth) has been made distinct from al-ghayy (error, misguidance). The evidence for Islam is clear—the Quran, the Prophet's character, the signs in creation. Truth is self-evident to those who sincerely seek it.",
    "So whoever renounces false gods": "Whoever rejects at-taghut (false deities, anything worshipped besides Allah, tyrannical powers, Satan) through yakfur (disbelief in them, rejection)...",
    "and believes in Allah": "...and has iman (belief, faith) in Allah alone...",
    "has certainly grasped the firmest, unfailing hand-hold.": "Such a person has seized al-'urwah al-wuthqa (the most trustworthy hand-hold, the firmest grip). This metaphor describes a rope or handle that will never break. Faith in Allah is the unbreakable connection that saves from destruction.",
    "And Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing.": "Allah is Samee' (hearing all declarations of faith and rejection) and 'Aleem (knowing the sincerity in hearts). He knows who truly believes and who merely pretends."
  },
  257: {
    "Allah is the Guardian of the believers—": "Allah is the Waliyy (guardian, protector, supporter, helper) of those who believe. He takes care of them, guides them, and protects them.",
    "He brings them out of darkness and into light.": "Allah extracts believers from dhulumat (darknesses—plural indicating multiple layers of ignorance, sin, and misguidance) into noor (light—singular, representing the one truth of Islam). This journey from darkness to light is the essence of faith.",
    "As for the disbelievers, their guardians are false gods": "The disbelievers have awliya' (guardians/protectors, plural) who are taghut (false deities, devils, tyrants). They follow multiple false paths.",
    "who lead them out of light and into darkness.": "These false guardians do the opposite of what Allah does—they take people from any light (natural disposition, previous guidance) into darknesses (layers of error and sin). This is spiritual regression.",
    "It is they who will be the residents of the Fire.": "These misguided people become ashab an-nar (companions of the Fire), permanent residents of Hell.",
    "They will be there forever.": "Their stay in Hell is eternal. The contrast is complete: believers go from darkness to light to Paradise; disbelievers go from light to darkness to Hell."
  },
  258: {
    "Are you ˹O Prophet˺ not aware of the one who argued with Abraham about his Lord because Allah had granted him kingship?": "This story involves Ibrahim debating with an arrogant king (traditionally identified as Nimrod). The king's power and authority made him arrogant enough to challenge divine truth. Worldly power often breeds spiritual blindness.",
    "˹Remember˺ when Abraham said, \"My Lord is the One Who has power to give life and cause death.\"": "Ibrahim defined his Lord with a fundamental attribute: the power to give life (yuhyi) and cause death (yumeet). This power belongs exclusively to Allah.",
    "He argued, \"I too have the power to give life and cause death.\"": "The arrogant king responded foolishly: \"I can give life and cause death too.\" He likely demonstrated by pardoning a condemned prisoner (\"giving life\") and executing another (\"causing death\"). This was sophistry—playing with words rather than engaging the real meaning.",
    "Abraham challenged ˹him˺, \"Allah causes the sun to rise from the east. So make it rise from the west.\"": "Ibrahim shifted the argument to something undeniable and beyond human manipulation. Allah brings the sun from the east; if you claim divine power, make it rise from the west. This exposed the king's impotence.",
    "And so the disbeliever was dumbstruck.": "The king was buhita—shocked into silence, utterly confounded. He had no response. His arrogance was exposed as empty.",
    "And Allah does not guide the wrongdoing people.": "Allah does not guide the zalimeen (wrongdoers, oppressors). Those who arrogantly oppose truth despite clear evidence do not receive divine guidance. Their own injustice blocks the path to truth."
  },
  259: {
    "Or ˹are you not aware of˺ the one who passed by a city which was in ruins.": "A righteous man (some say Prophet Uzayr/Ezra, others say a different righteous person) passed by a qaryah (city/town) that was khawiyah (ruined, collapsed upon its roofs, completely destroyed).",
    "He wondered, \"How could Allah bring this back to life after its destruction?\"": "He pondered Allah's power: how could this dead city be revived? This was not doubt but amazement and desire to understand Allah's creative power.",
    "So Allah caused him to die for a hundred years then brought him back to life.": "To demonstrate His power directly, Allah caused this man to die for exactly one hundred years, then resurrected him. This was a personal miracle showing divine power over life and death.",
    "Allah asked, \"How long have you remained ˹in this state˺?\"": "Upon resurrection, Allah questioned him to make him aware of what had occurred.",
    "He replied, \"Perhaps a day or part of a day.\"": "Death had no consciousness for him. He thought he had been asleep for a short time—a day at most. This shows that the dead have no awareness of time's passage.",
    "Allah said, \"No! You have remained here for a hundred years!": "Allah informed him of the true duration: a full century had passed in the world.",
    "Just look at your food and drink—they have not spoiled.": "Miraculously, his food and drink remained fresh and unspoiled for a hundred years—a sign of Allah's power to preserve what He wills.",
    "˹But now˺ look at ˹the remains of˺ your donkey!": "In contrast, his donkey had died and decomposed to bones—showing the natural course of death and decay.",
    "And ˹so˺ We have made you into a sign for humanity.": "This man's entire experience became an ayah (sign, lesson) for people—proof of resurrection and Allah's power.",
    "And look at the bones ˹of the donkey˺, how We bring them together then clothe them with flesh!\"": "Allah showed him the resurrection process in real-time: the donkey's scattered bones came together (nunshizuha—we raise them, assemble them), then were covered with flesh. He witnessed resurrection before his eyes.",
    "When this was made clear to him, he declared, \"˹Now˺ I know that Allah is Most Capable of everything.\"": "After witnessing this demonstration, he declared with certainty: Allah is Qadeer (perfectly capable, powerful) over all things. His wonder was transformed into certain knowledge."
  },
  260: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when Abraham said, \"My Lord! Show me how you give life to the dead.\"": "Ibrahim asked Allah to show him the process of resurrection. This was a request to witness, not a question from doubt.",
    "Allah responded, \"Do you not believe?\"": "Allah asked whether Ibrahim lacked belief. This question was to clarify his motivation.",
    "Abraham replied, \"Yes I do, but just so my heart can be reassured.\"": "Ibrahim confirmed his belief was certain, but he wanted his heart to reach tatma'inna (tranquility, deeper reassurance). Moving from knowledge of certainty to eye-witness certainty increases faith's strength. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"We are more worthy of doubt than Ibrahim.\" (Bukhari)—meaning Ibrahim had no doubt, so how can we have any?",
    "Allah said, \"Then bring four birds,": "Allah instructed Ibrahim to take four birds. Different narrations mention different species—perhaps a rooster, peacock, raven, and duck.",
    "train them to come to you,": "\"Surhunna ilayka\"—train them to recognize you and come when called. He should familiarize them with himself so they know him.",
    "˹then cut them into pieces,˺": "The instruction to slaughter and cut them is implied. Ibrahim was to kill the birds and cut them into pieces, mixing them together.",
    "and scatter them on different hilltops.": "He should distribute parts (juz'an) of the mixed birds on different mountains (jabal—hills). Each hilltop gets mixed pieces from all four birds.",
    "Then call them back, they will fly to you in haste.": "When Ibrahim calls them, they will come sa'yan (hastening, rushing) back to him—each bird fully restored and alive.",
    "And ˹so you will˺ know that Allah is Almighty, All-Wise.\"": "Through this demonstration, Ibrahim would know with certainty that Allah is Azeez (Almighty, overpowering) and Hakeem (All-Wise). Resurrection is easy for Allah, and His wisdom in demonstrating it to His prophet serves multiple purposes."
  },
  261: {
    "The example of those who spend their wealth in the cause of Allah": "Allah presents a parable (mathal) for those who spend their money fi sabilillah (in Allah's path—for charity, supporting truth, helping the needy).",
    "is that of a grain that sprouts into seven ears,": "One grain (habbah) of wheat produces a plant with seven ears (sanabil).",
    "each bearing one hundred grains.": "Each ear contains one hundred grains. So one grain becomes seven hundred—a 700-fold increase!",
    "And Allah multiplies ˹the reward even more˺ to whoever He wills.": "Beyond this already extraordinary multiplication, Allah can increase the reward even further (yuda'ifu) for whomever He wills, according to sincerity, need, and circumstances.",
    "For Allah is All-Bountiful, All-Knowing.": "Allah is Wasi' (vast in bounty, generous) and 'Aleem (knowing who deserves multiplication). His generosity knows no limits, and He knows the true value and intention of every donation."
  },
  262: {
    "Those who spend their wealth in the cause of Allah": "These are the people who give in charity for Allah's sake.",
    "and do not follow their charity with reminders of their generosity": "They do not commit mann—reminding recipients of the favor, making them feel indebted, or boasting about the charity. This ruins the good deed and humiliates the recipient.",
    "or hurtful words—": "Nor do they cause adha (harm, hurt) through words or actions toward those they helped. No insults, no condescension, no mentioning their poverty.",
    "they will get their reward from their Lord,": "Such sincere givers receive their ajr (reward) from Allah. He will reward them fully and generously.",
    "and there will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve.": "The ultimate success: no fear about the future (no khawf), and no grief about the past (no huzn). This is the description of Paradise dwellers."
  },
  263: {
    "Kind words and forgiveness": "Qawlun ma'roof (kind, appropriate speech—encouraging words, gentle refusal) and maghfirah (forgiveness, pardoning someone's faults or debts)...",
    "are better than charity followed by injury.": "...are superior to sadaqah (charity) that is followed by adha (injury, harm, hurtful reminders). It is better not to give at all than to give and then hurt the recipient.",
    "And Allah is Self-Sufficient, Most Forbearing.": "Allah is Ghaniyy (completely self-sufficient, needing nothing) and Haleem (forbearing, patient, not quick to punish). He does not need our charity—we give for our own benefit. His forbearance means He tolerates our mistakes, but we should not abuse His patience."
  },
  264: {
    "O believers! Do not waste your charity with reminders ˹of your generosity˺ or hurtful words,": "Believers are warned: do not nullify (tubtilu) your charity through mann and adha. These behaviors cancel the reward entirely.",
    "like those who donate their wealth just to show off": "This compares corrupted charity to riya' (showing off, ostentation)—giving charity only to be seen and praised by people, not for Allah's sake.",
    "and do not believe in Allah or the Last Day.": "The one who gives for show lacks true faith in Allah and the Day of Accountability. If they truly believed, they would give sincerely for Allah alone.",
    "Their example is that of a hard barren rock covered with a thin layer of soil": "Allah presents a parable: safwan (a smooth, hard rock) with a thin layer of turab (soil/dust) on top.",
    "hit by a strong rain—leaving it just a bare stone.": "When wabil (heavy rain) hits it, the soil washes away completely, leaving the rock sald (bare, smooth, nothing on it). The rain, which should produce growth, instead exposes barrenness.",
    "Such people are unable to preserve the reward of their charity.": "Like the washed-away soil, their charity produces no lasting reward. They gain nothing (la yaqdiroon 'ala shay'in) from what they earned through their insincere giving.",
    "Allah does not guide ˹such˺ disbelieving people.": "Allah does not guide the kafireen (disbelievers, those who reject faith). Their insincerity blocks them from divine guidance."
  },
  265: {
    "And the example of those who donate their wealth, seeking Allah's pleasure": "In contrast, sincere givers seek ibtighā' mardatillah (seeking Allah's pleasure) as their sole motivation.",
    "and believing the reward is certain,": "\"Tathbeetan min anfusihim\"—with certainty and firm belief from themselves. They are confident in Allah's promise of reward.",
    "is that of a garden on a fertile hill:": "The parable: a jannah (garden) on a rabwah (elevated, fertile ground)—the best location for growth.",
    "when heavy rain falls, it yields up twice its normal produce.": "When heavy rain (wabil) hits this garden, it produces ukulaha (its fruits/produce) dif'ayn (double, twice as much). The good soil and good rain create abundant harvest.",
    "If no heavy rain falls, a drizzle is sufficient.": "Even if heavy rain doesn't come, just tall (light drizzle, dew) is enough to produce good results. The garden is so well-positioned that minimal water suffices.",
    "And Allah is All-Seeing of what you do.": "Allah is Baseer (All-Seeing) of all deeds. He sees the intention behind every donation, every act of kindness, and rewards accordingly."
  },
  266: {
    "Would any of you wish to have a garden with palm trees, grapevines, and all kinds of fruits with rivers flowing underneath": "Allah presents a hypothetical scenario: imagine having a perfect garden with date palms, grapes, all types of fruit, and rivers flowing beneath. This represents the ultimate worldly investment and prosperity.",
    "and as they grow very old with dependent children,": "Then imagine reaching old age (kibar—advanced age, weakness) with dhurriyyah du'afa' (weak, young, dependent children) who rely entirely on you and that garden for survival. Your need for the garden is greatest at this vulnerable moment.",
    "a fiery whirlwind hits the garden, burning it all up?": "Suddenly, an i'sar (whirlwind, tornado) containing fire strikes the garden, completely burning it (ihtaraqat). Everything is destroyed in an instant. Complete disaster at the worst possible time.",
    "This is how Allah makes His revelations clear to you, so perhaps you will reflect.": "This parable illustrates wasted good deeds. Just as losing your garden at your time of greatest need would be devastating, so is losing your charitable rewards on the Day of Judgment (through showing off, reminders, or hurt) when you need them most. Allah clarifies His ayat (verses, signs) so people will reflect (tatafakkaroon) and avoid this tragedy."
  },
  267: {
    "O believers! Donate from the best of what you have earned": "Give from tayyibat (the good, pure, quality things) you have earned through work and trade.",
    "and of what We have produced for you from the earth.": "Also give from the agricultural produce Allah has provided from the earth. Both income and crops should be sources of charity.",
    "Do not pick out worthless things for donation,": "Do not intentionally select al-khabeeth (the bad, defective, worthless items) for charity while keeping the good for yourself.",
    "which you yourselves would only accept with closed eyes.": "You would not accept these inferior items yourself except ightimadan (with eyes closed, reluctantly, with disgust). If you wouldn't want to receive it, don't give it.",
    "And know that Allah is Self-Sufficient, Praiseworthy.": "Allah is Ghaniyy (Self-Sufficient—He needs nothing from you) and Hameed (Praiseworthy—worthy of all praise regardless of what you give). Give quality charity out of gratitude and love for Allah, not because He needs it."
  },
  268: {
    "The Devil threatens you with ˹the prospect of˺ poverty": "Ash-Shaytan (Satan) promises you faqr (poverty)—he whispers that if you give charity, you will become poor. This is his tactic to prevent generosity.",
    "and bids you to the shameful deed ˹of stinginess˺,": "He also commands you toward fahsha' (shameful deeds), particularly stinginess and withholding charity. Greed is shameful, especially when others are in need.",
    "while Allah promises you forgiveness and ˹great˺ bounties from Him.": "In contrast, Allah promises maghfirah (forgiveness) and fadl (bounty, favor, increase). Charity leads to more blessings, not poverty.",
    "And Allah is All-Bountiful, All-Knowing.": "Allah is Wasi' (vast in generosity, boundless) and 'Aleem (All-Knowing). He knows your needs and will provide abundantly. Trust His promise over Satan's lies."
  },
  269: {
    "Allah grants wisdom to whoever He wills.": "Allah gives hikmah (wisdom—deep understanding, proper judgment, applying knowledge correctly) to whomever He chooses. Wisdom is a divine gift.",
    "And whoever is granted wisdom is certainly blessed with a great privilege.": "Whoever receives hikmah has received khayran katheeran (abundant good). Wisdom is better than wealth. Ibn Abbas said wisdom is understanding the Quran—its meanings, laws, and application.",
    "But none will be mindful ˹of this˺ except people of reason.": "Only ulul-albab (people of understanding, those who use their intellects) recognize and appreciate the value of wisdom. Others pursue worldly things, missing the real treasure."
  },
  270: {
    "Whatever charities you give or vows you make are surely known to Allah.": "All nafaqah (expenditure, charity) and nadhr (vows, pledges) are known to Allah. He records every donation and every commitment.",
    "And the wrongdoers will have no helpers.": "The zalimoon (wrongdoers—those who withhold charity, break vows, or oppress others) will have no ansār (helpers, supporters) on the Day of Judgment. No one will save them from consequences."
  },
  271: {
    "To give charity publicly is good,": "If you give sadaqat (charities) openly (tubdoo), it is ni'imma (good, excellent). Public charity encourages others and demonstrates generosity.",
    "but to give to the poor privately is better for you,": "But if you conceal (tukhfooha) charity and give directly to the fuqara' (the poor), it is khayr (better) for you. Secret charity protects from showing off and maintains the recipient's dignity.",
    "and will absolve you of your sins.": "Allah will yukaffir (expiate, remove, cover) some of your sayyiat (sins, wrongdoings) through this sincere, hidden charity.",
    "And Allah is All-Aware of what you do.": "Allah is Khabeer (thoroughly informed, intimately aware) of all deeds, whether public or private. Nothing escapes His knowledge."
  },
  272: {
    "You are not responsible for people's guidance ˹O Prophet˺—": "The Prophet (and by extension all believers) are not responsible for hidayah (guidance) of others. Guidance is from Allah, not from us.",
    "it is Allah Who guides whoever He wills.": "Allah guides whomever He wills. Our job is to convey; His job is to guide hearts.",
    "Whatever you ˹believers˺ spend in charity, it is for your own good—": "Any charity you give benefits you (li-anfusikum), not Allah or even primarily the recipients. The reward is yours.",
    "as long as you do so seeking the pleasure of Allah.": "The condition: you must give ibtighā' wajhillah (seeking Allah's Face/pleasure). The intention must be pure.",
    "Whatever you donate will be paid back to you in full,": "Whatever you spend will be yuwaffa (repaid fully, given back completely) to you.",
    "and you will not be wronged.": "No one will be wronged (la tudhlamoon). You will receive full reward without any reduction or injustice."
  },
  273: {
    "˹Charity is˺ for the needy who are too engaged in the cause of Allah to move about in the land ˹for work˺.": "Priority should be given to fuqara' (the poor) who are uhsiru (restricted, confined) in Allah's path—dedicated to seeking knowledge, jihad, or dawah, unable to work for income.",
    "Those unfamiliar with their situation will think they are not in need ˹of charity˺ because they do not beg.": "Al-jahil (the ignorant person, one unfamiliar with their situation) thinks they are aghniya' (wealthy, self-sufficient) because of their ta'affuf (restraint, dignity, refusal to beg).",
    "You can recognize them by their appearance.": "You can identify them by their seemahum (marks, appearance)—perhaps their worn clothes, humble demeanor, or look of concern—not by their words.",
    "They do not beg people persistently.": "They do not ask people ilhafan (persistently, insistently, annoyingly). They maintain their dignity and self-respect.",
    "Whatever you give in charity is certainly well known to Allah.": "Any charity given is known to Allah. He sees and will reward those who help these dignified poor people."
  },
  274: {
    "Those who spend their wealth in charity day and night,": "Comprehensive giving: bil-layli wan-nahar (by night and day)—constantly, regularly, consistently.",
    "secretly and openly—": "Sirran wa 'alaniyah (secretly and openly)—both private and public charity. They give in all circumstances and modes.",
    "their reward is with their Lord,": "Their ajr (reward) is with Allah, guaranteed and preserved.",
    "and there will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve.": "The ultimate promise: no fear, no grief. This is the description of those who will enter Paradise with joy and security."
  },
  275: {
    "Those who consume interest": "Those who ya'kuloon ar-riba (consume, devour, engage in interest/usury). Riba literally means increase, excess—charging money for lending money.",
    "will stand ˹on Judgment Day˺ like those driven to madness by Satan's touch.": "They will rise from their graves staggering like someone whom ash-shaytan has driven to madness through mass (touch, possession). This vivid image shows their spiritual and moral corruption manifesting physically.",
    "That is because they say, \"Trade is no different than interest.\"": "Their justification: \"Innamal-bay'u mithlur-riba\"—trade is just like interest. They see no moral difference between legitimate profit through trade and exploitative profit through interest.",
    "But Allah has permitted trading and forbidden interest.": "Allah makes a clear distinction: He made bay' (trade, commerce) halal (permitted) and made riba haram (forbidden). The difference is real and significant. Trade involves risk, effort, and exchange of goods; interest is guaranteed profit without effort or risk, exploiting the needy.",
    "Whoever refrains—after having received warning from their Lord—": "Whoever receives maw'idhah (admonition, warning) from Allah and then stops (intaha) engaging in interest...",
    "may keep their previous gains,": "...they can keep ma salafa (what has passed, previous interest earned before knowing the prohibition). Past sins are forgiven upon repentance.",
    "and their case is left to Allah.": "Their matter (amruhu) is with Allah—He will judge their sincerity and forgive if repentance is genuine.",
    "As for those who persist,": "Whoever returns ('ada) to interest after being warned...",
    "it is they who will be the residents of the Fire. They will be there forever.": "They become ashab an-nar (companions of the Fire), dwelling eternally in Hell. This severe punishment shows the gravity of riba."
  },
  276: {
    "Allah has made interest fruitless": "Allah yamhaqu (destroys, eliminates the blessing from, makes fruitless) riba. Even if interest increases wealth numerically, it removes barakah (blessing). Interest wealth brings no real benefit.",
    "and charity fruitful.": "In contrast, Allah yurbi (increases, causes to grow) sadaqat (charities). Charity multiplies in blessing and reward, even if it reduces wealth temporarily.",
    "And Allah does not like any ungrateful evildoer.": "Allah does not love any kaffarin (ungrateful disbeliever) atheem (persistent sinner). Those who deal in interest show ingratitude for Allah's provisions and persist in sin."
  },
  277: {
    "Indeed, those who believe, do good, establish prayer, and pay alms-tax": "The contrast: true believers combine iman (faith), salihat (righteous deeds), salah (prayer), and zakah (obligatory charity).",
    "will receive their reward from their Lord,": "Their reward is guaranteed with Allah.",
    "and there will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve.": "Again, the ultimate success: no fear, no grief. This stands in stark contrast to the interest-dealers' fate."
  },
  278: {
    "O believers! Fear Allah,": "The command begins with taqwa—be conscious of Allah, fear His punishment.",
    "and give up outstanding interest": "Dharoo (leave, abandon) ma baqiya (what remains) of riba. Cancel all existing interest-based contracts and debts. Stop collecting interest immediately.",
    "if you are ˹true˺ believers.": "This is a condition: \"in kuntum mu'mineen\"—if you are truly believers. True faith requires obedience, especially in difficult matters like abandoning profitable interest."
  },
  279: {
    "If you do not,": "If you refuse to abandon interest...",
    "then beware of a war with Allah and His Messenger!": "...fa'dhanu bi-harbin minallahi wa rasoolihi—then take notice of war from Allah and His Messenger! This is the strongest warning in the Quran. Declaring war against Allah and His Messenger is the most terrifying threat imaginable. No sin receives this level of condemnation except riba.",
    "But if you repent,": "If you make tawbah (repentance) and abandon interest...",
    "you may retain your principal—": "...you are entitled to ru'us amwalikum (the heads/principals of your wealth)—the original amounts lent, without interest.",
    "neither inflicting nor suffering harm.": "La tadhlimoona (you do not wrong others by taking more than principal) wa la tudhlamoona (nor are you wronged by losing your principal). This is perfect justice—no exploitation, no loss."
  },
  280: {
    "If it is difficult for someone to repay a debt,": "If the debtor is dhoo 'usrah (in hardship, experiencing difficulty), unable to pay due to genuine financial constraints, not negligence or extravagance...",
    "postpone it until a time of ease.": "The creditor must grant nadhirah (respite, postponement, waiting period) until maysarah (ease, when the debtor's situation improves). This is not optional kindness but a religious obligation. Pressuring someone in genuine hardship is forbidden.",
    "And if you waive it as an act of charity,": "Even better: if you tasaddaqu (give it as charity, forgive the debt entirely), this is superior generosity. Cancelling debt for someone in hardship is a high form of charity.",
    "it will be better for you, if only you knew.": "This is khayr (better) for you—better for your soul, better in reward, better in Allah's sight. \"If only you knew\" suggests that the spiritual and eventual worldly benefits far outweigh the monetary loss. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"Whoever gives respite to someone in hardship, or cancels his debt, Allah will put him in His shade on the Day when there is no shade except His shade.\" (Muslim)"
  },
  281: {
    "Be mindful of the Day when you will ˹all˺ be returned to Allah,": "Fear and prepare for the Day when turja'oona (you will be returned) to Allah. Death is certain; the return to Allah is inevitable. Every transaction, every debt, every act will be reviewed.",
    "then every soul will be paid in full for what it has done,": "Each nafs (soul) will be tuwaffa (paid in full, given completely) what it earned—good and evil. Full recompense without reduction. This verse is reported to be the last verse revealed to the Prophet (peace be upon him), revealed nine days before his death.",
    "and none will be wronged.": "No one will be wronged (la yudhlamoon). Perfect justice will be executed. No good deed will be overlooked; no evil deed will be exaggerated. This should motivate fair dealing, especially in financial matters."
  },
  282: {
    "O believers! When you contract a loan for a fixed period of time, commit it to writing.": "When you engage in tadayantum (mutual debt/credit transactions) for an ajal musamman (fixed, specified term), record it in writing (iktuboohu). Documentation protects both parties from disputes and memory lapses. This is the longest verse in the Quran, demonstrating Islam's concern for financial justice and clarity.",
    "Let the scribe maintain justice between the parties.": "A katib (scribe, writer) should write the contract bil-'adl (with justice, fairly), not favoring either party. The scribe must be neutral, honest, and skilled.",
    "The scribe should not refuse to write as Allah has taught them to write.": "The scribe must not refuse (la ya'ba) to write. If Allah has given them this skill, they should use it to serve the community. Literacy is a blessing to be shared. This also establishes writing as a communal obligation—someone must be available to write contracts.",
    "They will write what the debtor dictates,": "The one who owes (alladhi 'alayhi al-haqq—the one upon whom the right/debt lies) should dictate (yumlil) the terms. This ensures they acknowledge the debt accurately and cannot later claim misrepresentation.",
    "bearing Allah in mind and not defrauding the debt.": "While dictating, the debtor must have taqwa of Allah and not reduce (yabkhas) anything from the debt. They must state the full amount and terms honestly.",
    "If the debtor is incompetent, weak, or unable to dictate,": "If the debtor is safeeh (incompetent, immature, foolish), da'eef (weak, incapable), or unable to dictate...",
    "let their guardian dictate for them with justice.": "...their waliyy (guardian, representative) should dictate bil-'adl (with justice, fairly). The guardian protects the debtor's interests while maintaining honesty.",
    "Call upon two of your men to witness.": "Obtain shaheedayn (two witnesses) from your men (rijalikum). Two adult, sane Muslim men should witness the contract.",
    "If two men cannot be found, then one man and two women of your choice will witness—": "If two men are unavailable, then one man and two women whom you are pleased with (tardawna—you accept, trust) can serve as witnesses.",
    "so if one of the women forgets the other may remind her.": "The reason for two women: \"an tadilla ihdahuma fatuthakkira ihdahuma al-ukhra\"—so that if one errs or forgets, the other can remind her. This addresses the historical context where women typically had less experience in financial and legal matters. The second woman serves as support and backup. This is specific to financial testimony and does not apply to all forms of witness testimony in Islamic law.",
    "The witnesses must not refuse when they are summoned.": "Witnesses should not decline (la ya'ba) when called. Being a witness is a communal responsibility. If someone needs your testimony, you should provide it.",
    "You must not be against writing ˹contracts˺ for a fixed period—whether the sum is small or great.": "Do not be reluctant (la tas'amu—don't be weary, don't find it burdensome) to write it, whether the debt is sagheeran (small) or kabeeran (large), until its ajal (term, due date). Every debt deserves proper documentation.",
    "This is more just ˹for you˺ in the sight of Allah, and more convenient to establish evidence and remove doubts.": "Writing contracts is aqsat (more just) with Allah, aqwam (more upright, stronger) for establishing shahada (testimony/evidence), and adna (closer, more likely) to avoid doubt (la tartabu—not to doubt or dispute). Documentation prevents conflicts.",
    "However, if you conduct an immediate transaction among yourselves,": "If it is tijaratan hadiratan (immediate, present trade/transaction) that you exchange hand-to-hand...",
    "then there is no need for you to record it,": "...there is no sin (junah) in not writing it. Cash transactions completed immediately don't require written contracts.",
    "but call upon witnesses when a deal is finalized.": "However, even in immediate sales, call witnesses when you conduct tabaya'tum (trade, buy and sell). Witnesses protect against later disputes about what was sold or for how much.",
    "Let no harm come to the scribe or witnesses.": "Do not harm (yudarra) the katib (scribe) or shaheed (witness). Don't pressure them to write falsely, delay them unnecessarily, or cause them any harm. Their service should not result in trouble for them.",
    "If you do, then you have gravely exceeded ˹your limits˺.": "If you harm them, it is fusooq (grave disobedience, transgression) in you. This is serious sin.",
    "Be mindful of Allah,": "Maintain taqwa in all your business dealings. Consciousness of Allah prevents fraud, oppression, and dishonesty.",
    "for Allah ˹is the One Who˺ teaches you.": "Allah is the one who teaches (yu'allimukum) you—through revelation, experience, and guidance. These detailed laws are divine teaching for your benefit.",
    "And Allah has ˹perfect˺ knowledge of all things.": "Allah is 'Aleem (All-Knowing) of everything—your intentions, your contracts, your honesty or deception. This knowledge should motivate integrity."
  },
  283: {
    "If you are on a journey and a scribe cannot be found,": "When traveling (safar) and unable to find a katib (scribe) to document the transaction...",
    "then a security can be taken.": "...then rihan maqboodah (collateral that is possessed, held in hand) can serve as security for the debt. Physical possession of collateral protects the creditor's interest when documentation is impossible.",
    "If you trust one another,": "If there is mutual trust between the parties (amina ba'dukum ba'dan—some of you trust others)...",
    "then ˹there is no need for a security, but˺ the debtor should honour this trust ˹by repaying the debt˺—": "...then the one who is trusted (alladhi utumina—the one given trust, the debtor) should fulfill his amanah (trust) by repaying the debt honestly.",
    "and let them fear Allah, their Lord.": "The debtor should maintain taqwa of Allah. Consciousness of Allah prevents betraying trust or defaulting on debts.",
    "And do not conceal the testimony,": "Witnesses must not conceal (taktumu) the shahada (testimony). If called to testify about a debt or transaction, tell the truth. Hiding testimony is a serious sin.",
    "for whoever conceals it, their hearts are indeed sinful.": "Whoever conceals testimony, qalbuhu athim (his heart is sinful). The sin affects the core of the person—their heart becomes corrupted. Testimony is a sacred trust.",
    "And Allah ˹fully˺ knows what you do.": "Allah knows all actions—what you conceal, what you reveal, what you testify, what you hide. This awareness should prevent dishonesty."
  },
  284: {
    "To Allah ˹alone˺ belongs whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth.": "Everything in existence belongs to Allah. He is the Owner, Controller, and Sustainer of all. This ownership gives Him absolute right to legislate and judge.",
    "Whether you reveal what is in your hearts or conceal it,": "Whether you manifest (tubdu) what is in your souls/hearts or hide (tukhfuhu) it, Allah knows. Thoughts, intentions, desires—nothing is hidden from Him.",
    "Allah will call you to account for it.": "Allah will bring you to hisab (accounting) for it. Even internal thoughts and intentions are subject to accountability. When this verse was first revealed, the companions were deeply concerned, fearing accountability for passing thoughts. Later verses clarified that involuntary thoughts (waswas) are forgiven.",
    "He forgives whoever He wills, and punishes whoever He wills.": "Allah exercises His prerogative: He forgives (yaghfir) whomever He wills and punishes (yu'adhdhibu) whomever He wills. His judgment is perfect, based on His complete knowledge and perfect justice.",
    "And Allah is Most Capable of everything.": "Allah is Qadeer (fully capable, all-powerful) over everything. This includes the power to know all hearts, judge all actions, forgive all sins, and execute all punishments. Nothing is beyond His capability."
  },
  285: {
    "The Messenger ˹firmly˺ believes in what has been revealed to him from his Lord,": "Ar-Rasul (the Messenger, Prophet Muhammad, peace be upon him) has amana (believed with certainty) in what was revealed to him from his Lord. His faith is complete and unwavering. This establishes the Prophet as the model of faith.",
    "and so do the believers.": "Wal-mu'minoon (and the believers) share this same faith. True believers follow the Prophet's example in belief.",
    "They ˹all˺ believe in Allah,": "The first pillar of faith: belief in Allah—His existence, oneness, names, attributes, and exclusive right to worship.",
    "His angels,": "The second pillar: belief in the mala'ikah (angels)—Allah's noble servants created from light who execute His commands without disobedience.",
    "His Books,": "The third pillar: belief in all divine kutub (books/scriptures) revealed throughout history—Torah, Gospel, Psalms, Quran, and others.",
    "and His messengers.": "The fourth pillar: belief in all the rusul (messengers) sent by Allah to guide humanity—from Adam to Muhammad (peace be upon them all).",
    "˹They proclaim,˺ \"We make no distinction between any of His messengers.\"": "La nufarriqu bayna ahadin min rusulihi—we do not discriminate among His messengers. We believe in all of them equally, not accepting some while rejecting others. All were truthful messengers from Allah deserving respect and obedience in their times.",
    "And they say, \"We hear and obey.": "Sami'na wa ata'na—we hear and we obey. This is the attitude of true believers: immediate, willing obedience to Allah's commands. Contrast this with the Israelites who said \"we hear and disobey\" (verse 93).",
    "˹We seek˺ Your forgiveness, our Lord!": "Ghufranaka Rabbana—Your forgiveness, our Lord. Despite obedience, believers humbly seek Allah's forgiveness, recognizing their inevitable shortcomings.",
    "And to You ˹alone˺ is the final return.\"": "Wa ilayka al-maseer—and to You is the final return. Everyone's ultimate destination is back to Allah for judgment. This awareness shapes how believers live."
  },
  286: {
    "Allah does not require of any soul more than what it can afford.": "La yukallifu Allahu nafsan illa wus'aha—Allah does not burden any soul beyond its capacity. This is a fundamental principle of Islamic law: obligations match abilities. When this verse was revealed, it eased the companions' worry about the previous verse's mention of accountability for thoughts. Allah clarified He only holds accountable for what people can control.",
    "All good will be for its own benefit,": "Laha ma kasabat—for it (the soul) is what it earned of good. Every good deed benefits the doer themselves.",
    "and all evil will be to its own loss.": "Wa 'alayha ma iktasabat—and upon it is what it earned of evil. Every sin harms the sinner themselves. No one benefits from another's good or suffers from another's evil in the Hereafter.",
    "˹The believers pray,˺ \"Our Lord! Do not punish us if we forget or make a mistake.": "Rabbana la tu'akhidhna in naseena aw akhta'na—Our Lord, do not take us to account if we forget or err. This dua asks for forgiveness for unintentional mistakes and forgetfulness. The Prophet (peace be upon him) reported that when believers recite this, Allah says: \"I have done so.\" (Muslim)",
    "Our Lord! Do not place a burden on us like the one you placed on those before us.": "Rabbana wa la tahmil 'alayna isran kama hamaltahu 'ala allatheena min qablina—Our Lord, do not impose upon us a burden (isr) like You imposed on those before us. Previous nations had more difficult laws—for example, repentance for the Israelites sometimes required execution (calf-worshippers), or their impurities could only be cleaned by cutting the affected part. Muslims ask to be spared such difficult requirements. The Prophet reported Allah responded: \"I have done so.\" (Muslim)",
    "Our Lord! Do not burden us with what we cannot bear.": "Rabbana wa la tuhammilna ma la taqata lana bihi—Our Lord, do not load upon us what we have no ability to bear. This asks for relief from overwhelming trials, unbearable tests, or obligations beyond capacity. Allah answered: \"I have done so.\" (Muslim)",
    "Pardon us,": "Wa'fu 'anna—and pardon us, erase our sins completely. 'Afw means to obliterate, to remove all traces of wrong.",
    "forgive us,": "Waghfir lana—and forgive us. Maghfirah is covering and protection from the consequences of sins. Both pardon (erasing) and forgiveness (covering) are requested.",
    "and have mercy on us.": "Warhamna—and have mercy on us. Rahmah is comprehensive mercy that brings all good and removes all harm. This three-part request (pardon, forgive, show mercy) covers all aspects of divine grace.",
    "You are our ˹only˺ Guardian.": "Anta mawlana—You are our guardian, protector, supporter. Mawla indicates complete dependence on Allah for everything.",
    "So grant us victory over the disbelieving people.\"": "Fansurna 'ala al-qawm al-kafireen—so grant us victory over the disbelieving people. The final request is for nasr (victory, divine help) against those who reject faith. This victory includes both spiritual triumph over falsehood and physical protection from enemies. This verse, along with the preceding one, forms one of the most important supplications in Islam. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"Whoever recites the last two verses of Surah Al-Baqarah at night, they will suffice him.\" (Bukhari & Muslim)—meaning they protect from harm and fulfill spiritual needs."
  }
};